{"title_page": "Windows Server 2012", "text_new": "{{short description|server operating system by Microsoft released in 2012}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2017}}\n{{Good article}}\n{{Infobox OS version\n| version of             = [[Windows NT]]\n| name                   = \n| logo                   = Windows Server 2012 logo.svg\n| logo size              =\n| screenshot             = Start screen on Windows Server 2012.png\n| caption                = Windows Server 2012 [[Start screen (Windows)|Start Screen]]\n| developer              = Microsoft\n| family                 = [[Microsoft Windows]]\n| working state          = Current<!-- \"Current\", \"Discontinued\" (operating systems), or \"No longer supported\" (releases) -->\n| source_model = {{ubl\n  | [[Proprietary software|Closed-source]]\n  | [[Source-available software|Source-available]] (through [[Shared Source Initiative]])\n}}\n| first release date     = {{Start date and age|2012|8|1}}\n| first release url      = http://blogs.technet.com/b/windowsserver/archive/2012/08/01/windows-server-2012-released-to-manufacturing.aspx\n| GA date                = {{Start date and age|2012|9|4}}\n| GA url                 = http://blogs.technet.com/b/windowsserver/archive/2012/08/01/windows-server-2012-released-to-manufacturing.aspx\n| release version        = 6.2 (Build 9200)\n| release date           = {{Start date and age|2012|8|1}}\n| release url            = http://blogs.technet.com/b/windowsserver/archive/2012/08/01/windows-server-2012-released-to-manufacturing.aspx\n| preview version        =\n| preview date           =\n| preview url            =\n| marketing target       = Business\n| programmed in          = \n| language               = <!-- Supported human languages (English, French, Italian, Arabic, ...) -->\n| language count         = \n| language footnote      = \n| update model           = [[Windows Update]], [[Windows Server Update Services]], [[System Center Configuration Manager|SCCM]]\n| package manager        = <!-- dpkg, rpm, Windows installer, etc. -->\n| supported platforms    = [[x86-64]]\n| kernel type            = [[Hybrid kernel|Hybrid]] ([[Windows NT kernel]])\n| ui                     = [[Windows shell]] ([[Graphical user interface|GUI]])\n| license                = [[Commercial software|Commercial]] [[proprietary software]]\n| preceded by            = [[Windows Server 2008 R2]] (2009)\n| succeeded by           = [[Windows Server 2012 R2]] (2013)\n| website                = {{URL|http://www.microsoft.com/en-us/server-cloud/windows-server/default.aspx}}\n| support status         = {{Plainlist|\n* Start date: October 30, 2012<ref name=\"prod-lifecycle\">{{cite web|title=Microsoft Product Lifecycle|url=http://support.microsoft.com/lifecycle/search/default.aspx?sort=PN&alpha=Windows+Server+2012&gadate=0&msdate=0&esdate=0&medate=0&spdate=0&Filter=FilterNO|work=Microsoft Support|publisher=Microsoft|date=January 2012|accessdate=October 10, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130227071426/http://support.microsoft.com/lifecycle/search/default.aspx?sort=PN&alpha=Windows+Server+2012&gadate=0&msdate=0&esdate=0&medate=0&spdate=0&Filter=FilterNO|archive-date=February 27, 2013}}</ref>\n* Mainstream support ended on October 9, 2018<ref name=\"prod-lifecycle\"/>\n* Extended support until October 10, 2023<ref name=\"prod-lifecycle\"/>\n}}\n| other_articles =\n}}\n'''Windows Server 2012''', codenamed \"Windows Server 8\",<ref name=\"ZDNet1\">{{cite web | url=http://www.zdnet.com/blog/microsoft/windows-server-8-officially-dubbed-windows-server-2012/12475 | title=Windows Server \"8\" officially dubbed Windows Server 2012 | work=[[ZDNet]] | publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] | accessdate=April 17, 2012 | first=Mary Jo |last=Foley |date=April 17, 2012}}</ref> is the fifth release of [[Windows Server]]. It is the [[Server (computing)|server]] version of [[Windows 8]] and succeeds [[Windows 7]]-based [[Windows Server 2008 R2]], released nearly three years earlier. Two pre-release versions, a [[Alpha version|developer preview]] and a [[beta version]], were released during development. The software was generally available to customers starting on September 4, 2012, by [[Microsoft]].<ref name=\"MSofficialRTM\">{{cite web |url=http://blogs.technet.com/b/windowsserver/archive/2012/08/01/windows-server-2012-released-to-manufacturing.aspx|title=Windows Server 2012 released to manufacturing! |work=Windows Server Blog |agency=[[Microsoft TechNet#Blogs|TechNet blogs]] |publisher=Microsoft |date=August 1, 2012 |last=Snover |first=Jeffrey |accessdate=January 29, 2013}}</ref>\n\nUnlike its predecessor, Windows Server 2012 has no support for [[Itanium]]-based computers,<ref name=\"no itanium\">{{cite web |url=http://www.zdnet.com/blog/microsoft/microsoft-pulls-the-plug-on-future-itanium-support/5796 |title=Microsoft pulls the plug on future Itanium support |last=Foley |first=Mary Jo |work=[[ZDNet]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |date=April 5, 2010 |accessdate=January 1, 2012}}</ref> and has four editions. Various features were added or improved over Windows Server 2008 R2 (with many placing an emphasis on [[cloud computing]]), such as an updated version of [[Hyper-V]], an [[IP address management]] role, a new version of [[Windows Task Manager]], and [[ReFS]], a new [[file system]]. Windows Server 2012 received generally good reviews in spite of having included the same controversial [[Metro (design language)|Metro]]-based user interface seen in Windows 8, which includes the \"Charms Bar\" for quick access to settings in the desktop environment.\n\n==History==\nWindows Server 2012, codenamed \"Windows Server 8\",<ref name=\"ZDNet1\" /> is the fifth release of [[Windows Server]] family of operating systems developed concurrently with [[Windows 8]].<ref name=\"betawinsupersite\" /><ref name=\"WSVRBlog-RC\" /> It was not until April 17, 2012 that the company announced that the final product name would be \"Windows Server 2012\".<ref name=\"ZDNet1\" />\n\nMicrosoft introduced Windows Server 2012 and its [[alpha version|developer preview]] in the [[BUILD (Microsoft)|BUILD 2011]] conference on September 9, 2011.<ref name=\"serverandcloudblog\">{{cite web | url=http://blogs.technet.com/b/server-cloud/archive/2011/09/09/windows-server-8-an-introduction.aspx | title=Windows Server 8: An Introduction | publisher=Microsoft | work=Server & Cloud Blog |agency=[[Microsoft TechNet#Blogs|TechNet blogs]] | date=September 9, 2011 | accessdate=January 23, 2013 | first=Bill | last = Laing}}</ref> However, unlike Windows 8, the developer preview of Windows Server 2012 was only made available to [[MSDN]] subscribers.<ref>{{cite web|title=Download Windows Server 8 Developer Preview via MSDN|url=http://news.softpedia.com/news/Download-Windows-Server-8-Developer-Preview-via-MSDN-221760.shtml|work=[[Softpedia]]|publisher=SoftNews SRL|accessdate=January 25, 2013|date=September 14, 2011}}</ref> It included a [[graphical user interface]] (GUI) based on [[Metro (design language)|Metro design language]] and a new Server Manager, a graphical application used for server management.<ref name=\"win8serverdevpreviewzdnet\" /> On February 16, 2012, Microsoft released an update for developer preview build that extended its expiry date from April 8, 2012 to January 15, 2013.<ref>{{cite web|last=Arghire|first=Ionut|title=Windows 8 Developer Preview Expiration Date Gets Postponed|url=http://news.softpedia.com/news/Windows-8-Developer-Preview-Expiration-Date-Gets-Postponed-253670.shtml|work=[[Softpedia]]|publisher=SoftNews SRL|accessdate=July 15, 2013|date=February 18, 2012}}</ref>\n\nBefore Windows Server 2012 was finalized, two test [[software build|builds]] were made public. A public [[beta version]] of Windows Server 2012 was released along with the Windows 8 Consumer Preview on February 29, 2012.<ref name=\"betawinsupersite\">{{cite web | url=http://www.windowsitpro.com/article/windows8/download-information-windows-server-8-beta-windows-8-consumer-preview-142434 | title=Q: Where can I download and get more information on Windows Server \"8\" Beta and Windows 8 Consumer Preview? | work=[[Windows IT Pro]] | publisher=[[Penton Media]] | date=February 29, 2012 | accessdate=February 29, 2012 | last=Savill |first=John }}</ref> The [[release candidate]] of Windows Server 2012 was released on May 31, 2012, along with the Windows 8 Release Preview.<ref name=\"WSVRBlog-RC\">{{cite web|url=http://blogs.technet.com/b/windowsserver/archive/2012/04/24/windows-server-2012-release-candidate-timing.aspx |title=Windows Server 2012 Release Candidate Timing |work=Windows Server Blog |agency=[[Microsoft TechNet#Blogs|TechNet blogs]] |publisher=Microsoft |date=April 24, 2012 |accessdate=January 21, 2013 |first=Jeffrey |last=Snover}}</ref>\n\nThe product was [[Release to manufacturing|released to manufacturing]] on August 1, 2012 (along with [[Windows 8]]) and became [[general availability|generally available]] on September 4, that year.<ref name=\"MSofficialRTM\"/> However, not all [[#Editions|editions of Windows Server 2012]] were released at the same time. Windows Server 2012 Essentials was released to manufacturing on October 9, 2012<ref>{{cite web|last=Snover|first=Jeffrey|title=Windows Server 2012 Essentials released to manufacturing, available for evaluation today!|url=http://blogs.technet.com/b/windowsserver/archive/2012/10/09/windows-server-2012-essentials-released-to-manufacturing-available-for-evaluation-today.aspx |work=Windows Server Blog! |agency=[[Microsoft TechNet#Blogs|TechNet blogs]] |publisher=Microsoft |accessdate=January 25, 2013}}</ref> and was made generally available on November 1, 2012.<ref>{{cite web |title=Windows Server 2012 Essentials reaches general availability! |url=http://blogs.technet.com/b/windowsserver/archive/2012/11/05/windows-server-2012-essentials-reaches-general-availability.aspx |work=Windows Server Blog! |agency=[[Microsoft TechNet#Blogs|TechNet blogs]] |publisher=Microsoft |accessdate=January 25, 2013}}</ref> As of September 23, 2012, all students subscribed to [[DreamSpark]] program can download Windows Server 2012 Standard or Datacenter free of charge.<ref>{{cite web|title=Windows Server 2012|url=https://www.dreamspark.com/Product/Product.aspx?productid=42|work=[[Microsoft DreamSpark]]|publisher=Microsoft|accessdate=January 25, 2013}}</ref>\n\nWindows Server 2012 is based on [[Windows Server 2008 R2]] and [[Windows 8]] and requires [[x86-64]] CPUs (64-bit), while [[Windows Server 2008]] worked on the older [[IA-32]] (32-bit) architecture as well. Coupled with fundamental changes in the structure of the client backups and the shared folders, there is no clear method for migrating from the previous version to Windows Server 2012.\n\n==Features==\n{{see also|Features new to Windows 8}}\n\n===Installation options===\nUnlike its predecessor, Windows Server 2012 can switch between \"[[Server Core]]\" and \"Server with a [[Graphical user interface|GUI]]\" installation options without a full reinstallation. Server Core \u2013 an option with a command-line interface only \u2013 is now the recommended configuration. There is also a third installation option that allows some GUI elements such as [[Microsoft Management Console|MMC]] and Server Manager to run, but without the normal desktop, [[Shell (computing)|shell]] or default programs like [[File Explorer]].<ref name=\"win8serverdevpreviewzdnet\">{{cite web | url=http://www.zdnet.com/windows-8-server-developer-preview-3040093932/ | title=Windows 8 Server Developer Preview | work=[[ZDNet]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] | date=September 14, 2011 | accessdate=January 1, 2012 | last=Bisson |first=Simon}}</ref>\n\n===User interface===\nServer Manager has been redesigned with an emphasis on easing management of multiple servers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.neowin.net/news/windows-server-8-screenshot-leak-shows-new-ui |title=WIndows Server 8 Screenshot Leak Shows New UI |work=Neowin.net |publisher=Neowin LLC |date=September 9, 2011 |accessdate=January 21, 2013 |first=John |last=Callaham}}</ref> The operating system, like Windows 8, uses the Metro-based [[user interface]] unless installed in Server Core mode.<ref name=\"thenextweb\">{{cite web | url=https://thenextweb.com/microsoft/2011/09/09/leaked-windows-server-8-screenshot-shows-off-metro-infused-ui/ | title=Windows Server 8 Screenshot leaks | publisher=The Next Web | work=News | date=September 9, 2011 | accessdate=January 1, 2012 | last=Wilhelm |first=Alex}}</ref> [[Windows Store]] is available in this version of Windows but is not installed by default.<ref>{{cite web|title=Managing Privacy: Windows Store and Resulting Internet Communication|url=https://technet.microsoft.com/en-us/library/jj884083.aspx|work=[[Microsoft TechNet|TechNet]]|publisher=[[Microsoft]]|accessdate=January 30, 2014}}</ref> [[Windows PowerShell]] in this version has over 2300 commandlets, compared to around 200 in Windows Server 2008 R2.<ref name=\"winserver8previewunedited\">{{cite web | url=http://www.winsupersite.com/article/windowsserver8/windows-server-8-preview-unedited-complete-version-141146 | title=Windows Server \"8\" Preview (Unedited, Complete Version) | work=Paul Thurott's Supersite for Windows | publisher=[[Penton Media]]| date=November 2, 2011 | accessdate=January 1, 2012 | last=Thurott | first=Paul}}</ref>\n\n===Task Manager===\n{{main|Windows Task Manager}}<!--[[WP:Summary style]]-->\nWindows Server 2012 includes a new version of [[Windows Task Manager]] together with the old version.<ref name=\"techradaroldversion\">{{cite web | url=http://www.techradar.com/news/software/operating-systems/50-windows-8-tips-tricks-and-secrets-1028220/2#articleContent | title=Windows 8 tips: mastering the interface | publisher=Future Publishing | work=Techradar | date=October 25, 2012 | accessdate=January 22, 2013 | last=Williams |first=Mike |last2=Hanson |first2=Matt}}</ref> In the new version the tabs are hidden by default, showing applications only. In the new Processes tab, the processes are displayed in varying shades of yellow, with darker shades representing heavier resource use.<ref name=\"win8taskmanager\">{{cite web | url=http://blogs.msdn.com/b/b8/archive/2011/10/13/the-windows-8-task-manager.aspx | title=The Windows 8 Task Manager | publisher=Microsoft | work=Building Windows 8 |agency=[[MSDN#Blogs|MSDN blogs]] | date=October 13, 2011 | accessdate=January 31, 2013 |first=Ryan |last=Haveson | editor-last=Sinofsky |editor-first=Steven }}</ref> Information found in the older versions are now moved to the new Details tab. The Performance tab shows \"CPU\", \"Memory\", \"Disk\", \"Wi-Fi\" and \"Ethernet\" graphs. Unlike the Windows 8 version of Task Manager (which looks similar), the \"Disk\" activity graph is not enabled by default. The CPU tab no longer displays individual graphs for every logical processor on the system by default, although that remains an option. Additionally, it can display data for each [[non-uniform memory access]] (NUMA) node. When displaying data for each logical processor for machines with more than 64 logical processors, the CPU tab now displays simple utilization percentages on heat-mapping tiles.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://blogs.msdn.com/b/b8/archive/2011/10/27/using-task-manager-with-64-logical-processors.aspx | title=Using Task Manager with 64+ logical processors |work=Building Windows 8 |agency=[[MSDN#Blogs|MSDN blogs]] | accessdate=October 29, 2011}}</ref> The color used for these heat maps is blue, with darker shades again indicating heavier utilization. Hovering the cursor over any logical processor's data now shows the NUMA node of that processor and its ID, if applicable. Additionally, a new Startup tab has been added that lists startup applications,<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.itproportal.com/2011/10/24/how-get-most-out-new-windows-8-task-manager/ | title=How to Get the Most out of New Windows 8 Task Manager? | accessdate=October 29, 2011}}</ref> however this tab does not exist in Windows Server 2012.<ref>{{cite web |first=Aaron |last=Hu | url=http://social.technet.microsoft.com/Forums/en-US/winserver8gen/thread/ac155cdc-f0ea-444a-b9df-709a824b23a2 | title=How to disable start-up items in windows server 2012 |work=[[Microsoft TechNet#Forums|TechNet Forums]] |publisher=Microsoft |accessdate=October 14, 2012 |quote=The Startup tab is not present on Windows Server 2012. It is only on Windows 8.}}</ref> The new task manager recognizes when a [[Windows Store]] app has the \"Suspended\" status.\n\n===IP address management (IPAM)===\nWindows Server 2012 has an [[IP address management]] role for discovering, monitoring, auditing, and managing the [[IP address]] space used on a corporate network. The IPAM is used for the management and monitoring of [[Domain Name System]] (DNS) and [[Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol]] (DHCP) servers. Both [[IPv4]] and [[IPv6]] are fully supported.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://technet.microsoft.com/en-us/library/hh831353 |title=IP Address Management (IPAM) Overview |publisher=Microsoft |work=[[Microsoft TechNet#Library|TechNet Library]] |date=February 29, 2012 |accessdate=January 21, 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Active Directory===\nWindows Server 2012 has a number of changes to [[Active Directory]] from the version shipped with Windows Server 2008 R2. The Active Directory Domain Services installation wizard has been replaced by a new section in Server Manager, and a GUI has been added to the Active Directory Recycle Bin.<ref name=\"redmondmagAD\">{{cite web | url=http://redmondmag.com/articles/2012/07/01/whats-new-in-windows-server-2012-active-directory.aspx | title=Quick Guide: What's New in Windows Server 2012 Active Directory | publisher=1105 Redmond Media | work=Redmond magazine | date=July 3, 2012 | accessdate=January 21, 2013 | last=Shields |first=Greg}}</ref> Multiple password policies can be set in the same domain.<ref name=\"technetADpasswordpolicies\">{{cite web | url=http://blogs.technet.com/b/meamcs/archive/2012/05/29/creating-fine-grained-password-policies-through-gui-windows-server-2012-server-8-beta.aspx | title=Creating fine grained password policies through GUI Windows server (''sic'') 2012 \"Server 8 beta\" | publisher=Microsoft | work= Team blog of MCS @ Middle East and Africa |agency=[[Microsoft TechNet#Blogs|TechNet blogs]] | date=May 29, 2012 | accessdate=January 21, 2013 | last=Sherif Mahmoud |first=Tamer}}</ref> Active Directory in Windows Server 2012 is now aware of any changes resulting from virtualization, and virtualized domain controllers can be safely cloned. Upgrades of the domain functional level to Windows Server 2012 are simplified; it can be performed entirely in Server Manager. Active Directory Federation Services is no longer required to be downloaded when installed as a role, and claims which can be used by the Active Directory Federation Services have been introduced into the Kerberos token. Windows Powershell commands used by Active Directory Administrative Center can be viewed in a \"Powershell History Viewer\".<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.infoworld.com/d/microsoft-windows/windows-server-8-the-4-best-new-active-directory-features-177128 |title=Windows Server 8: The 4 best new Active Directory features |last=Bruzzese |first=J. Peter |work=[[InfoWorld]] |publisher=[[International Data Group|IDG]] |date=October 26, 2011 |accessdate=January 1, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://windowsitpro.com/windows-server-2012/what-s-new-windows-server-2012-active-directory |title=What's New in Windows Server 2012 Active Directory |date=September 14, 2011 |accessdate=July 16, 2013 |last=Deuby |first=Sean |work=[[Windows IT Pro]] |publisher=[[Penton Media]]}}</ref>\n\n===Hyper-V===\nWindows Server 2012, along with Windows 8, includes a new version of [[Hyper-V]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://channel9.msdn.com/events/BUILD/BUILD2011/SAC-973F | title=Day 2: Windows Server 8 |work=[[Channel 9 (MSDN)|Channel 9]] |publisher=Microsoft |accessdate=February 2, 2013 |date=September 14, 2011 |first=Max |last=Herrmann |first2=Bill |last2=Laing |first3=Manlio |last3=Vecchiet |first4=Mike |last4=Neil}}</ref> as presented at the Microsoft BUILD event.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://channel9.msdn.com/Events/Build/Build2011?sort=sequential&direction=desc&term=windows+server+8 |title=BUILD2011: Windows Server 8 |work=[[Channel 9 (MSDN)|Channel 9]] |publisher=Microsoft |accessdate=February 2, 2013 |date=September 13\u201316, 2011 |location=[[Anaheim, California]]}}</ref> Many new features have been added to Hyper-V, including network virtualization, multi-tenancy, storage resource pools, cross-premises connectivity, and cloud backup. Additionally, many of the former restrictions on resource consumption have been greatly lifted. Each virtual machine in this version of Hyper-V can access up to 64 virtual processors, up to 1 terabyte of memory, and up to 64 terabytes of virtual disk space per virtual hard disk (using a new .vhdx format).<ref name=\"officialhypervpage\">{{cite web | url=http://www.microsoft.com/en-us/server-cloud/windows-server/server-virtualization.aspx | title=Server Virtualization Features | publisher=Microsoft | accessdate=October 5, 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"winsupersite.com\">{{cite web |first=John |last=Savill | url=http://www.windowsitpro.com/article/windowsserver8/windows-server-8s-scalability-numbers-140931| title=Q: What are Windows Server 8's Scalability Numbers? |work=[[Windows IT Pro]] |publisher=[[Penton Media]] |date=October 28, 2011 |accessdate=November 5, 2011}}</ref> Up to 1024 virtual machines can be active per host, and up to 8000 can be active per failover cluster.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://channel9.msdn.com/Events/BUILD/BUILD2011/SAC-437T |title=Day 2: A deep dive into Hyper-V Networking |work=[[Channel 9 (MSDN)|Channel 9]] |publisher=Microsoft |accessdate=January 22, 2013 |date=September 14, 2011 |first=Pankaj |last=Garg |first2=See-Mong |last2=Tan}}</ref> [[Second-level address translation|SLAT]] is a required processor feature for Hyper-V on Windows 8, while for Windows Server 2012 it is only required for the supplementary [[RemoteFX]] role.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.windowsitpro.com/article/windowsserver8/windows-8-server-hyperv-support-slat-140925 | title=Q: Will Windows Server 8 require the processor to support SLAT? |date=October 21, 2011 | accessdate=November 5, 2011 | last=Savil |first=John |work=[[Windows IT Pro]] |publisher=[[Penton Media]]}}</ref>\n\n===ReFS===\n{{Main|ReFS}}\nResilient File System (ReFS),<ref name=\"technetReFS1\">{{cite web | url=http://blogs.technet.com/b/askpfeplat/archive/2013/01/02/windows-server-2012-does-refs-replace-ntfs-when-should-i-use-it.aspx | title=Windows Server 2012: Does ReFS replace NTFS? When should I use it? | work=Ask Premier Field Engineering (PFE) Platforms |agency=[[Microsoft TechNet#Blogs|TechNet blogs]] |publisher=Microsoft | date=January 1, 2013 | accessdate=January 20, 2013 | last=Lucas |first=Martin}}</ref> codenamed \"Protogon\",<ref name=\"zdnetrefsunveiled\"/> is a new [[file system]] in Windows Server 2012 initially intended for [[file server]]s that improves on [[NTFS]] in some respects. Major new features of ReFS include:<ref name=\"B8_ReFS\">{{cite web|url=http://blogs.msdn.com/b/b8/archive/2012/01/16/building-the-next-generation-file-system-for-windows-refs.aspx |title=Building the next generation file system for Windows: ReFS |work=Building Windows 8 |agency=[[MSDN#Blogs|MSDN blogs]] |publisher=Microsoft |last=Verma |first=Surendra |editor-first=Steven |editor-last=Sinofsky  |editor-link=Steven Sinofsky |date=January 16, 2012 |accessdate=January 20, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"zdnetrefs\">{{cite web | url=http://www.zdnet.com/microsoft-takes-wraps-off-new-windows-file-system-3040094832/ | title=Microsoft takes wraps off new Windows file system | work=[[ZDNet]] | publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] | date=January 17, 2012 | accessdate=January 20, 2013 | last=Meyer |first=David}}</ref>\n\n;Improved reliability for on-disk structures: ReFS uses [[B+ tree]]s<ref name=\"B8_ReFS\"/> for all on-disk structures including metadata and file data. Metadata and file data are organized into tables similar to a [[relational database]]. The file size, number of files in a [[folder (computing)|folder]], total volume size and number of folders in a volume are limited by 64-bit numbers; as a result ReFS supports a maximum file size of 16 [[exabyte]]s, a maximum of 18.4 \u00d7 10<sup>18</sup> folders and a maximum volume size of 1 [[yottabyte]] (with 64 KB [[Data cluster|clusters]]) which allows large scalability with no practical limits on file and folder size (hardware restrictions still apply). Free space is counted by a hierarchical allocator which includes three separate tables for large, medium, and small chunks. File names and file paths are each limited to a 32 KB [[Unicode]] text string.\n;Built-in resilience: ReFS employs an [[copy-on-write|allocation-on-write]] update strategy for metadata,<ref name=\"B8_ReFS\"/>  which allocates new chunks for every update transaction and uses large IO batches. All ReFS metadata has built-in 64-bit checksums which are stored independently. The file data can have an optional checksum in a separate \"integrity [[fork (filesystem)|stream]]\", in which case the file update strategy also implements allocation-on-write; this is controlled by a new \"integrity\" attribute applicable to both files and directories. If nevertheless file data or metadata becomes corrupt, the file can be deleted without taking the whole volume offline. As a result of built-in resiliency, administrators do not need to periodically run error-checking tools such as [[CHKDSK]] when using ReFS.\n;Compatibility with existing APIs and technologies: ReFS does not require new system APIs and most file system filters continue to work with ReFS volumes.<ref name=\"B8_ReFS\"/>  ReFS supports many existing Windows and NTFS features such as [[BitLocker]] encryption, [[Access Control Lists]], [[USN Journal]], change notifications,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/windows/desktop/aa365465(v=vs.85).aspx |title=ReadDirectoryChangesW function |work=[[MSDN#Library|MSDN Library]] |publisher=Microsoft |date=November 8, 2012 |accessdate=January 21, 2013}}</ref> [[NTFS symbolic link|symbolic links]], [[NTFS junction point|junction points]], [[Volume Mount Point|mount points]], [[NTFS reparse point|reparse points]], [[Shadow Copy|volume snapshots]], [[Master File Table|file IDs]], and [[NTFS#Opportunistic locks|oplock]]. ReFS seamlessly<ref name=\"B8_ReFS\" /> integrates with [[Storage Spaces]], a [[storage virtualization]] layer that allows data mirroring and striping, as well as sharing storage pools between machines.<ref name=\"B8_storage_spaces\">{{cite web |url=http://blogs.msdn.com/b/b8/archive/2012/01/05/virtualizing-storage-for-scale-resiliency-and-efficiency.aspx |title=Virtualizing storage for scale, resiliency, and efficiency |work=Building Windows 8 |agency=[[MSDN#Blogs|MSDN blogs]] |publisher=Microsoft |date=January 5, 2012 |accessdate=January 18, 2013 |first=Rajeev |last=Nagar |editor-first=Steven |editor-last=Sinofsky  |editor-link=Steven Sinofsky}}</ref> ReFS resiliency features enhance the mirroring feature provided by Storage Spaces and can detect whether any mirrored copies of files become corrupt using background [[data scrubbing]] process, which periodically reads all mirror copies and verifies their checksums then replaces bad copies with good ones.\n\nSome NTFS features are not supported in ReFS, including [[NTFS#Distributed Link Tracking (DLT)|object IDs]], [[8.3 filename|short names]], [[NTFS compression|file compression]], [[Encrypting File System|file level encryption (EFS)]], [[Transactional NTFS|user data transactions]], [[hard link]]s, [[extended attributes]], and [[disk quota]]s.<ref name=\"zdnetrefsunveiled\">{{cite web |url=http://www.zdnet.com/blog/microsoft/microsoft-goes-public-with-plans-for-its-new-windows-8-file-system/11666 |title=Microsoft goes public with plans for its new Windows 8 file system |work=[[ZDNet]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |date=January 16, 2012 |accessdate=January 21, 2013 |first=Mary Jo |last=Foley}}</ref><ref name=\"B8_ReFS\"/> [[Sparse file]]s are supported.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://blogs.technet.com/b/askpfeplat/archive/2013/01/02/windows-server-2012-does-refs-replace-ntfs-when-should-i-use-it.aspx |title=Windows Server 2012: Does ReFS replace NTFS? When should I use it? |date=January 2, 2013 |accessdate=March 31, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://social.technet.microsoft.com/Forums/en-US/winserver8gen/thread/54f061b9-da35-4c82-b0b0-8cb3dbfc34a4 |title=ReFS (Resilient File System) supports sparse files |accessdate=March 31, 2013}}</ref> Support for [[NTFS#Alternate data streams (ADS)|named streams]] is not implemented in Windows 8 and Windows Server 2012, though it was later added in Windows 8.1 and Windows Server 2012 R2.<ref name=\"TechNet_REFS\">{{cite web|url = https://technet.microsoft.com/en-us/library/hh831724.aspx|title = Resilient File System Overview|date = 29 February 2012|website = [[Microsoft TechNet#Library|TechNet Library]]|publisher = [[Microsoft]]|accessdate = 25 December 2013}}</ref> ReFS does not itself offer [[data deduplication]].<ref name=\"B8_ReFS\" /> Dynamic disks with mirrored or striped volumes are replaced with mirrored or striped storage pools provided by Storage Spaces. In Windows Server 2012, automated error-correction with integrity streams is only supported on mirrored spaces; automatic recovery on parity spaces was added in Windows 8.1 and Windows Server 2012 R2.<ref name=\"TechNet_REFS\"/> Booting from ReFS is not supported either.\n\n===IIS 8.0===\nWindows Server 2012 includes version 8.0 of [[Internet Information Services]] (IIS). The new version contains new features such as [[Server Name Indication|SNI]], CPU usage caps for particular websites,<ref name=\"IIS8-1\">{{cite web | url=http://redmondmag.com/Articles/2012/08/15/Microsoft-Touts-IIS-8-Improvements.aspx?Page=1 | title=Microsoft Touts IIS 8 Improvements | work=Redmond magazine |publisher=1105 Redmond Media | accessdate=August 17, 2012 | last=Mackie |first=Kurt}}</ref> centralized management of [[SSL certificate]]s, [[WebSocket]] support and improved support for NUMA, but few other substantial changes were made.<ref name=\"compweeklyIIS8-2\">{{cite web | url=http://www.computerweekly.com/photostory/2240162614/Windows-Server-2012-inside-Microsofts-Enterprise-Server-OS/4/Windows-Server-2-12 | title=Windows Server 2012: inside Microsoft's Enterprise Server OS | publisher=[[TechTarget]] | work=[[Computer Weekly]] | date=September 4, 2012 | accessdate=January 21, 2013 | last=Anderson |first=Tim}}</ref>\n\n===Remote Desktop Protocol 8.0===\n[[Remote Desktop Protocol]] has new functions such as Adaptive Graphics (progressive rendering and related techniques), automatic selection of TCP or UDP as transport protocol, [[multi touch]] support, DirectX 11 support for vGPU, [[USB redirection]] supported independently of vGPU support, etc.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.technet.com/b/windowsserver/archive/2012/05/09/windows-server-2012-remote-desktop-services-rds.aspx |title=Windows Server 2012 Remote Desktop Services (RDS) \u2013 Windows Server Blog \u2013 Site Home \u2013 TechNet Blogs |publisher=Blogs.technet.com |date= May 8, 2012|accessdate=2014-02-13}}</ref><ref name=\"tech80\" /> A \"connection quality\" button is displayed in the RDP client connection bar for RDP 8.0 connections; clicking on it provides further information about connection, including whether UDP is in use or not.<ref name=\"kb2592687\">{{cite web|url=http://support.microsoft.com/kb/2592687 |title=Remote Desktop Protocol (RDP) 8.0 update for Windows 7 and Windows Server 2008 R2 |publisher=Support.microsoft.com |date= |accessdate=2014-02-13}}</ref>\n\n===Scalability===\nWindows Server 2012 supports the following maximum hardware specifications.<ref name=\"winsupersite.com\"/><ref name=\"processormax\"/> Windows Server 2012 improves over its predecessor Windows Server 2008 R2:\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin:auto; text-align:center;\"\n|-\n!Specification\n!Windows Server 2012 !! Windows Server 2008 R2\n|-\n|[[CPU|Physical processors]]{{efn|name=\"CPU-2K8R2\"}}\n|64\n|64\n|-\n|[[Logical processor]]s<br />when [[Hyper-V]] is disabled\n|640\n|256\n|-\n|Logical processors<br />when Hyper-V is enabled\n|320{{efn|Each virtualized partition, including the host itself, can use up to 64 processors.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://blogs.technet.com/b/askcore/archive/2013/03/28/logical-processor-count-changes-after-enabling-hyper-v-role-on-windows-server-2012.aspx | title=Logical Processor count changes after enabling Hyper-V role on Windows Server 2012 | accessdate=April 1, 2013 | date=March 28, 2013}}</ref>}}\n|64\n|-\n|[[Random-access memory|Memory]]\n|{{nowrap|4 [[Terabyte|TB]]}}\n|{{nowrap|2 TB}}\n|-\n|Failover cluster nodes (in any single cluster)\n|64\n|16\n|}\n\n==System requirements==\n{| class=\"wikitable floatright\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|+ Minimum system requirements for Windows Server 2012<ref name=\"system requirements\">{{cite web |title=Installing Windows Server 2012 |url=https://technet.microsoft.com/library/jj134246#BKMK_sysreq |work=[[Microsoft TechNet#Library|TechNet Library]] |publisher=Microsoft |at=System requirements |accessdate=June 10, 2012}}</ref>\n|-\n! [[Central processing unit|Processor]]\n| 1.4&nbsp;GHz, [[x64]]\n|-\n! [[Random-access memory|Memory]]\n| 512 MB\n|-\n! Free [[disk space]]\n| 32 GB (more if there is at least 16 GB of RAM)\n|}\nWindows Server 2012 runs only on [[x64]] processors. Unlike its predecessor, Windows Server 2012 does not support [[Itanium]].<ref name=\"no itanium\" />\n\nUpgrades from Windows Server 2008 and Windows Server 2008 R2 are supported, although upgrades from prior releases are not.<ref name=\"system requirements\"/>\n{{Clear}}\n\n==Editions==\nWindows Server 2012 has four editions: Foundation, Essentials, Standard  and Datacenter.<ref name=\"editionszdnet\">{{cite web | url=http://www.zdnet.com/microsoft-goes-public-with-windows-server-2012-versions-licensing-7000000341/ | title=Microsoft goes public with Windows Server 2012 versions, licensing | work=[[ZDNet]] |publisher = [[CBS Interactive]] | date=July 5, 2012 | accessdate=July 5, 2012 | last=Foley |first=Mary Jo}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.microsoft.com/en-us/server-cloud/products/windows-server-2012-r2/Purchasing.aspx | title=Purchasing Windows Server 2012| publisher=Microsoft | accessdate=December 8, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"editionspdf\">{{cite web | url=http://download.microsoft.com/download/4/D/B/4DB352D1-C610-466A-9AAF-EEF4F4CFFF27/WS2012_Licensing-Pricing_FAQ.pdf | title=Windows Server 2012 Licensing and Pricing FAQ | publisher=Microsoft | accessdate=July 5, 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"editionslicensingpdf\">{{cite web | url=http://download.microsoft.com/download/0/4/B/04BD0EB1-42FE-488B-919F-3981EF9B2101/WS2012_Licensing-Pricing_Datasheet.pdf | title=Windows Server 2012 Licensing Data Sheet | publisher=Microsoft | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120722011620/http://download.microsoft.com/download/0/4/B/04BD0EB1-42FE-488B-919F-3981EF9B2101/WS2012_Licensing-Pricing_Datasheet.pdf |archive-date=July 22, 2012 }}</ref><ref name=\"processormax\">{{cite web | url=http://blogs.technet.com/b/matthts/archive/2012/10/14/windows-server-sockets-logical-processors-symmetric-multi-threading.aspx | title=Windows Server - Sockets, Logical Processors, Symmetric Multi Threading | work=Matthijs's blog |agency=[[Microsoft TechNet#Blogs|TechNet blogs]] |publisher=Microsoft | date=October 13, 2012 | accessdate=October 14, 2012 | last=Seldam |first=Matthijs ten}}</ref>\n\n{|class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"width:100%; text-align:center\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:20%\" | Specifications\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:20%\" | Foundation<ref>{{cite web|title=Introduction to Windows Server 2012 Foundation|url=https://technet.microsoft.com/en-us/library/jj679892.aspx|website=[[Microsoft TechNet|TechNet]]|publisher=[[Microsoft]]|accessdate=8 December 2015}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:20%\" | Essentials\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:20%\" | Standard\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:20%\" | Datacenter\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Distribution\n| OEM only || Retail, volume licensing, OEM || Retail, volume licensing, OEM || Volume licensing and OEM\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Licensing model\n| Per server || Per server || Per [[CPU]] pair{{efn|name=long}} + [[Client access license|CAL]]{{efn|name=\"CALs\"}} || Per CPU pair{{efn|name=long}} + CAL{{efn|name=\"CALs\"}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Processor chip limit<ref name=\"processormax\"/>\n| 1 || 2 || 64{{efn|name=\"proclicenseneeded\"}} || 64{{efn|name=\"proclicenseneeded\"}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Memory limit\n| 32 GB || 64 GB || 4 TB || 4 TB\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | User limit\n| {{partial|15}} || {{partial|25}} || {{Yes|Unlimited}} || {{Yes|Unlimited}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[File sharing]] limits\n| {{partial|1 standalone DFS root}} || {{partial|1 standalone DFS root}} || {{yes|Unlimited}} || {{yes|Unlimited}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[Network Policy Server|Network Policy]] and Access Services limits\n| {{Partial|50 RRAS connections and 10 IAS connections}} || {{partial|250 RRAS connections, 50 IAS connections, and 2 IAS Server Groups}}  || {{yes|Unlimited}} || {{yes|Unlimited}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[Remote Desktop Services]] limits\n| {{Partial|50 Remote Desktop Services connections}} || {{partial|Gateway only}}  || {{Yes|Unlimited}} || {{Yes|Unlimited}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Virtualization rights\n| {{N/A}} || {{Partial|Either in 1 VM or 1 physical server, but not both at once}} || {{partial|2 VMs{{efn|name=long}}}} || {{Yes|Unlimited}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[AD LDS|Active Directory Lightweight Directory Services]]\n| {{yes}} || {{yes}} || {{yes}} || {{yes}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[Active Directory Federation Services]]\n| {{yes}}<ref>{{cite web | url=https://technet.microsoft.com/en-us/library/jj679892.aspx | title=Introduction to Windows Server 2012 Foundation |work=[[Microsoft TechNet#Library|TechNet Library]] | publisher=Microsoft | accessdate=November 4, 2012}}</ref>  || {{yes}} || {{yes}} || {{yes}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[Active Directory Rights Management Services]]\n| {{yes}} || {{yes}} || {{yes}} || {{yes}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Application server role\n| {{yes}} || {{Partial}} || {{yes}} || {{yes}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol|DHCP]] role\n| {{yes}} || {{yes}} || {{yes}} || {{yes}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[DNS server]] role\n| {{yes}} || {{yes}} || {{yes}} || {{yes}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Fax server role\n| {{yes}} || {{yes}} || {{yes}} || {{yes}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Print and document services\n| {{yes}} || {{yes}} || {{yes}} || {{yes}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Server Manager\n| {{yes}} || {{yes}} || {{yes}} || {{yes}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | UDDI services\n| {{yes}} || {{yes}} || {{yes}} || {{yes}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Web services ([[Internet Information Services]])\n| {{yes}} || {{yes}} || {{yes}} || {{yes}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[Windows Deployment Services]]\n| {{yes}} || {{yes}} || {{yes}} || {{yes}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[Windows Powershell]]\n| {{yes}} || {{yes}} || {{yes}} || {{yes}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[Active Directory#Domain Services|Active Directory Domain Services]]\n| {{partial|Must be root of forest and domain}} || {{yes}} || {{yes}} || {{yes}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[Active Directory#Certificate Services|Active Directory Certificate Services]]\n| {{partial|Certificate Authorities only}} || {{partial|Certificate Authorities only}}  || {{yes}} || {{yes}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[Hyper-V]]\n| {{no}}  || {{partial|R2 onwards}} || {{yes}} || {{yes}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Server Core mode\n| {{no}}  || {{no}} || {{yes}} || {{yes}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[Windows Server Update Services]]\n| {{no}} || {{no}} || {{yes}} || {{yes}}\n|}\n\n==Reception==\nReviews of Windows Server 2012 have been generally positive.<ref name=\"zdnetreview\">{{cite web | url=http://www.zdnet.com/windows-server-2012-rtm-review-7000004213/ | title=Windows Server 2012: RTM review | work=[[ZDNet]] | publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] | date=September 13, 2012 | accessdate=January 19, 2013 | last=Bisson | first=Simon}}</ref><ref name=\"theregisterreview\">{{cite web | url=https://www.theregister.co.uk/2012/09/05/windows_server_2012_review/page2.html | title=Windows Server 2012: Smarter, stronger, frustrating | work=[[The Register]] | publisher=Situation Publishing | accessdate=January 19, 2013 |date=September 5, 2012 | last=Anderson |first=Tim}}</ref><ref name=\"serverwatchreview\">{{cite web | url=http://www.serverwatch.com/server-reviews/a-hands-on-look-at-windows-server-2012.html | title=Windows Server 2012 Review: The Bottom Line | work=ServerWatch | publisher=[[QuinStreet]] | date=October 3, 2012 | accessdate=January 19, 2013 | last=Ferrill |first=Paul}}</ref> Simon Bisson of ''[[ZDNet]]'' described it as \"ready for the datacenter, today,\"<ref name=\"zdnetreview\" /> while Tim Anderson of [[The Register]] said that \"The move towards greater modularity, stronger automation and improved virtualisation makes perfect sense in a world of public and private clouds\" but remarked that \"That said, the capability of Windows to deliver obscure and time-consuming errors is unchanged\" and concluded that \"Nevertheless, this is a strong upgrade overall.\"<ref name=\"theregisterreview\" />\n\n''InfoWorld'' noted that Server 2012's use of Windows 8's panned \"Metro\" user interface was countered by Microsoft's increasing emphasis on the Server Core mode, which had been \"fleshed out with new depth and ease-of-use features\" and increased use of the \"practically mandatory\" PowerShell.<ref name=\"infoworldreview\">{{cite web | url=http://www.infoworld.com/d/microsoft-windows/review-weighing-windows-server-2012-196431 | title=Review: Weighing Windows Server 2012 | work=[[InfoWorld]] |publisher=[[International Data Group|IDG]] | date=June 27, 2012 | accessdate=January 19, 2013 | last=Rist |first=Oliver}}</ref> However, Michael Otey of [[Windows IT Pro]] expressed dislike with the new Metro interface and the lack of ability to use the older desktop interface alone, saying that most users of Windows Server manage their servers using the graphical user interface rather than PowerShell.<ref name=\"winitprokillwindowsserver\">{{cite web | url=http://www.windowsitpro.com/article/windowsserver2012/microsoft-kill-windows-server-143747 | title=Is Microsoft Trying to Kill Windows Server? | work=[[Windows IT Pro]] |publisher=[[Penton Media]] | date=July 25, 2012 | accessdate=January 19, 2013 | last=Otey |first=Michael}}</ref> The Australian construction company Kennards found the OS stable.<ref name=\"zdnetdeploymentcase\">{{cite web | url=http://www.zdnet.com/au/kennards-adopts-windows-server-2012-for-virtualisation-7000004115/ | title=Kennards adopts Windows Server 2012 for virtualisation | publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] | work=[[ZDNet]] | date=September 12, 2012 | accessdate=January 21, 2013 | last=Lui |first=Spandas}}</ref>\n\nPaul Ferrill wrote that \"Windows Server 2012 Essentials provides all the pieces necessary to provide centralized file storage, client backups, and remote access,\"<ref name=\"serverwatchessentialsreview\">{{cite web | url=http://www.serverwatch.com/server-reviews/windows-server-2012-essentials-hands-on-look.html | title=A Hands-on Look at Windows Server 2012 Essentials | work=ServerWatch |publisher=[[QuinStreet]] | date=December 16, 2012 | accessdate=January 20, 2013 | last=Ferrill |first=Paul}}</ref> but Tim Anderson contended that \"Many businesses that are using [[Windows Small Business Server|SBS2011]] and earlier will want to stick with what they have\", citing the absence of [[Microsoft Exchange Server|Exchange]], the lack of ability to synchronize with [[Active Directory Federation Services]] and the 25-user limit,<ref name=\"pcproessentialsreview\">{{cite web | url=http://www.pcpro.co.uk/reviews/software/378850/windows-server-2012-essentials | title=Windows Server 2012 Essentials review | work=[[PC Pro]] |publisher=[[Dennis Publishing]] | date=December 21, 2012 | accessdate=January 20, 2013 | last=Anderson |first=Tim}}</ref> while [[Paul Thurott]] wrote \"you should choose Foundation only if you have at least some in-company IT staff and/or are comfortable outsourcing management to a Microsoft partner or solution provider\" and \"Essentials is, in my mind, ideal for any modern startup of just a few people.\"<ref name=\"winitproessentialsfoundation\">{{cite web | url=http://www.windowsitpro.com/article/windowsserver2012/windows-server-2012-foundation-essentials-144405 | title=Windows Server 2012: Foundation vs. Essentials | work=[[Windows IT Pro]] | publisher=[[Penton Media]] | date=October 2, 2012 | accessdate=January 20, 2013 | last=Thurott |first=Paul}}</ref>\n\n==Windows Server 2012 R2==\n{{Main|Windows Server 2012 R2}}\n\nThe second release of Windows Server 2012, called '''Windows Server 2012 R2''', was released along with [[Windows 8.1]] in October 2013<ref>{{cite web |last1=LeBlanc |first1=Brandon |title=Windows 8.1 now available! |url=https://blogs.windows.com/windowsexperience/2013/10/17/windows-8-1-now-available/ |website=Windows Experience Blog |publisher=Microsoft |date=17 October 2013}}</ref> after a pre-release version had been released on August 27, 2013, by [[Microsoft]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/archive/blogs/serverandtools/windows-server-2012-r2-reaches-the-release-to-manufacturing-rtm-milestone/ |title=Windows Server 2012 R2 Reaches the Release to Manufacturing (RTM) Milestone |website= Microsoft Docs | date=August 27, 2013 |accessdate=January 13, 2015}}</ref> A [[service pack]], formally designated Windows Server 2012 R2 Update, was released in April 2014.<ref name=\"R2_Update\">http://blogs.windows.com/bloggingwindows/2014/08/05/august-updates-for-windows-8-1-and-windows-server-2012-r2/</ref><ref name=\"Windows Server 2012 R2 Preview eBook\">{{cite web |url=http://hyperv.veeam.com/backup-resseler-whats-new-windows-server-2012-3071/ |title=eBook - What's new in Windows Server 2012 R2 Preview |last=Resseler |first=Mike | publisher=[[Veeam Software]] | date=August 27, 2013 |accessdate=September 3, 2013}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Microsoft Servers]]\n* [[Comparison of Microsoft Windows versions]]\n* [[History of Microsoft Windows]]\n* [[Comparison of operating systems]]\n* [[List of operating systems]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Notelist|notes=\n{{efn|name=\"CALs\"|For the Standard and Datacenter editions, each user or device accessing the software must have a [[client access license]] (CAL) assigned (either per-user or per-device), so there may be no more simultaneous users than the number of client-access licenses, except up to 2 simultaneous users purely to administer the server software, or for running virtualization or web workloads. Remote Desktop Services requires an additional CAL separate from the aforementioned CAL.}}\n\n{{efn|name=\"CPU-2K8R2\"|Applies to Windows Server 2008 R2 and 2012 Datacenter and Windows Server 2012 Standard only. Other editions support less.}}\n\n{{efn|name=\"proclicenseneeded\"|If the number of physical processors in a particular server is under 64, the limit is determined by the quantity of licenses assigned to that server. In that case, the number of physical processors cannot exceed twice the number of licenses assigned to the server.}}\n\n{{efn|name=long|Each license of Windows Server 2012 Standard or Datacenter allows ''up to two'' processor chips. Each license of Windows Server 2012 Standard allows up to two virtual instances of Windows Server 2012 Standard on that physical server. If more virtual instances of Windows Server 2012 Standard are needed, each additional license of Windows Server 2012 allows up to two more virtual instances of Windows Server 2012 Standard, even though the physical server itself may have sufficient licenses for its processor chip count. Because Windows Server 2012 Datacenter has no limit on the number of virtual instances per licensed server, only enough licenses for the physical server are needed for any number of virtual instances of Windows Server 2012 Datacenter. If the number of processor chips or virtual instances is an odd number, the number of licenses required is the same as the ''next even number''. For example, a single-processor-chip server would still require 1 license, the ''same'' as if the server were two-processor-chip and a five-processor-chip server would require 3 licenses, the ''same'' as if the server were six-processor-chip, and if 15 virtual instances of Windows Server 2012 Standard are needed on one server, 8 licenses of Windows Server 2012, which can cover up to 16 virtual instances, are needed (assuming, in this example, that the processor chip count does not exceed 16).}}\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book|title=Windows Server 2012 Inside Out|publisher=[[Microsoft Press]]|last=Stanek |first=William|year=2013|isbn=978-0-7356-6631-3}}\n* {{cite book|title=Windows Server 2012 R2 Inside Out Volume 1: Configuration, Storage, & Essentials|publisher=[[Microsoft Press]]|last=Stanek |first=William|year=2014|isbn=978-0-7356-8267-2}}\n* {{cite book|title=Windows Server 2012 R2 Inside Out Volume 2: Services, Security, & Infrastructure|publisher=[[Microsoft Press]]|last=Stanek |first=William|year=2014|isbn=978-0-7356-8255-9}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiversity|Windows Server}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.microsoft.com/en-us/server-cloud/windows-server/default.aspx}}\n* [https://technet.microsoft.com/en-us/library/hh801901.aspx Windows Server 2012 R2 and Windows Server 2012] on [[Microsoft TechNet|TechNet]]\n* [http://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/dn609939%28v=vs.85%29.aspx Windows Server 2012 R2] on [[MSDN]]\n* [http://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/dn609938%28v=vs.85%29.aspx Windows Server 2012] on [[MSDN]]\n* [http://www.technig.com/mcsa-lab-manual-articles-windows-server-2012-r2/ Tutorials and Lab Manual Articles of Windows Server 2012 R2] \n{{Microsoft Windows family}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n<!--- Categories --->\n[[Category:Windows Server]]\n[[Category:X86-64 operating systems]]\n[[Category:Windows 8]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|server operating system by Microsoft released in 2012}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2017}}\n{{Good article}}\n{{Infobox OS version\n| version of             = [[Windows NT]]\n| name                   = \n| logo                   = Windows Server 2012 logo.svg\n| logo size              =\n| screenshot             = Start screen on Windows Server 2012.png\n| caption                = Windows Server 2012 [[Start screen (Windows)|Start Screen]]\n| developer              = Microsoft\n| family                 = [[Microsoft Windows]]\n| working state          = Current<!-- \"Current\", \"Discontinued\" (operating systems), or \"No longer supported\" (releases) -->\n| source_model = {{ubl\n  | [[Proprietary software|Closed-source]]\n  | [[Source-available software|Source-available]] (through [[Shared Source Initiative]])\n}}\n| first release date     = {{Start date and age|2012|8|1}}\n| first release url      = http://blogs.technet.com/b/windowsserver/archive/2012/08/01/windows-server-2012-released-to-manufacturing.aspx\n| GA date                = {{Start date and age|2012|9|4}}\n| GA url                 = http://blogs.technet.com/b/windowsserver/archive/2012/08/01/windows-server-2012-released-to-manufacturing.aspx\n| release version        = 6.2 (Build 9200)\n| release date           = {{Start date and age|2012|8|1}}\n| release url            = http://blogs.technet.com/b/windowsserver/archive/2012/08/01/windows-server-2012-released-to-manufacturing.aspx\n| preview version        =\n| preview date           =\n| preview url            =\n| marketing target       = Business\n| programmed in          = \n| language               = <!-- Supported human languages (English, French, Italian, Arabic, ...) -->\n| language count         = \n| language footnote      = \n| update model           = [[Windows Update]], [[Windows Server Update Services]], [[System Center Configuration Manager|SCCM]]\n| package manager        = <!-- dpkg, rpm, Windows installer, etc. -->\n| supported platforms    = [[x86-64]]\n| kernel type            = [[Hybrid kernel|Hybrid]] ([[Windows NT kernel]])\n| ui                     = [[Windows shell]] ([[Graphical user interface|GUI]])\n| license                = [[Commercial software|Commercial]] [[proprietary software]]\n| preceded by            = [[Windows Server 2008 R2]] (2009)\n| succeeded by           = [[Windows Server 2012 R2]] (2013)\n| website                = {{URL|http://www.microsoft.com/en-us/server-cloud/windows-server/default.aspx}}\n| support status         = {{Plainlist|\n* Start date: October 30, 2012<ref name=\"prod-lifecycle\">{{cite web|title=Microsoft Product Lifecycle|url=http://support.microsoft.com/lifecycle/search/default.aspx?sort=PN&alpha=Windows+Server+2012&gadate=0&msdate=0&esdate=0&medate=0&spdate=0&Filter=FilterNO|work=Microsoft Support|publisher=Microsoft|date=January 2012|accessdate=October 10, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130227071426/http://support.microsoft.com/lifecycle/search/default.aspx?sort=PN&alpha=Windows+Server+2012&gadate=0&msdate=0&esdate=0&medate=0&spdate=0&Filter=FilterNO|archive-date=February 27, 2013}}</ref>\n* Mainstream support ended on October 9, 2018<ref name=\"prod-lifecycle\"/>\n* Extended support until October 10, 2023<ref name=\"prod-lifecycle\"/>\n}}\n| other_articles =\n}}\n'''Windows Server 2012''', codenamed \"Windows Server 8\",<ref name=\"ZDNet1\">{{cite web | url=http://www.zdnet.com/blog/microsoft/windows-server-8-officially-dubbed-windows-server-2012/12475 | title=Windows Server \"8\" officially dubbed Windows Server 2012 | work=[[ZDNet]] | publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] | accessdate=April 17, 2012 | first=Mary Jo |last=Foley |date=April 17, 2012}}</ref> is the fifth release of [[Windows Server]]. It is the [[Server (computing)|server]] version of [[Windows 8]] and succeeds [[Windows 7]]-based [[Windows Server 2008 R2]], released nearly three years earlier. Two pre-release versions, a [[Alpha version|developer preview]] and a [[beta version]], were released during development. The software was generally available to customers starting on September 4, 2012, by [[Microsoft]].<ref name=\"MSofficialRTM\">{{cite web |url=http://blogs.technet.com/b/windowsserver/archive/2012/08/01/windows-server-2012-released-to-manufacturing.aspx|title=Windows Server 2012 released to manufacturing! |work=Windows Server Blog |agency=[[Microsoft TechNet#Blogs|TechNet blogs]] |publisher=Microsoft |date=August 1, 2012 |last=Snover |first=Jeffrey |accessdate=January 29, 2013}}</ref>\n\nUnlike its predecessor, Windows Server 2012 has no support for [[Itanium]]-based computers,<ref name=\"no itanium\">{{cite web |url=http://www.zdnet.com/blog/microsoft/microsoft-pulls-the-plug-on-future-itanium-support/5796 |title=Microsoft pulls the plug on future Itanium support |last=Foley |first=Mary Jo |work=[[ZDNet]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |date=April 5, 2010 |accessdate=January 1, 2012}}</ref> and has four editions. Various features were added or improved over Windows Server 2008 R2 (with many placing an emphasis on [[cloud computing]]), such as an updated version of [[Hyper-V]], an [[IP address management]] role, a new version of [[Windows Task Manager]], and [[ReFS]], a new [[file system]]. Windows Server 2012 received generally good reviews in spite of having included the same controversial [[Metro (design language)|Metro]]-based user interface seen in Windows 8, which includes the \"Charms Bar\" for quick access to settings in the desktop environment.\n\n==History==\nWindows Server 2012, codenamed \"Windows Server 8\",<ref name=\"ZDNet1\" /> is the fifth release of [[Windows Server]] family of operating systems developed concurrently with [[Windows 8]].<ref name=\"betawinsupersite\" /><ref name=\"WSVRBlog-RC\" /> It was not until April 17, 2012 that the company announced that the final product name would be \"Windows Server 2012\".<ref name=\"ZDNet1\" />\n\nMicrosoft introduced Windows Server 2012 and its [[alpha version|developer preview]] in the [[BUILD (Microsoft)|BUILD 2011]] conference on September 9, 2011.<ref name=\"serverandcloudblog\">{{cite web | url=http://blogs.technet.com/b/server-cloud/archive/2011/09/09/windows-server-8-an-introduction.aspx | title=Windows Server 8: An Introduction | publisher=Microsoft | work=Server & Cloud Blog |agency=[[Microsoft TechNet#Blogs|TechNet blogs]] | date=September 9, 2011 | accessdate=January 23, 2013 | first=Bill | last = Laing}}</ref> However, unlike Windows 8, the developer preview of Windows Server 2012 was only made available to [[MSDN]] subscribers.<ref>{{cite web|title=Download Windows Server 8 Developer Preview via MSDN|url=http://news.softpedia.com/news/Download-Windows-Server-8-Developer-Preview-via-MSDN-221760.shtml|work=[[Softpedia]]|publisher=SoftNews SRL|accessdate=January 25, 2013|date=September 14, 2011}}</ref> It included a [[graphical user interface]] (GUI) based on [[Metro (design language)|Metro design language]] and a new Server Manager, a graphical application used for server management.<ref name=\"win8serverdevpreviewzdnet\" /> On February 16, 2012, Microsoft released an update for developer preview build that extended its expiry date from April 8, 2012 to January 15, 2013.<ref>{{cite web|last=Arghire|first=Ionut|title=Windows 8 Developer Preview Expiration Date Gets Postponed|url=http://news.softpedia.com/news/Windows-8-Developer-Preview-Expiration-Date-Gets-Postponed-253670.shtml|work=[[Softpedia]]|publisher=SoftNews SRL|accessdate=July 15, 2013|date=February 18, 2012}}</ref>\n\nBefore Windows Server 2012 was finalized, two test [[software build|builds]] were made public. A public [[beta version]] of Windows Server 2012 was released along with the Windows 8 Consumer Preview on February 29, 2012.<ref name=\"betawinsupersite\">{{cite web | url=http://www.windowsitpro.com/article/windows8/download-information-windows-server-8-beta-windows-8-consumer-preview-142434 | title=Q: Where can I download and get more information on Windows Server \"8\" Beta and Windows 8 Consumer Preview? | work=[[Windows IT Pro]] | publisher=[[Penton Media]] | date=February 29, 2012 | accessdate=February 29, 2012 | last=Savill |first=John }}</ref> The [[release candidate]] of Windows Server 2012 was released on May 31, 2012, along with the Windows 8 Release Preview.<ref name=\"WSVRBlog-RC\">{{cite web|url=http://blogs.technet.com/b/windowsserver/archive/2012/04/24/windows-server-2012-release-candidate-timing.aspx |title=Windows Server 2012 Release Candidate Timing |work=Windows Server Blog |agency=[[Microsoft TechNet#Blogs|TechNet blogs]] |publisher=Microsoft |date=April 24, 2012 |accessdate=January 21, 2013 |first=Jeffrey |last=Snover}}</ref>\n\nThe product was [[Release to manufacturing|released to manufacturing]] on August 1, 2012 (along with [[Windows 8]]) and became [[general availability|generally available]] on September 4, that year.<ref name=\"MSofficialRTM\"/> However, not all [[#Editions|editions of Windows Server 2012]] were released at the same time. Windows Server 2012 Essentials was released to manufacturing on October 9, 2012<ref>{{cite web|last=Snover|first=Jeffrey|title=Windows Server 2012 Essentials released to manufacturing, available for evaluation today!|url=http://blogs.technet.com/b/windowsserver/archive/2012/10/09/windows-server-2012-essentials-released-to-manufacturing-available-for-evaluation-today.aspx |work=Windows Server Blog! |agency=[[Microsoft TechNet#Blogs|TechNet blogs]] |publisher=Microsoft |accessdate=January 25, 2013}}</ref> and was made generally available on November 1, 2012.<ref>{{cite web |title=Windows Server 2012 Essentials reaches general availability! |url=http://blogs.technet.com/b/windowsserver/archive/2012/11/05/windows-server-2012-essentials-reaches-general-availability.aspx |work=Windows Server Blog! |agency=[[Microsoft TechNet#Blogs|TechNet blogs]] |publisher=Microsoft |accessdate=January 25, 2013}}</ref> As of September 23, 2012, all students subscribed to [[DreamSpark]] program can download Windows Server 2012 Standard or Datacenter free of charge.<ref>{{cite web|title=Windows Server 2012|url=https://www.dreamspark.com/Product/Product.aspx?productid=42|work=[[Microsoft DreamSpark]]|publisher=Microsoft|accessdate=January 25, 2013}}</ref>\n\nWindows Server 2012 is based on [[Windows Server 2008 R2]] and [[Windows 8]] and requires [[x86-64]] CPUs (64-bit), while [[Windows Server 2008]] worked on the older [[IA-32]] (32-bit) architecture as well. Coupled with fundamental changes in the structure of the client backups and the shared folders, there is no clear method for migrating from the previous version to Windows Server 2012.\n\n==Features==\n{{see also|Features new to Windows 8}}\n\n===Installation options===\nUnlike its predecessor, Windows Server 2012 can switch between \"[[Server Core]]\" and \"Server with a [[Graphical user interface|GUI]]\" installation options without a full reinstallation. Server Core \u2013 an option with a command-line interface only \u2013 is now the recommended configuration. There is also a third installation option that allows some GUI elements such as [[Microsoft Management Console|MMC]] and Server Manager to run, but without the normal desktop, [[Shell (computing)|shell]] or default programs like [[File Explorer]].<ref name=\"win8serverdevpreviewzdnet\">{{cite web | url=http://www.zdnet.com/windows-8-server-developer-preview-3040093932/ | title=Windows 8 Server Developer Preview | work=[[ZDNet]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] | date=September 14, 2011 | accessdate=January 1, 2012 | last=Bisson |first=Simon}}</ref>\n\n===User interface===\nServer Manager has been redesigned with an emphasis on easing management of multiple servers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.neowin.net/news/windows-server-8-screenshot-leak-shows-new-ui |title=WIndows Server 8 Screenshot Leak Shows New UI |work=Neowin.net |publisher=Neowin LLC |date=September 9, 2011 |accessdate=January 21, 2013 |first=John |last=Callaham}}</ref> The operating system, like Windows 8, uses the Metro-based [[user interface]] unless installed in Server Core mode.<ref name=\"thenextweb\">{{cite web | url=https://thenextweb.com/microsoft/2011/09/09/leaked-windows-server-8-screenshot-shows-off-metro-infused-ui/ | title=Windows Server 8 Screenshot leaks | publisher=The Next Web | work=News | date=September 9, 2011 | accessdate=January 1, 2012 | last=Wilhelm |first=Alex}}</ref> [[Windows Store]] is available in this version of Windows but is not installed by default.<ref>{{cite web|title=Managing Privacy: Windows Store and Resulting Internet Communication|url=https://technet.microsoft.com/en-us/library/jj884083.aspx|work=[[Microsoft TechNet|TechNet]]|publisher=[[Microsoft]]|accessdate=January 30, 2014}}</ref> [[Windows PowerShell]] in this version has over 2300 commandlets, compared to around 200 in Windows Server 2008 R2.<ref name=\"winserver8previewunedited\">{{cite web | url=http://www.winsupersite.com/article/windowsserver8/windows-server-8-preview-unedited-complete-version-141146 | title=Windows Server \"8\" Preview (Unedited, Complete Version) | work=Paul Thurott's Supersite for Windows | publisher=[[Penton Media]]| date=November 2, 2011 | accessdate=January 1, 2012 | last=Thurott | first=Paul}}</ref>\n\n===Task Manager===\n{{main|Windows Task Manager}}<!--[[WP:Summary style]]-->\nWindows Server 2012 includes a new version of [[Windows Task Manager]] together with the old version.<ref name=\"techradaroldversion\">{{cite web | url=http://www.techradar.com/news/software/operating-systems/50-windows-8-tips-tricks-and-secrets-1028220/2#articleContent | title=Windows 8 tips: mastering the interface | publisher=Future Publishing | work=Techradar | date=October 25, 2012 | accessdate=January 22, 2013 | last=Williams |first=Mike |last2=Hanson |first2=Matt}}</ref> In the new version the tabs are hidden by default, showing applications only. In the new Processes tab, the processes are displayed in varying shades of yellow, with darker shades representing heavier resource use.<ref name=\"win8taskmanager\">{{cite web | url=http://blogs.msdn.com/b/b8/archive/2011/10/13/the-windows-8-task-manager.aspx | title=The Windows 8 Task Manager | publisher=Microsoft | work=Building Windows 8 |agency=[[MSDN#Blogs|MSDN blogs]] | date=October 13, 2011 | accessdate=January 31, 2013 |first=Ryan |last=Haveson | editor-last=Sinofsky |editor-first=Steven }}</ref> Information found in the older versions are now moved to the new Details tab. The Performance tab shows \"CPU\", \"Memory\", \"Disk\", \"Wi-Fi\" and \"Ethernet\" graphs. Unlike the Windows 8 version of Task Manager (which looks similar), the \"Disk\" activity graph is not enabled by default. The CPU tab no longer displays individual graphs for every logical processor on the system by default, although that remains an option. Additionally, it can display data for each [[non-uniform memory access]] (NUMA) node. When displaying data for each logical processor for machines with more than 64 logical processors, the CPU tab now displays simple utilization percentages on heat-mapping tiles.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://blogs.msdn.com/b/b8/archive/2011/10/27/using-task-manager-with-64-logical-processors.aspx | title=Using Task Manager with 64+ logical processors |work=Building Windows 8 |agency=[[MSDN#Blogs|MSDN blogs]] | accessdate=October 29, 2011}}</ref> The color used for these heat maps is blue, with darker shades again indicating heavier utilization. Hovering the cursor over any logical processor's data now shows the NUMA node of that processor and its ID, if applicable. Additionally, a new Startup tab has been added that lists startup applications,<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.itproportal.com/2011/10/24/how-get-most-out-new-windows-8-task-manager/ | title=How to Get the Most out of New Windows 8 Task Manager? | accessdate=October 29, 2011}}</ref> however this tab does not exist in Windows Server 2012.<ref>{{cite web |first=Aaron |last=Hu | url=http://social.technet.microsoft.com/Forums/en-US/winserver8gen/thread/ac155cdc-f0ea-444a-b9df-709a824b23a2 | title=How to disable start-up items in windows server 2012 |work=[[Microsoft TechNet#Forums|TechNet Forums]] |publisher=Microsoft |accessdate=October 14, 2012 |quote=The Startup tab is not present on Windows Server 2012. It is only on Windows 8.}}</ref> The new task manager recognizes when a [[Windows Store]] app has the \"Suspended\" status.\n\n===IP address management (IPAM)===\nWindows Server 2012 has an [[IP address management]] role for discovering, monitoring, auditing, and managing the [[IP address]] space used on a corporate network. The IPAM is used for the management and monitoring of [[Domain Name System]] (DNS) and [[Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol]] (DHCP) servers. Both [[IPv4]] and [[IPv6]] are fully supported.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://technet.microsoft.com/en-us/library/hh831353 |title=IP Address Management (IPAM) Overview |publisher=Microsoft |work=[[Microsoft TechNet#Library|TechNet Library]] |date=February 29, 2012 |accessdate=January 21, 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Active Directory===\nWindows Server 2012 has a number of changes to [[Active Directory]] from the version shipped with Windows Server 2008 R2. The Active Directory Domain Services installation wizard has been replaced by a new section in Server Manager, and a GUI has been added to the Active Directory Recycle Bin.<ref name=\"redmondmagAD\">{{cite web | url=http://redmondmag.com/articles/2012/07/01/whats-new-in-windows-server-2012-active-directory.aspx | title=Quick Guide: What's New in Windows Server 2012 Active Directory | publisher=1105 Redmond Media | work=Redmond magazine | date=July 3, 2012 | accessdate=January 21, 2013 | last=Shields |first=Greg}}</ref> Multiple password policies can be set in the same domain.<ref name=\"technetADpasswordpolicies\">{{cite web | url=http://blogs.technet.com/b/meamcs/archive/2012/05/29/creating-fine-grained-password-policies-through-gui-windows-server-2012-server-8-beta.aspx | title=Creating fine grained password policies through GUI Windows server (''sic'') 2012 \"Server 8 beta\" | publisher=Microsoft | work= Team blog of MCS @ Middle East and Africa |agency=[[Microsoft TechNet#Blogs|TechNet blogs]] | date=May 29, 2012 | accessdate=January 21, 2013 | last=Sherif Mahmoud |first=Tamer}}</ref> Active Directory in Windows Server 2012 is now aware of any changes resulting from virtualization, and virtualized domain controllers can be safely cloned. Upgrades of the domain functional level to Windows Server 2012 are simplified; it can be performed entirely in Server Manager. Active Directory Federation Services is no longer required to be downloaded when installed as a role, and claims which can be used by the Active Directory Federation Services have been introduced into the Kerberos token. Windows Powershell commands used by Active Directory Administrative Center can be viewed in a \"Powershell History Viewer\".<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.infoworld.com/d/microsoft-windows/windows-server-8-the-4-best-new-active-directory-features-177128 |title=Windows Server 8: The 4 best new Active Directory features |last=Bruzzese |first=J. Peter |work=[[InfoWorld]] |publisher=[[International Data Group|IDG]] |date=October 26, 2011 |accessdate=January 1, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://windowsitpro.com/windows-server-2012/what-s-new-windows-server-2012-active-directory |title=What's New in Windows Server 2012 Active Directory |date=September 14, 2011 |accessdate=July 16, 2013 |last=Deuby |first=Sean |work=[[Windows IT Pro]] |publisher=[[Penton Media]]}}</ref>\n\n===Hyper-V===\nWindows Server 2012, along with Windows 8, includes a new version of [[Hyper-V]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://channel9.msdn.com/events/BUILD/BUILD2011/SAC-973F | title=Day 2: Windows Server 8 |work=[[Channel 9 (MSDN)|Channel 9]] |publisher=Microsoft |accessdate=February 2, 2013 |date=September 14, 2011 |first=Max |last=Herrmann |first2=Bill |last2=Laing |first3=Manlio |last3=Vecchiet |first4=Mike |last4=Neil}}</ref> as presented at the Microsoft BUILD event.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://channel9.msdn.com/Events/Build/Build2011?sort=sequential&direction=desc&term=windows+server+8 |title=BUILD2011: Windows Server 8 |work=[[Channel 9 (MSDN)|Channel 9]] |publisher=Microsoft |accessdate=February 2, 2013 |date=September 13\u201316, 2011 |location=[[Anaheim, California]]}}</ref> Many new features have been added to Hyper-V, including network virtualization, multi-tenancy, storage resource pools, cross-premises connectivity, and cloud backup. Additionally, many of the former restrictions on resource consumption have been greatly lifted. Each virtual machine in this version of Hyper-V can access up to 64 virtual processors, up to 1 terabyte of memory, and up to 64 terabytes of virtual disk space per virtual hard disk (using a new .vhdx format).<ref name=\"officialhypervpage\">{{cite web | url=http://www.microsoft.com/en-us/server-cloud/windows-server/server-virtualization.aspx | title=Server Virtualization Features | publisher=Microsoft | accessdate=October 5, 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"winsupersite.com\">{{cite web |first=John |last=Savill | url=http://www.windowsitpro.com/article/windowsserver8/windows-server-8s-scalability-numbers-140931| title=Q: What are Windows Server 8's Scalability Numbers? |work=[[Windows IT Pro]] |publisher=[[Penton Media]] |date=October 28, 2011 |accessdate=November 5, 2011}}</ref> Up to 1024 virtual machines can be active per host, and up to 8000 can be active per failover cluster.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://channel9.msdn.com/Events/BUILD/BUILD2011/SAC-437T |title=Day 2: A deep dive into Hyper-V Networking |work=[[Channel 9 (MSDN)|Channel 9]] |publisher=Microsoft |accessdate=January 22, 2013 |date=September 14, 2011 |first=Pankaj |last=Garg |first2=See-Mong |last2=Tan}}</ref> [[Second-level address translation|SLAT]] is a required processor feature for Hyper-V on Windows 8, while for Windows Server 2012 it is only required for the supplementary [[RemoteFX]] role.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.windowsitpro.com/article/windowsserver8/windows-8-server-hyperv-support-slat-140925 | title=Q: Will Windows Server 8 require the processor to support SLAT? |date=October 21, 2011 | accessdate=November 5, 2011 | last=Savil |first=John |work=[[Windows IT Pro]] |publisher=[[Penton Media]]}}</ref>\n\n===ReFS===\n{{Main|ReFS}}\nResilient File System (ReFS),<ref name=\"technetReFS1\">{{cite web | url=http://blogs.technet.com/b/askpfeplat/archive/2013/01/02/windows-server-2012-does-refs-replace-ntfs-when-should-i-use-it.aspx | title=Windows Server 2012: Does ReFS replace NTFS? When should I use it? | work=Ask Premier Field Engineering (PFE) Platforms |agency=[[Microsoft TechNet#Blogs|TechNet blogs]] |publisher=Microsoft | date=January 1, 2013 | accessdate=January 20, 2013 | last=Lucas |first=Martin}}</ref> codenamed \"Protogon\",<ref name=\"zdnetrefsunveiled\"/> is a new [[file system]] in Windows Server 2012 initially intended for [[file server]]s that improves on [[NTFS]] in some respects. Major new features of ReFS include:<ref name=\"B8_ReFS\">{{cite web|url=http://blogs.msdn.com/b/b8/archive/2012/01/16/building-the-next-generation-file-system-for-windows-refs.aspx |title=Building the next generation file system for Windows: ReFS |work=Building Windows 8 |agency=[[MSDN#Blogs|MSDN blogs]] |publisher=Microsoft |last=Verma |first=Surendra |editor-first=Steven |editor-last=Sinofsky  |editor-link=Steven Sinofsky |date=January 16, 2012 |accessdate=January 20, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"zdnetrefs\">{{cite web | url=http://www.zdnet.com/microsoft-takes-wraps-off-new-windows-file-system-3040094832/ | title=Microsoft takes wraps off new Windows file system | work=[[ZDNet]] | publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] | date=January 17, 2012 | accessdate=January 20, 2013 | last=Meyer |first=David}}</ref>\n\n;Improved reliability for on-disk structures: ReFS uses [[B+ tree]]s<ref name=\"B8_ReFS\"/> for all on-disk structures including metadata and file data. Metadata and file data are organized into tables similar to a [[relational database]]. The file size, number of files in a [[folder (computing)|folder]], total volume size and number of folders in a volume are limited by 64-bit numbers; as a result ReFS supports a maximum file size of 16 [[exabyte]]s, a maximum of 18.4 \u00d7 10<sup>18</sup> folders and a maximum volume size of 1 [[yottabyte]] (with 64 KB [[Data cluster|clusters]]) which allows large scalability with no practical limits on file and folder size (hardware restrictions still apply). Free space is counted by a hierarchical allocator which includes three separate tables for large, medium, and small chunks. File names and file paths are each limited to a 32 KB [[Unicode]] text string.\n;Built-in resilience: ReFS employs an [[copy-on-write|allocation-on-write]] update strategy for metadata,<ref name=\"B8_ReFS\"/>  which allocates new chunks for every update transaction and uses large IO batches. All ReFS metadata has built-in 64-bit checksums which are stored independently. The file data can have an optional checksum in a separate \"integrity [[fork (filesystem)|stream]]\", in which case the file update strategy also implements allocation-on-write; this is controlled by a new \"integrity\" attribute applicable to both files and directories. If nevertheless file data or metadata becomes corrupt, the file can be deleted without taking the whole volume offline. As a result of built-in resiliency, administrators do not need to periodically run error-checking tools such as [[CHKDSK]] when using ReFS.\n;Compatibility with existing APIs and technologies: ReFS does not require new system APIs and most file system filters continue to work with ReFS volumes.<ref name=\"B8_ReFS\"/>  ReFS supports many existing Windows and NTFS features such as [[BitLocker]] encryption, [[Access Control Lists]], [[USN Journal]], change notifications,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/windows/desktop/aa365465(v=vs.85).aspx |title=ReadDirectoryChangesW function |work=[[MSDN#Library|MSDN Library]] |publisher=Microsoft |date=November 8, 2012 |accessdate=January 21, 2013}}</ref> [[NTFS symbolic link|symbolic links]], [[NTFS junction point|junction points]], [[Volume Mount Point|mount points]], [[NTFS reparse point|reparse points]], [[Shadow Copy|volume snapshots]], [[Master File Table|file IDs]], and [[NTFS#Opportunistic locks|oplock]]. ReFS seamlessly<ref name=\"B8_ReFS\" /> integrates with [[Storage Spaces]], a [[storage virtualization]] layer that allows data mirroring and striping, as well as sharing storage pools between machines.<ref name=\"B8_storage_spaces\">{{cite web |url=http://blogs.msdn.com/b/b8/archive/2012/01/05/virtualizing-storage-for-scale-resiliency-and-efficiency.aspx |title=Virtualizing storage for scale, resiliency, and efficiency |work=Building Windows 8 |agency=[[MSDN#Blogs|MSDN blogs]] |publisher=Microsoft |date=January 5, 2012 |accessdate=January 18, 2013 |first=Rajeev |last=Nagar |editor-first=Steven |editor-last=Sinofsky  |editor-link=Steven Sinofsky}}</ref> ReFS resiliency features enhance the mirroring feature provided by Storage Spaces and can detect whether any mirrored copies of files become corrupt using background [[data scrubbing]] process, which periodically reads all mirror copies and verifies their checksums then replaces bad copies with good ones.\n\nSome NTFS features are not supported in ReFS, including [[NTFS#Distributed Link Tracking (DLT)|object IDs]], [[8.3 filename|short names]], [[NTFS compression|file compression]], [[Encrypting File System|file level encryption (EFS)]], [[Transactional NTFS|user data transactions]], [[hard link]]s, [[extended attributes]], and [[disk quota]]s.<ref name=\"zdnetrefsunveiled\">{{cite web |url=http://www.zdnet.com/blog/microsoft/microsoft-goes-public-with-plans-for-its-new-windows-8-file-system/11666 |title=Microsoft goes public with plans for its new Windows 8 file system |work=[[ZDNet]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |date=January 16, 2012 |accessdate=January 21, 2013 |first=Mary Jo |last=Foley}}</ref><ref name=\"B8_ReFS\"/> [[Sparse file]]s are supported.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://blogs.technet.com/b/askpfeplat/archive/2013/01/02/windows-server-2012-does-refs-replace-ntfs-when-should-i-use-it.aspx |title=Windows Server 2012: Does ReFS replace NTFS? When should I use it? |date=January 2, 2013 |accessdate=March 31, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://social.technet.microsoft.com/Forums/en-US/winserver8gen/thread/54f061b9-da35-4c82-b0b0-8cb3dbfc34a4 |title=ReFS (Resilient File System) supports sparse files |accessdate=March 31, 2013}}</ref> Support for [[NTFS#Alternate data streams (ADS)|named streams]] is not implemented in Windows 8 and Windows Server 2012, though it was later added in Windows 8.1 and Windows Server 2012 R2.<ref name=\"TechNet_REFS\">{{cite web|url = https://technet.microsoft.com/en-us/library/hh831724.aspx|title = Resilient File System Overview|date = 29 February 2012|website = [[Microsoft TechNet#Library|TechNet Library]]|publisher = [[Microsoft]]|accessdate = 25 December 2013}}</ref> ReFS does not itself offer [[data deduplication]].<ref name=\"B8_ReFS\" /> Dynamic disks with mirrored or striped volumes are replaced with mirrored or striped storage pools provided by Storage Spaces. In Windows Server 2012, automated error-correction with integrity streams is only supported on mirrored spaces; automatic recovery on parity spaces was added in Windows 8.1 and Windows Server 2012 R2.<ref name=\"TechNet_REFS\"/> Booting from ReFS is not supported either.\n\n===IIS 8.0===\nWindows Server 2012 includes version 8.0 of [[Internet Information Services]] (IIS). The new version contains new features such as [[Server Name Indication|SNI]], CPU usage caps for particular websites,<ref name=\"IIS8-1\">{{cite web | url=http://redmondmag.com/Articles/2012/08/15/Microsoft-Touts-IIS-8-Improvements.aspx?Page=1 | title=Microsoft Touts IIS 8 Improvements | work=Redmond magazine |publisher=1105 Redmond Media | accessdate=August 17, 2012 | last=Mackie |first=Kurt}}</ref> centralized management of [[SSL certificate]]s, [[WebSocket]] support and improved support for NUMA, but few other substantial changes were made.<ref name=\"compweeklyIIS8-2\">{{cite web | url=http://www.computerweekly.com/photostory/2240162614/Windows-Server-2012-inside-Microsofts-Enterprise-Server-OS/4/Windows-Server-2-12 | title=Windows Server 2012: inside Microsoft's Enterprise Server OS | publisher=[[TechTarget]] | work=[[Computer Weekly]] | date=September 4, 2012 | accessdate=January 21, 2013 | last=Anderson |first=Tim}}</ref>\n\n===Remote Desktop Protocol 8.0===\n[[Remote Desktop Protocol]] has new functions such as Adaptive Graphics (progressive rendering and related techniques), automatic selection of TCP or UDP as transport protocol, [[multi touch]] support, DirectX 11 support for vGPU, [[USB redirection]] supported independently of vGPU support, etc.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.technet.com/b/windowsserver/archive/2012/05/09/windows-server-2012-remote-desktop-services-rds.aspx |title=Windows Server 2012 Remote Desktop Services (RDS) \u2013 Windows Server Blog \u2013 Site Home \u2013 TechNet Blogs |publisher=Blogs.technet.com |date= May 8, 2012|accessdate=2014-02-13}}</ref><ref name=\"tech80\" /> A \"connection quality\" button is displayed in the RDP client connection bar for RDP 8.0 connections; clicking on it provides further information about connection, including whether UDP is in use or not.<ref name=\"kb2592687\">{{cite web|url=http://support.microsoft.com/kb/2592687 |title=Remote Desktop Protocol (RDP) 8.0 update for Windows 7 and Windows Server 2008 R2 |publisher=Support.microsoft.com |date= |accessdate=2014-02-13}}</ref>\n\n===Scalability===\nWindows Server 2012 supports the following maximum hardware specifications.<ref name=\"winsupersite.com\"/><ref name=\"processormax\"/> Windows Server 2012 improves over its predecessor Windows Server 2008 R2:\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin:auto; text-align:center;\"\n|-\n!Specification\n!Windows Server 2012 !! Windows Server 2008 R2\n|-\n|[[CPU|Physical processors]]{{efn|name=\"CPU-2K8R2\"}}\n|64\n|64\n|-\n|[[Logical processor]]s<br />when [[Hyper-V]] is disabled\n|640\n|256\n|-\n|Logical processors<br />when Hyper-V is enabled\n|320{{efn|Each virtualized partition, including the host itself, can use up to 64 processors.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://blogs.technet.com/b/askcore/archive/2013/03/28/logical-processor-count-changes-after-enabling-hyper-v-role-on-windows-server-2012.aspx | title=Logical Processor count changes after enabling Hyper-V role on Windows Server 2012 | accessdate=April 1, 2013 | date=March 28, 2013}}</ref>}}\n|64\n|-\n|[[Random-access memory|Memory]]\n|{{nowrap|4 [[Terabyte|TB]]}}\n|{{nowrap|2 TB}}\n|-\n|Failover cluster nodes (in any single cluster)\n|64\n|16\n|}\n\n==System requirements==\n{| class=\"wikitable floatright\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|+ Minimum system requirements for Windows Server 2012<ref name=\"system requirements\">{{cite web |title=Installing Windows Server 2012 |url=https://technet.microsoft.com/library/jj134246#BKMK_sysreq |work=[[Microsoft TechNet#Library|TechNet Library]] |publisher=Microsoft |at=System requirements |accessdate=June 10, 2012}}</ref>\n|-\n! [[Central processing unit|Processor]]\n| 1.4&nbsp;GHz, [[x64]]\n|-\n! [[Random-access memory|Memory]]\n| 512 MB\n|-\n! Free [[disk space]]\n| 32 GB (more if there is at least 16 GB of RAM)\n|}\nWindows Server 2012 runs only on [[x64]] processors. Unlike its predecessor, Windows Server 2012 does not support [[Itanium]].<ref name=\"no itanium\" />\n\nUpgrades from Windows Server 2008 and Windows Server 2008 R2 are supported, although upgrades from prior releases are not.<ref name=\"system requirements\"/>\n{{Clear}}\n\n==Editions==\nWindows Server 2012 has four editions: Foundation, Essentials, Standard  and Datacenter.<ref name=\"editionszdnet\">{{cite web | url=http://www.zdnet.com/microsoft-goes-public-with-windows-server-2012-versions-licensing-7000000341/ | title=Microsoft goes public with Windows Server 2012 versions, licensing | work=[[ZDNet]] |publisher = [[CBS Interactive]] | date=July 5, 2012 | accessdate=July 5, 2012 | last=Foley |first=Mary Jo}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.microsoft.com/en-us/server-cloud/products/windows-server-2012-r2/Purchasing.aspx | title=Purchasing Windows Server 2012| publisher=Microsoft | accessdate=December 8, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"editionspdf\">{{cite web | url=http://download.microsoft.com/download/4/D/B/4DB352D1-C610-466A-9AAF-EEF4F4CFFF27/WS2012_Licensing-Pricing_FAQ.pdf | title=Windows Server 2012 Licensing and Pricing FAQ | publisher=Microsoft | accessdate=July 5, 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"editionslicensingpdf\">{{cite web | url=http://download.microsoft.com/download/0/4/B/04BD0EB1-42FE-488B-919F-3981EF9B2101/WS2012_Licensing-Pricing_Datasheet.pdf | title=Windows Server 2012 Licensing Data Sheet | publisher=Microsoft | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120722011620/http://download.microsoft.com/download/0/4/B/04BD0EB1-42FE-488B-919F-3981EF9B2101/WS2012_Licensing-Pricing_Datasheet.pdf |archive-date=July 22, 2012 }}</ref><ref name=\"processormax\">{{cite web | url=http://blogs.technet.com/b/matthts/archive/2012/10/14/windows-server-sockets-logical-processors-symmetric-multi-threading.aspx | title=Windows Server - Sockets, Logical Processors, Symmetric Multi Threading | work=Matthijs's blog |agency=[[Microsoft TechNet#Blogs|TechNet blogs]] |publisher=Microsoft | date=October 13, 2012 | accessdate=October 14, 2012 | last=Seldam |first=Matthijs ten}}</ref>\n\n{|class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"width:100%; text-align:center\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:20%\" | Specifications\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:20%\" | Foundation<ref>{{cite web|title=Introduction to Windows Server 2012 Foundation|url=https://technet.microsoft.com/en-us/library/jj679892.aspx|website=[[Microsoft TechNet|TechNet]]|publisher=[[Microsoft]]|accessdate=8 December 2015}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:20%\" | Essentials\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:20%\" | Standard\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:20%\" | Datacenter\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Distribution\n| OEM only || Retail, volume licensing, OEM || Retail, volume licensing, OEM || Volume licensing and OEM\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Licensing model\n| Per server || Per server || Per [[CPU]] pair{{efn|name=long}} + [[Client access license|CAL]]{{efn|name=\"CALs\"}} || Per CPU pair{{efn|name=long}} + CAL{{efn|name=\"CALs\"}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Processor chip limit<ref name=\"processormax\"/>\n| 1 || 2 || 64{{efn|name=\"proclicenseneeded\"}} || 64{{efn|name=\"proclicenseneeded\"}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Memory limit\n| 32 GB || 64 GB || 4 TB || 4 TB\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | User limit\n| {{partial|15}} || {{partial|25}} || {{Yes|Unlimited}} || {{Yes|Unlimited}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[File sharing]] limits\n| {{partial|1 standalone DFS root}} || {{partial|1 standalone DFS root}} || {{yes|Unlimited}} || {{yes|Unlimited}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[Network Policy Server|Network Policy]] and Access Services limits\n| {{Partial|50 RRAS connections and 10 IAS connections}} || {{partial|250 RRAS connections, 50 IAS connections, and 2 IAS Server Groups}}  || {{yes|Unlimited}} || {{yes|Unlimited}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[Remote Desktop Services]] limits\n| {{Partial|50 Remote Desktop Services connections}} || {{partial|Gateway only}}  || {{Yes|Unlimited}} || {{Yes|Unlimited}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Virtualization rights\n| {{N/A}} || {{Partial|Either in 1 VM or 1 physical server, but not both at once}} || {{partial|2 VMs{{efn|name=long}}}} || {{Yes|Unlimited}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[AD LDS|Active Directory Lightweight Directory Services]]\n| {{yes}} || {{yes}} || {{yes}} || {{yes}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[Active Directory Federation Services]]\n| {{yes}}<ref>{{cite web | url=https://technet.microsoft.com/en-us/library/jj679892.aspx | title=Introduction to Windows Server 2012 Foundation |work=[[Microsoft TechNet#Library|TechNet Library]] | publisher=Microsoft | accessdate=November 4, 2012}}</ref>  || {{yes}} || {{yes}} || {{yes}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[Active Directory Rights Management Services]]\n| {{yes}} || {{yes}} || {{yes}} || {{yes}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Application server role\n| {{yes}} || {{Partial}} || {{yes}} || {{yes}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol|DHCP]] role\n| {{yes}} || {{yes}} || {{yes}} || {{yes}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[DNS server]] role\n| {{yes}} || {{yes}} || {{yes}} || {{yes}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Fax server role\n| {{yes}} || {{yes}} || {{yes}} || {{yes}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Print and document services\n| {{yes}} || {{yes}} || {{yes}} || {{yes}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Server Manager\n| {{yes}} || {{yes}} || {{yes}} || {{yes}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | UDDI services\n| {{yes}} || {{yes}} || {{yes}} || {{yes}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Web services ([[Internet Information Services]])\n| {{yes}} || {{yes}} || {{yes}} || {{yes}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[Windows Deployment Services]]\n| {{yes}} || {{yes}} || {{yes}} || {{yes}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[Windows Powershell]]\n| {{yes}} || {{yes}} || {{yes}} || {{yes}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[Active Directory#Domain Services|Active Directory Domain Services]]\n| {{partial|Must be root of forest and domain}} || {{yes}} || {{yes}} || {{yes}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[Active Directory#Certificate Services|Active Directory Certificate Services]]\n| {{partial|Certificate Authorities only}} || {{partial|Certificate Authorities only}}  || {{yes}} || {{yes}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[Hyper-V]]\n| {{no}}  || {{partial|R2 onwards}} || {{yes}} || {{yes}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Server Core mode\n| {{no}}  || {{no}} || {{yes}} || {{yes}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[Windows Server Update Services]]\n| {{no}} || {{no}} || {{yes}} || {{yes}}\n|}\n\n==Reception==\nReviews of Windows Server 2012 have been generally positive.<ref name=\"zdnetreview\">{{cite web | url=http://www.zdnet.com/windows-server-2012-rtm-review-7000004213/ | title=Windows Server 2012: RTM review | work=[[ZDNet]] | publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] | date=September 13, 2012 | accessdate=January 19, 2013 | last=Bisson | first=Simon}}</ref><ref name=\"theregisterreview\">{{cite web | url=https://www.theregister.co.uk/2012/09/05/windows_server_2012_review/page2.html | title=Windows Server 2012: Smarter, stronger, frustrating | work=[[The Register]] | publisher=Situation Publishing | accessdate=January 19, 2013 |date=September 5, 2012 | last=Anderson |first=Tim}}</ref><ref name=\"serverwatchreview\">{{cite web | url=http://www.serverwatch.com/server-reviews/a-hands-on-look-at-windows-server-2012.html | title=Windows Server 2012 Review: The Bottom Line | work=ServerWatch | publisher=[[QuinStreet]] | date=October 3, 2012 | accessdate=January 19, 2013 | last=Ferrill |first=Paul}}</ref> Simon Bisson of ''[[ZDNet]]'' described it as \"ready for the datacenter, today,\"<ref name=\"zdnetreview\" /> while Tim Anderson of [[The Register]] said that \"The move towards greater modularity, stronger automation and improved virtualisation makes perfect sense in a world of public and private clouds\" but remarked that \"That said, the capability of Windows to deliver obscure and time-consuming errors is unchanged\" and concluded that \"Nevertheless, this is a strong upgrade overall.\"<ref name=\"theregisterreview\" />\n\n''InfoWorld'' noted that Server 2012's use of Windows 8's panned \"Metro\" user interface was countered by Microsoft's increasing emphasis on the Server Core mode, which had been \"fleshed out with new depth and ease-of-use features\" and increased use of the \"practically mandatory\" PowerShell.<ref name=\"infoworldreview\">{{cite web | url=http://www.infoworld.com/d/microsoft-windows/review-weighing-windows-server-2012-196431 | title=Review: Weighing Windows Server 2012 | work=[[InfoWorld]] |publisher=[[International Data Group|IDG]] | date=June 27, 2012 | accessdate=January 19, 2013 | last=Rist |first=Oliver}}</ref> However, Michael Otey of [[Windows IT Pro]] expressed dislike with the new Metro interface and the lack of ability to use the older desktop interface alone, saying that most users of Windows Server manage their servers using the graphical user interface rather than PowerShell.<ref name=\"winitprokillwindowsserver\">{{cite web | url=http://www.windowsitpro.com/article/windowsserver2012/microsoft-kill-windows-server-143747 | title=Is Microsoft Trying to Kill Windows Server? | work=[[Windows IT Pro]] |publisher=[[Penton Media]] | date=July 25, 2012 | accessdate=January 19, 2013 | last=Otey |first=Michael}}</ref> The Australian construction company Kennards found the OS stable.<ref name=\"zdnetdeploymentcase\">{{cite web | url=http://www.zdnet.com/au/kennards-adopts-windows-server-2012-for-virtualisation-7000004115/ | title=Kennards adopts Windows Server 2012 for virtualisation | publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] | work=[[ZDNet]] | date=September 12, 2012 | accessdate=January 21, 2013 | last=Lui |first=Spandas}}</ref>\n\nPaul Ferrill wrote that \"Windows Server 2012 Essentials provides all the pieces necessary to provide centralized file storage, client backups, and remote access,\"<ref name=\"serverwatchessentialsreview\">{{cite web | url=http://www.serverwatch.com/server-reviews/windows-server-2012-essentials-hands-on-look.html | title=A Hands-on Look at Windows Server 2012 Essentials | work=ServerWatch |publisher=[[QuinStreet]] | date=December 16, 2012 | accessdate=January 20, 2013 | last=Ferrill |first=Paul}}</ref> but Tim Anderson contended that \"Many businesses that are using [[Windows Small Business Server|SBS2011]] and earlier will want to stick with what they have\", citing the absence of [[Microsoft Exchange Server|Exchange]], the lack of ability to synchronize with [[Active Directory Federation Services]] and the 25-user limit,<ref name=\"pcproessentialsreview\">{{cite web | url=http://www.pcpro.co.uk/reviews/software/378850/windows-server-2012-essentials | title=Windows Server 2012 Essentials review | work=[[PC Pro]] |publisher=[[Dennis Publishing]] | date=December 21, 2012 | accessdate=January 20, 2013 | last=Anderson |first=Tim}}</ref> while [[Paul Thurott]] wrote \"you should choose Foundation only if you have at least some in-company IT staff and/or are comfortable outsourcing management to a Microsoft partner or solution provider\" and \"Essentials is, in my mind, ideal for any modern startup of just a few people.\"<ref name=\"winitproessentialsfoundation\">{{cite web | url=http://www.windowsitpro.com/article/windowsserver2012/windows-server-2012-foundation-essentials-144405 | title=Windows Server 2012: Foundation vs. Essentials | work=[[Windows IT Pro]] | publisher=[[Penton Media]] | date=October 2, 2012 | accessdate=January 20, 2013 | last=Thurott |first=Paul}}</ref>\n\n==Windows Server 2012 R2==\n{{Main|Windows Server 2012 R2}}\n\nThe second release of Windows Server 2012, called '''Windows Server 2012 R2''', was released along with [[Windows 8.1]] in October 2013<ref>{{cite web |last1=LeBlanc |first1=Brandon |title=Windows 8.1 now available! |url=https://blogs.windows.com/windowsexperience/2013/10/17/windows-8-1-now-available/ |website=Windows Experience Blog |publisher=Microsoft |date=17 October 2013}}</ref> after a pre-release version had been released on August 27, 2013, by [[Microsoft]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/archive/blogs/serverandtools/windows-server-2012-r2-reaches-the-release-to-manufacturing-rtm-milestone/ |title=Windows Server 2012 R2 Reaches the Release to Manufacturing (RTM) Milestone |website= Microsoft Docs | date=August 27, 2013 |accessdate=January 13, 2015}}</ref> A [[service pack]], formally designated Windows Server 2012 R2 Update, was released in April 2014.<ref name=\"R2_Update\">http://blogs.windows.com/bloggingwindows/2014/08/05/august-updates-for-windows-8-1-and-windows-server-2012-r2/</ref><ref name=\"Windows Server 2012 R2 Preview eBook\">{{cite web |url=http://hyperv.veeam.com/backup-resseler-whats-new-windows-server-2012-3071/ |title=eBook - What's new in Windows Server 2012 R2 Preview |last=Resseler |first=Mike | publisher=[[Veeam Software]] | date=August 27, 2013 |accessdate=September 3, 2013}}</ref> It is the first server operating system released by Microsoft to exclusively support 64-bit processors.\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Microsoft Servers]]\n* [[Comparison of Microsoft Windows versions]]\n* [[History of Microsoft Windows]]\n* [[Comparison of operating systems]]\n* [[List of operating systems]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Notelist|notes=\n{{efn|name=\"CALs\"|For the Standard and Datacenter editions, each user or device accessing the software must have a [[client access license]] (CAL) assigned (either per-user or per-device), so there may be no more simultaneous users than the number of client-access licenses, except up to 2 simultaneous users purely to administer the server software, or for running virtualization or web workloads. Remote Desktop Services requires an additional CAL separate from the aforementioned CAL.}}\n\n{{efn|name=\"CPU-2K8R2\"|Applies to Windows Server 2008 R2 and 2012 Datacenter and Windows Server 2012 Standard only. Other editions support less.}}\n\n{{efn|name=\"proclicenseneeded\"|If the number of physical processors in a particular server is under 64, the limit is determined by the quantity of licenses assigned to that server. In that case, the number of physical processors cannot exceed twice the number of licenses assigned to the server.}}\n\n{{efn|name=long|Each license of Windows Server 2012 Standard or Datacenter allows ''up to two'' processor chips. Each license of Windows Server 2012 Standard allows up to two virtual instances of Windows Server 2012 Standard on that physical server. If more virtual instances of Windows Server 2012 Standard are needed, each additional license of Windows Server 2012 allows up to two more virtual instances of Windows Server 2012 Standard, even though the physical server itself may have sufficient licenses for its processor chip count. Because Windows Server 2012 Datacenter has no limit on the number of virtual instances per licensed server, only enough licenses for the physical server are needed for any number of virtual instances of Windows Server 2012 Datacenter. If the number of processor chips or virtual instances is an odd number, the number of licenses required is the same as the ''next even number''. For example, a single-processor-chip server would still require 1 license, the ''same'' as if the server were two-processor-chip and a five-processor-chip server would require 3 licenses, the ''same'' as if the server were six-processor-chip, and if 15 virtual instances of Windows Server 2012 Standard are needed on one server, 8 licenses of Windows Server 2012, which can cover up to 16 virtual instances, are needed (assuming, in this example, that the processor chip count does not exceed 16).}}\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book|title=Windows Server 2012 Inside Out|publisher=[[Microsoft Press]]|last=Stanek |first=William|year=2013|isbn=978-0-7356-6631-3}}\n* {{cite book|title=Windows Server 2012 R2 Inside Out Volume 1: Configuration, Storage, & Essentials|publisher=[[Microsoft Press]]|last=Stanek |first=William|year=2014|isbn=978-0-7356-8267-2}}\n* {{cite book|title=Windows Server 2012 R2 Inside Out Volume 2: Services, Security, & Infrastructure|publisher=[[Microsoft Press]]|last=Stanek |first=William|year=2014|isbn=978-0-7356-8255-9}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiversity|Windows Server}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.microsoft.com/en-us/server-cloud/windows-server/default.aspx}}\n* [https://technet.microsoft.com/en-us/library/hh801901.aspx Windows Server 2012 R2 and Windows Server 2012] on [[Microsoft TechNet|TechNet]]\n* [http://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/dn609939%28v=vs.85%29.aspx Windows Server 2012 R2] on [[MSDN]]\n* [http://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/dn609938%28v=vs.85%29.aspx Windows Server 2012] on [[MSDN]]\n* [http://www.technig.com/mcsa-lab-manual-articles-windows-server-2012-r2/ Tutorials and Lab Manual Articles of Windows Server 2012 R2] \n{{Microsoft Windows family}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n<!--- Categories --->\n[[Category:Windows Server]]\n[[Category:X86-64 operating systems]]\n[[Category:Windows 8]]\n", "name_user": "Sek-2", "label": "safe", "comment": "remove entirely", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Windows_Server_2012"}
{"title_page": "Franco-Albertans", "text_new": "{{More footnotes|date=May 2011}}\n{{Infobox ethnic group\n|group       = Franco-Albertans\n|native_name = {{small|''Franco-Albertains''}}\n|flag        = [[File:Flag_of_the_Franco_Albertains.svg|200px|border]]<br /> [[Franco-Albertan flag]]\n|image       = \n|caption     = \n|population     = 79,840<ref>{{cite web |title=Census 2016, focus on geography series - Alberta - Official language minority community |url=https://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2016/as-sa/fogs-spg/Facts-PR-Eng.cfm?TOPIC=5&LANG=Eng&GK=PR&GC=48 |accessdate=17 October 2018}}</ref>\n|popplace    = [[Alberta]]\n|langs       = [[Canadian French]]{{\u00b7}}[[Canadian English]]\n|rels        = Mainly [[Roman Catholicism|Roman Catholic]]\n|related     = [[French Canadians]] [[M\u00e9tis in Alberta|M\u00e9tis]] [[Acadians]] [[French people|French]]\n}}\n'''Franco-Albertans''' ({{lang-fr|Franco-Albertains}}) are an extended community of [[French Canadians]] or [[French language|French]]-speaking people living in the [[Provinces and territories of Canada|Canadian province]] of [[Alberta]]. Alberta was predominantly French-speaking until the end of the 19th century, but has since been predominantly [[English speaking|English-speaking]]. In the capital of Alberta, [[Edmonton]], this population is mainly concentrated in the [[Bonnie Doon, Edmonton|Bonnie Doon]] area. In [[Calgary]], a large population is dispersed throughout the city. There are several Francophone communities bringing together a few tens of thousands of people, such as those of [[Bonnyville]], [[Plamondon, Alberta|Plamondon]], Saint-Paul, mainly in the north and north-central of [[Alberta]], [[St Isidore's|St-Isidore]], Regional Municipality of [[Municipal District of Smoky River No. 130|Smoky River No. 130]] (including the cities of [[Falher]], [[Donnelly, Alberta|Donnelly]], [[McLennan, Alberta|McLennan]] and [[Girouxville]]) mainly in northwestern Alberta. For several decades, there have also been emerging Francophone populations in medium-sized Alberta cities such as [[Grande Prairie]], [[Fort McMurray]], [[Red Deer, Alberta|Red Deer]] and [[Lethbridge]], among others.\n\nThe Unith\u00e9\u00e2tre in Edmonton and the Theater Society perform in French. The Alberta Visual Arts Center provides a place of expression for French-speaking artists and artisans. There is also an annual French language and culture festival in [[Alberta]].\n\n==History==\nFrench history in Alberta goes back to the [[fur trade in North America]] when [[voyageurs]] (travelling<ref>\n[[\n]]\n</ref> traders) with the Montreal-based [[North-West Company]] arrived in the late 1780s.   Along with new arrivals from [[Canada East]], the French continued to make up a large percentage of the workforce in the [[Hudson\u2019s Bay Company]] after it took over the NWCo. In 1821, and French was the primary European language spoken in what later became Alberta until the 1870s.\n\nAfter Canada acquired [[Rupert\u2019s Land]] (which included the future Alberta) from the HBCo., more francophones arrived from Eastern Canada, the United States, and Europe, this time to settle and found agricultural communities.  They were later joined by urban migrants, and there are now French quarters in both Calgary and Edmonton.\n\nHowever, in 1892, the [[Northwest Territories]] (which at the time covered the [[Canadian Prairies]] west of [[Southern Manitoba]]) abolished French as an official language. In 1984, its status as an official language was restored in the Canadian territories, but not in the prairie provinces.\n\nIn 2011 81,085 Albertans spoke French as first language, giving Alberta the fourth largest francophone population in Canada after Quebec, Ontario, and New Brunswick.  Between  2006 and 2011, of all provinces, it is Alberta where the growth rate of the population with French as a mother tongue or language spoken most often at home was the most important.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2011/as-sa/98-314-x/98-314-x2011003_1-eng.cfm|title=French and the francophonie in Canada|website=www12.statcan.gc.ca|language=en|access-date=2017-05-05}}</ref> The Francophone population grew by approximately 18% since 2006.\nIn the 2006 census 12% of Albertans or 390,000 people claimed French or Acadian ancestry, making French the 3rd largest ethnic group in the province after British (including Scottish) and German.  A combined total of 238,000 Albertans can speak French either as a first or additional language.  In the 2011-12 school year 5,943 students in Alberta were enrolled in francophone schools (where French is the sole language of instruction except during the English Language Arts class) and 145,099 students in Alberta were taking French as a Second Language (FSL) classes.\n\nFour municipalities in Alberta are officially bilingual and offer local services in French: Beaumont ({{convert|15|km}} southeast of Edmonton), Legal ({{convert|35|km}} north of Edmonton), Falher ({{convert|420|km}} northwest of Edmonton), and Plamondon ({{convert|204|km}} northeast of Edmonton).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.culturetourism.alberta.ca/francophone-secretariat/english/facts-and-statistics/|title=Header and Footer|last=Alberta|first=Government of|website=www.culturetourism.alberta.ca|language=en|access-date=2017-05-05}}</ref>\n\n[[File:R\u00e9seau des municipalit\u00e9s bilingues de l'Alberta.png|thumb|Nine municipalities that are members of the Alberta Bilingual Municipalities Network.<ref>[https://www.alberta.ca/release.cfm?xID=471088AC318FE-0275-478A-29387B822D1D55A4#.WUQh8iofsEJ.facebook Alberta unveils first French policy]</ref>]]\nFranco-Albertans are concentrated in communities such as [[Legal, Alberta|Legal]], [[Bonnyville, Alberta|Bonnyville]], [[Plamondon, Alberta|Plamondon]], and [[St. Paul, Alberta|St. Paul]] in the northeastern part of the province, northwest areas such as the hamlet of [[St. Isidore, Alberta|St. Isidore]], [[Municipal District of Smoky River No. 130]] &nbsp; including the towns of [[Falher, Alberta|Falher]], [[Donnelly, Alberta|Donnelly]], [[McLennan, Alberta|McLennan]] and [[Girouxville, Alberta|Girouxville]] and north central [[Alberta]]. Immigration from [[Quebec]] to Alberta in the 1970s and again in the 21st century has also increased the [[francophone]] population of the province, especially in the cities of [[Calgary]], [[Edmonton]] and [[Fort McMurray]].\n\n== Origins ==\nThe territory corresponding today to Alberta was explored in 1741-1749 by the brothers Fran\u00e7ois and Louis-Joseph de la V\u00e9rendrye. The territory was then populated by the [[Assiniboine]], [[Gros Ventre|Atsina]], [[Cree]], [[Blackfoot Confederacy|Blackfoot]], [[Slavey]], Tchipewyan, Tsa-dunnes and [[Tsuu T'ina 145|Tsuu T'inas]]. Some of these peoples have already been present since the end of the 18th century and very early on had commercial ties with the Whites. People called \"[[Coureur des bois|Coureurs des Bois]]\" from [[New France]] also roamed the territory in search of [[Fur|furs]]. French therefore becomes the first language of European origin to be spoken on the territory. Many French [[Toponymy|toponyms]] are also created. [[Anthony Henday]] in [[1754]], [[Peter Pond]] in [[1778]], Alexander MacKenzie in 1789 and 1783, as well as Peter Fiddler and David Thompson at the turn of the 19th century explored the rest of the territory5. By the end of the 18th century, there were already 18 forts because the Hudson's Bay Company and the North West Company competed for the fur trade4 but the two merged in 1821, retaining the name of Compagnie de la Baie Hudson 5.\n\nFrench-speaking settlers from various regions of Canada and the world settled during the 19th century4. The first French-speaking Catholic missionaries to visit the territory were Abbots Blanchet and Demers, in 18384. It was at this time that the Saint-Joachim parish of Edmonton was founded4. There were then five missionaries to serve the whole territory, but the Oblates of Marie-Immaculate were established in 18464. The first school was founded in 1859 at Fort Edmonton4. Religious communities play an important role in education4 and Albert Lacombe is one of the main missionaries5.\n\nThe progress of the establishment of whites in the North threatens the monopoly of the Hudson's Bay Company (HBC) 5. Following the presentation of the report of the Henry Youle Hind expedition of 1857, the British government decided not to renew the license of the HBC5. Its territory was bought by the Canadian government on June 23, 1870 and became the Northwest Territories a year later5. There were only about 1,000 whites in 1881 and, despite the arrival of the Canadian Pacific Railway in Calgary in 1883, the population increased slowly and reached only 17,500 whites in 18915. French already has a important unofficial status at the time, but the Northwest Territories Act of 1875 offered no protection for this language7. In 1877, the Government of Canada changed its mind by adopting section 11, which allowed the use of French in the courts, the Territorial Council, the minutes and the Assembly journal; in 1886, section 11 became section 110 of the Northwest Territories Act7. The federal law protects Catholic and French-language schools, while the 1875 law provides for the possibility, for minorities, the right to establish separate schools7. The Council for Public Education was created in 1884 and divided into two committees, one Protestant and the other Catholic, managing their own schools7. Religious education is, however, restricted to one hour per day7.\n\n==Culture==\n\n''L\u2019Unith\u00e9\u00e2tre'' in Edmonton and the ''Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 de Th\u00e9\u00e2tre'' serve a French-speaking audience, and a number of folk dancing troupes tour the province. The ''Centre d\u2019arts visuels de l\u2019Alberta'' provides a venue for francophone artists and craftsmen, and the annual Franco-Alberta Festival showcases French language and culture.\n\n==Media==\nFrancophones in Alberta receive broadcast media service primarily from the television and radio services of the [[Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 Radio-Canada]], the French-language division of the [[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation]], including [[Ici Radio-Canada T\u00e9l\u00e9]]'s station [[CBXFT-DT]], [[Ici Radio-Canada Premi\u00e8re]]'s [[CHFA-FM]] and [[Ici Musique]]'s [[CBCX-FM]]. Francophone community radio stations exist in Edmonton ([[CFED-FM]]) and [[Plamondon, Alberta|Plamondon]] ([[CHPL-FM]]); a third community radio station, [[CKRP-FM]] in [[Falher, Alberta|Falher]], was shut down in 2017.\n\nIn print, the province is served by the French-language weekly newspaper ''Le Franco''.\n\n==Notable Franco-Albertans==\nThe first notable Franco-Albertan, in many regards, was [[Father Albert Lacombe]].\n\n=== Politics ===\n* [[Prosper-Edmond Lessard]] - Alberta\u2019s first French-speaking cabinet minister. [[Alberta Liberal Party|Liberal]] [[Member of the Legislative Assembly|MLA]] for [[Pakan (electoral district)|Pakan]] (1909-1913) and [[St. Paul (provincial electoral district)|St. Paul]] (1913-1921), [[Senate of Canada|Senator]] for Alberta (1925-1931).\n* [[Wilfrid Gari\u00e9py]] - founding Franco-Albertan/Canadian politician, Liberal MLA for [[Beaver River (provincial electoral district)|Beaver River]] (1913-1921), Alberta Minister of Municipal Affairs (1917-1918), Provincial Secretary (1918).\n* [[\u00c9douard Hector Rouleau]] - Medical doctor, Conservative Politician, pioneer of Calgary.\n* [[Jean L\u00e9on C\u00f4t\u00e9]] - Liberal MLA for [[Athabasca (provincial electoral district)|Athabasca]] (1909-1913) and [[Grouard (electoral district)|Grouard]] (1913-1923).\n* [[Joseph Miville Dechene|Joseph Miville Dech\u00eane]] - Liberal MLA for Beaver River (1921-1926) and St. Paul (1930-1935), [[Liberal Party of Canada|Liberal]] [[Member of parliament|MP]] for [[Athabaska (electoral district)|Athabaska]] (1940-1958).\n* [[Laudas Joly]] - [[United Farmers of Alberta|United Farmers]] MLA for St. Paul (1921-1930) and [[Alberta Social Credit Party|Social Credit]] MLA for [[Bonnyville (provincial electoral district)|Bonnyville]] (1952-1955).\n* [[Joseph Beaudry]] - Social Credit MLA for St. Paul (1935-1952).\n* [[Leo Piquette|L\u00e9o Piquette]] - [[Alberta New Democratic Party|NDP]] MLA for [[Athabasca-Lac La Biche]] (1986-1989), francophone minority rights advocate.\n* [[Paul Langevin (politician)|Paul Andr\u00e9 Joseph Langevin]] - Liberal, then [[Progressive Conservative Association of Alberta|PC]] MLA for [[Lac La Biche-St. Paul]] (1993-2001).\n* [[Denis Ducharme]] - PC MLA for [[Bonnyville-Cold Lake]] (1997-2008).\n* [[Hector Goudreau]] - PC MLA for [[Dunvegan-Central Peace-Notley]] (2004-2015), Alberta Minister of Tourism, Parks, Recreation and Culture (2006\u20132008), Alberta Minister of Municipal Affairs (2008-2011).\n* [[Claudette Tardif]] - Liberal, then independent Senator for Alberta (2005\u2013present). Francophone of Russian descent.\n* [[Colin Piquette]] - son of L\u00e9o Piquette, NDP MLA for [[Athabasca-Sturgeon-Redwater]] (2015\u2013present).\n* [[Marie Renaud]] - NDP MLA for [[St. Albert (provincial electoral district)|St. Albert]] (2015\u2013present).\n* [[Randy Boissonnault]] - Liberal MP for [[Edmonton Centre]] (2015\u20132019).\n*[[Pierre Poilievre]] - Conservative MP for [[Nepean\u2014Carleton]] (2004-present).\n\n=== Sports ===\n* [[Chris Benoit|Chris Beno\u00eet]] - Professional wrestler. Born to a French-Canadian family in Montr\u00e9al, but raised in Edmonton, and wrestled out of Calgary.\n* [[Arthur Boileau]] - Former professional runner of French-Canadian descent. Represented Canada in the 1984 and 1988 Olympics in the Marathon. Born in Edmonton.\n\n=== Art ===\n* [[Beno\u00eet Pariseau]] - Author and broadcaster\n* [[Crystal Plamondon]] - singer and songwriter from [[Plamondon, Alberta]].\n* Les B\u00fbcherons, a duo which presents French-Canadian music and dance to audiences throughout the province.\n* [[Robert Goulet]] - American entertainer of French-Canadian parentage and Franco-Albertan residency. Migrated with his French-Canadian family from Massachusetts to northern Alberta when he was three months old. Was rumoured to be seeking Canadian citizenship, but died in 2007 before any action could be taken.\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Canada}}\n*[[French Canadians]]\n**[[Acadians]], [[French-speaking Quebecer]], [[Franco-Columbian]], [[Franco-Manitoban]], [[Franco-Newfoundlander]], [[Franco-Ontarian]], [[Fransaskois]], [[Franco-T\u00e9nois]], [[Franco-Yukonnais]]\n*[[Franco-Albertan Flag]]\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.lunitheatre.ca L'Unith\u00e9\u00e2tre]\n*[http://www.acfa.ab.ca/ French-Canadian Association of Alberta (ACFA)]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20050402210922/http://collections.ic.gc.ca/ABbenevolat/ ACFA r\u00e9gionale d'Edmonton]\n*[http://www.lefranco.ab.ca/ Le Franco]\n*[http://www.abheritage.ca/francophone/en/  Alberta's Francophone Heritage Website]\n*[http://www.connexioncarriere.ca/ Connexion Carri\u00e8re - Centre de recherche d'emploi]\n\n{{Topics on Alberta}}\n{{Ethnicity in Alberta}}\n{{French diaspora}}\n\n[[Category:Culture of Alberta]]\n[[Category:Franco-Albertan people|*]]\n[[Category:French-Canadian people|A]]\n", "text_old": "{{More footnotes|date=May 2011}}\n{{Infobox ethnic group\n|group       = Franco-Albertans\n|native_name = {{small|''Franco-Albertains''}}\n|flag        = [[File:Flag_of_the_Franco_Albertains.svg|200px|border]]<br /> [[Franco-Albertan flag]]\n|image       = \n|caption     = \n|population     = 79,840<ref>{{cite web |title=Census 2016, focus on geography series - Alberta - Official language minority community |url=https://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2016/as-sa/fogs-spg/Facts-PR-Eng.cfm?TOPIC=5&LANG=Eng&GK=PR&GC=48 |accessdate=17 October 2018}}</ref>\n|popplace    = [[Alberta]]\n|langs       = [[Canadian French]]{{\u00b7}}[[Canadian English]]\n|rels        = Mainly [[Roman Catholicism|Roman Catholic]]\n|related     = [[French Canadians]] [[M\u00e9tis in Alberta|M\u00e9tis]] [[Acadians]] [[French people|French]]\n}}\n'''Franco-Albertans''' ({{lang-fr|Franco-Albertains}}) are an extended community of [[French Canadians]] or [[French language|French]]-speaking people living in the [[Provinces and territories of Canada|Canadian province]] of [[Alberta]]. Alberta was predominantly French-speaking until the end of the 19th century, but has since been predominantly [[English speaking|English-speaking]]. In the capital of Alberta, [[Edmonton]], this population is mainly concentrated in the [[Bonnie Doon, Edmonton|Bonnie Doon]] area. In [[Calgary]], a large population is dispersed throughout the city. There are several Francophone communities bringing together a few tens of thousands of people, such as those of [[Bonnyville]], [[Plamondon, Alberta|Plamondon]], Saint-Paul, mainly in the north and north-central of [[Alberta]], [[St Isidore's|St-Isidore]], Regional Municipality of [[Municipal District of Smoky River No. 130|Smoky River No. 130]] (including the cities of [[Falher]], [[Donnelly, Alberta|Donnelly]], [[McLennan, Alberta|McLennan]] and [[Girouxville]]) mainly in northwestern Alberta. For several decades, there have also been emerging Francophone populations in medium-sized Alberta cities such as [[Grande Prairie]], [[Fort McMurray]], [[Red Deer, Alberta|Red Deer]] and [[Lethbridge]], among others.\n\nThe Unith\u00e9\u00e2tre in Edmonton and the Theater Society perform in French. The Alberta Visual Arts Center provides a place of expression for French-speaking artists and artisans. There is also an annual French language and culture festival in [[Alberta]].\n\n==History==\nFrench history in Alberta goes back to the [[fur trade in North America]] when [[voyageurs]] (travelling<ref>\n[[\n]]\n</ref> traders) with the Montreal-based [[North-West Company]] arrived in the late 1780s.   Along with new arrivals from [[Canada East]], the French continued to make up a large percentage of the workforce in the [[Hudson\u2019s Bay Company]] after it took over the NWCo. In 1821, and French was the primary European language spoken in what later became Alberta until the 1870s.\n\nAfter Canada acquired [[Rupert\u2019s Land]] (which included the future Alberta) from the HBCo., more francophones arrived from Eastern Canada, the United States, and Europe, this time to settle and found agricultural communities.  They were later joined by urban migrants, and there are now French quarters in both Calgary and Edmonton.\n\nHowever, in 1892, the [[Northwest Territories]] (which at the time covered the [[Canadian Prairies]] west of [[Southern Manitoba]]) abolished French as an official language. In 1984, its status as an official language was restored in the Canadian territories, but not in the prairie provinces.\n\nIn 2011 81,085 Albertans spoke French as first language, giving Alberta the fourth largest francophone population in Canada after Quebec, Ontario, and New Brunswick.  Between  2006 and 2011, of all provinces, it is Alberta where the growth rate of the population with French as a mother tongue or language spoken most often at home was the most important.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2011/as-sa/98-314-x/98-314-x2011003_1-eng.cfm|title=French and the francophonie in Canada|website=www12.statcan.gc.ca|language=en|access-date=2017-05-05}}</ref> The Francophone population grew by approximately 18% since 2006.\nIn the 2006 census 12% of Albertans or 390,000 people claimed French or Acadian ancestry, making French the 3rd largest ethnic group in the province after British (including Scottish) and German.  A combined total of 238,000 Albertans can speak French either as a first or additional language.  In the 2011-12 school year 5,943 students in Alberta were enrolled in francophone schools (where French is the sole language of instruction except during the English Language Arts class) and 145,099 students in Alberta were taking French as a Second Language (FSL) classes.\n\nFour municipalities in Alberta are officially bilingual and offer local services in French: Beaumont ({{convert|15|km}} southeast of Edmonton), Legal ({{convert|35|km}} north of Edmonton), Falher ({{convert|420|km}} northwest of Edmonton), and Plamondon ({{convert|204|km}} northeast of Edmonton).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.culturetourism.alberta.ca/francophone-secretariat/english/facts-and-statistics/|title=Header and Footer|last=Alberta|first=Government of|website=www.culturetourism.alberta.ca|language=en|access-date=2017-05-05}}</ref>\n\n[[File:R\u00e9seau des municipalit\u00e9s bilingues de l'Alberta.png|thumb|Nine municipalities that are members of the Alberta Bilingual Municipalities Network.<ref>[https://www.alberta.ca/release.cfm?xID=471088AC318FE-0275-478A-29387B822D1D55A4#.WUQh8iofsEJ.facebook Alberta unveils first French policy]</ref>]]\nFranco-Albertans are concentrated in communities such as [[Legal, Alberta|Legal]], [[Bonnyville, Alberta|Bonnyville]], [[Plamondon, Alberta|Plamondon]], and [[St. Paul, Alberta|St. Paul]] in the northeastern part of the province, northwest areas such as the hamlet of [[St. Isidore, Alberta|St. Isidore]], [[Municipal District of Smoky River No. 130]] &nbsp; including the towns of [[Falher, Alberta|Falher]], [[Donnelly, Alberta|Donnelly]], [[McLennan, Alberta|McLennan]] and [[Girouxville, Alberta|Girouxville]] and north central [[Alberta]]. Immigration from [[Quebec]] to Alberta in the 1970s and again in the 21st century has also increased the [[francophone]] population of the province, especially in the cities of [[Calgary]], [[Edmonton]] and [[Fort McMurray]].\n\n== Origines ==\nThe territory corresponding today to Alberta was explored in 1741-1749 by the brothers Fran\u00e7ois and Louis-Joseph de la V\u00e9rendrye. The territory was then populated by the [[Assiniboine]], [[Gros Ventre|Atsina]], [[Cree]], [[Blackfoot Confederacy|Blackfoot]], [[Slavey]], Tchipewyan, Tsa-dunnes and [[Tsuu T'ina 145|Tsuu T'inas]]. Some of these peoples have already been present since the end of the 18th century and very early on had commercial ties with the Whites. People called \"[[Coureur des bois|Coureurs des Bois]]\" from [[New France]] also roamed the territory in search of [[Fur|furs]]. French therefore becomes the first language of European origin to be spoken on the territory. Many French [[Toponymy|toponyms]] are also created. [[Anthony Henday]] in [[1754]], [[Peter Pond]] in [[1778]], Alexander MacKenzie in 1789 and 1783, as well as Peter Fiddler and David Thompson at the turn of the 19th century explored the rest of the territory5. By the end of the 18th century, there were already 18 forts because the Hudson's Bay Company and the North West Company competed for the fur trade4 but the two merged in 1821, retaining the name of Compagnie de la Baie Hudson 5.\n\nFrench-speaking settlers from various regions of Canada and the world settled during the 19th century4. The first French-speaking Catholic missionaries to visit the territory were Abbots Blanchet and Demers, in 18384. It was at this time that the Saint-Joachim parish of Edmonton was founded4. There were then five missionaries to serve the whole territory, but the Oblates of Marie-Immaculate were established in 18464. The first school was founded in 1859 at Fort Edmonton4. Religious communities play an important role in education4 and Albert Lacombe is one of the main missionaries5.\n\nThe progress of the establishment of whites in the North threatens the monopoly of the Hudson's Bay Company (HBC) 5. Following the presentation of the report of the Henry Youle Hind expedition of 1857, the British government decided not to renew the license of the HBC5. Its territory was bought by the Canadian government on June 23, 1870 and became the Northwest Territories a year later5. There were only about 1,000 whites in 1881 and, despite the arrival of the Canadian Pacific Railway in Calgary in 1883, the population increased slowly and reached only 17,500 whites in 18915. French already has a important unofficial status at the time, but the Northwest Territories Act of 1875 offered no protection for this language7. In 1877, the Government of Canada changed its mind by adopting section 11, which allowed the use of French in the courts, the Territorial Council, the minutes and the Assembly journal; in 1886, section 11 became section 110 of the Northwest Territories Act7. The federal law protects Catholic and French-language schools, while the 1875 law provides for the possibility, for minorities, the right to establish separate schools7. The Council for Public Education was created in 1884 and divided into two committees, one Protestant and the other Catholic, managing their own schools7. Religious education is, however, restricted to one hour per day7.\n\n==Culture==\n\n''L\u2019Unith\u00e9\u00e2tre'' in Edmonton and the ''Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 de Th\u00e9\u00e2tre'' serve a French-speaking audience, and a number of folk dancing troupes tour the province. The ''Centre d\u2019arts visuels de l\u2019Alberta'' provides a venue for francophone artists and craftsmen, and the annual Franco-Alberta Festival showcases French language and culture.\n\n==Media==\nFrancophones in Alberta receive broadcast media service primarily from the television and radio services of the [[Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 Radio-Canada]], the French-language division of the [[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation]], including [[Ici Radio-Canada T\u00e9l\u00e9]]'s station [[CBXFT-DT]], [[Ici Radio-Canada Premi\u00e8re]]'s [[CHFA-FM]] and [[Ici Musique]]'s [[CBCX-FM]]. Francophone community radio stations exist in Edmonton ([[CFED-FM]]) and [[Plamondon, Alberta|Plamondon]] ([[CHPL-FM]]); a third community radio station, [[CKRP-FM]] in [[Falher, Alberta|Falher]], was shut down in 2017.\n\nIn print, the province is served by the French-language weekly newspaper ''Le Franco''.\n\n==Notable Franco-Albertans==\nThe first notable Franco-Albertan, in many regards, was [[Father Albert Lacombe]].\n\n=== Politics ===\n* [[Prosper-Edmond Lessard]] - Alberta\u2019s first French-speaking cabinet minister. [[Alberta Liberal Party|Liberal]] [[Member of the Legislative Assembly|MLA]] for [[Pakan (electoral district)|Pakan]] (1909-1913) and [[St. Paul (provincial electoral district)|St. Paul]] (1913-1921), [[Senate of Canada|Senator]] for Alberta (1925-1931).\n* [[Wilfrid Gari\u00e9py]] - founding Franco-Albertan/Canadian politician, Liberal MLA for [[Beaver River (provincial electoral district)|Beaver River]] (1913-1921), Alberta Minister of Municipal Affairs (1917-1918), Provincial Secretary (1918).\n* [[\u00c9douard Hector Rouleau]] - Medical doctor, Conservative Politician, pioneer of Calgary.\n* [[Jean L\u00e9on C\u00f4t\u00e9]] - Liberal MLA for [[Athabasca (provincial electoral district)|Athabasca]] (1909-1913) and [[Grouard (electoral district)|Grouard]] (1913-1923).\n* [[Joseph Miville Dechene|Joseph Miville Dech\u00eane]] - Liberal MLA for Beaver River (1921-1926) and St. Paul (1930-1935), [[Liberal Party of Canada|Liberal]] [[Member of parliament|MP]] for [[Athabaska (electoral district)|Athabaska]] (1940-1958).\n* [[Laudas Joly]] - [[United Farmers of Alberta|United Farmers]] MLA for St. Paul (1921-1930) and [[Alberta Social Credit Party|Social Credit]] MLA for [[Bonnyville (provincial electoral district)|Bonnyville]] (1952-1955).\n* [[Joseph Beaudry]] - Social Credit MLA for St. Paul (1935-1952).\n* [[Leo Piquette|L\u00e9o Piquette]] - [[Alberta New Democratic Party|NDP]] MLA for [[Athabasca-Lac La Biche]] (1986-1989), francophone minority rights advocate.\n* [[Paul Langevin (politician)|Paul Andr\u00e9 Joseph Langevin]] - Liberal, then [[Progressive Conservative Association of Alberta|PC]] MLA for [[Lac La Biche-St. Paul]] (1993-2001).\n* [[Denis Ducharme]] - PC MLA for [[Bonnyville-Cold Lake]] (1997-2008).\n* [[Hector Goudreau]] - PC MLA for [[Dunvegan-Central Peace-Notley]] (2004-2015), Alberta Minister of Tourism, Parks, Recreation and Culture (2006\u20132008), Alberta Minister of Municipal Affairs (2008-2011).\n* [[Claudette Tardif]] - Liberal, then independent Senator for Alberta (2005\u2013present). Francophone of Russian descent.\n* [[Colin Piquette]] - son of L\u00e9o Piquette, NDP MLA for [[Athabasca-Sturgeon-Redwater]] (2015\u2013present).\n* [[Marie Renaud]] - NDP MLA for [[St. Albert (provincial electoral district)|St. Albert]] (2015\u2013present).\n* [[Randy Boissonnault]] - Liberal MP for [[Edmonton Centre]] (2015\u20132019).\n*[[Pierre Poilievre]] - Conservative MP for [[Nepean\u2014Carleton]] (2004-present).\n\n=== Sports ===\n* [[Chris Benoit|Chris Beno\u00eet]] - Professional wrestler. Born to a French-Canadian family in Montr\u00e9al, but raised in Edmonton, and wrestled out of Calgary.\n* [[Arthur Boileau]] - Former professional runner of French-Canadian descent. Represented Canada in the 1984 and 1988 Olympics in the Marathon. Born in Edmonton.\n\n=== Art ===\n* [[Beno\u00eet Pariseau]] - Author and broadcaster\n* [[Crystal Plamondon]] - singer and songwriter from [[Plamondon, Alberta]].\n* Les B\u00fbcherons, a duo which presents French-Canadian music and dance to audiences throughout the province.\n* [[Robert Goulet]] - American entertainer of French-Canadian parentage and Franco-Albertan residency. Migrated with his French-Canadian family from Massachusetts to northern Alberta when he was three months old. Was rumoured to be seeking Canadian citizenship, but died in 2007 before any action could be taken.\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Canada}}\n*[[French Canadians]]\n**[[Acadians]], [[French-speaking Quebecer]], [[Franco-Columbian]], [[Franco-Manitoban]], [[Franco-Newfoundlander]], [[Franco-Ontarian]], [[Fransaskois]], [[Franco-T\u00e9nois]], [[Franco-Yukonnais]]\n*[[Franco-Albertan Flag]]\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.lunitheatre.ca L'Unith\u00e9\u00e2tre]\n*[http://www.acfa.ab.ca/ French-Canadian Association of Alberta (ACFA)]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20050402210922/http://collections.ic.gc.ca/ABbenevolat/ ACFA r\u00e9gionale d'Edmonton]\n*[http://www.lefranco.ab.ca/ Le Franco]\n*[http://www.abheritage.ca/francophone/en/  Alberta's Francophone Heritage Website]\n*[http://www.connexioncarriere.ca/ Connexion Carri\u00e8re - Centre de recherche d'emploi]\n\n{{Topics on Alberta}}\n{{Ethnicity in Alberta}}\n{{French diaspora}}\n\n[[Category:Culture of Alberta]]\n[[Category:Franco-Albertan people|*]]\n[[Category:French-Canadian people|A]]\n", "name_user": "Leventio", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eOrigines:sp", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Franco-Albertans"}
{"title_page": "Aaron Zigman", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Aaron Zigman\n| image              = Top-film-composers-aaron-zigman.jpg\n| image_size         = \n| caption            = \n| birth_name         = \n| birth_place        = [[San Diego, California]]\n| death_date         = \n| death_place        = \n| occupation         = Composer, arranger, conductor, songwriter, producer\n| known_for          = Award-winning film composer and musician\n| notable_works      = Film scores for ''The Notebook'', ''Bridge to Terabithia'', ''John Q.'', ''The Proposal'', ''Flicka'', ''The Company Men'', ''For Colored Girls'', ''Flash of Genius'', ''Sex & the City I'' and ''II''. Co-wrote, arranged, and produced songs with Quincy Jones, Christina Aguilera, John Legend, Ray Charles, Natalie Cole, Aretha Franklin, Patti LaBelle, and Tina Turner.\n| website            = {{url|http://www.aaronzigman.com}}\n| landscape          = <!-- yes, if wide image, otherwise leave blank -->\n}}\n'''Aaron Zigman''' is a classically-trained American composer, producer, arranger, songwriter, and musician who has scored music for films including ''[[The Notebook]]'', ''[[The Company Men]]'', ''[[Bridge to Terabithia (2007 film)|Bridge to Terabithia]]'', ''[[John Q.]]'', ''[[The Proposal (2009 film)|The Proposal]]'', ''[[Flicka]]'', ''[[For Colored Girls]]'', ''[[Flash of Genius (film)|Flash of Genius]]'', ''[[Sex and the City|Sex & the City]], [[Alpha Dog]],'' and ''[[Escape from Planet Earth]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://catalog.afi.com/Person/273866-Aaron-Zigman?sid=cadb9b5a-b336-4745-bf58-01991f6bdf6b&sr=11.577783&cp=1&pos=0&isMiscCredit=false|title=AFI{{!}}Catalog|website=catalog.afi.com|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> He has also written, arranged and produced over 50 hit albums, and co-written songs with legendary and contemporary artists including [[Quincy Jones]], [[Christina Aguilera]], Phil Collins, [[Was (Not Was)]], [[John Legend]], Dione Warwick, [[Ray Charles]], Natalie Cole, Aretha Franklin, Tina Turner, and [[Seal (musician)|Seal]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.allaboutjazz.com/aaron-zigman-the-making-of-a-hit-soundtrack-the-jazz-influence-and-the-inside-story-of-music-for-the-cinema-by-victor-l-schermer.php|title=Aaron Zigman: The Making of a Hit Soundtrack, the Jazz Influence, and the &quot;Inside Story&quot; of Music for the Cinema article @ All About Jazz|last=Jazz|first=All About|website=All About Jazz|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and career==\nZigman was born in [[San Diego, California]]. A graduate of [[Point Loma High School]], he studied at the [[University of California, Los Angeles]].<ref name=\":0\" /> \n\nWhile still in college, he had a contract with Almo Irving and wrote songs for [[Carly Simon]] and the T.V. show ''Fame'', and co-wrote with [[David Lasley]], [[Jerry Knight]], and [[Steve Cropper]].<ref>[http://www.aaronzigman.com/bio.htm Aaron Zigman's official site] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110707072636/http://www.aaronzigman.com/bio.htm |date=2011-07-07 }}</ref> In 1983, he began studying with his cousin [[George Bassman]] (who orchestrated ''[[The Wizard of Oz (1939 film)|The Wizard of Oz]]'' and wrote the music for the films ''Marty'' and ''[[The Postman Always Rings Twice (1981 film)|The Postman Always Rings Twice]]'').<ref name=\":0\" /> Bassman had also penned the [[Tommy Dorsey]] Classic, \"Getting Sentimental Over You\", was the musical arranger for [[Lena Horne]] and [[Benny Goodman]], and orchestrated for [[Andre Kostelanetz]]. \n\nIn the 1980s, Zigman began to make a name for himself as a studio musician and wrote the pop music hit \"Crush On You\", a top chart record for [[The Jets (Minnesota band)|The Jets]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1988-01-24-vw-37763-story.html|title=Partying to the Max in Beverly Hills|date=1988-01-24|website=Los Angeles Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" /> He then worked for [[Clive Davis]], and produced and arranged for [[Aretha Franklin]] and [[Natalie Cole]].<ref name=\":0\" /> During this time he wrote, arranged and produced songs for many of the top singers and artists in the industry such as [[Ray Charles]], [[Phil Collins]], [[Dionne Warwick]], [[Boz Scaggs]], [[Tina Turner]], [[Seal (musician)|Seal]], [[Carly Simon]], the [[Pointer Sisters]], Jermaine Stewart,  [[Huey Lewis]], [[Jennifer Holliday]], [[Patti LaBelle]], [[Chicago]], [[Natalie Cole]], and [[Christina Aguilera]].<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bmi.com/news/entry/aaron_zigman_finds_his_calling|title=Aaron Zigman Finds His Calling|date=2010-01-02|website=BMI.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> \n\nIn the 1990s he entered the film industry, with his work being featured on soundtracks for ''[[Mulan (1998 film)|Mulan]]'', ''[[What's Love Got to Do with It (film)|What's Love Got to Do With It?]]'', ''[[The Birdcage]]'', ''[[Licence to Kill]]'', and ''[[Pocahontas (1995 film)|Pocahontas]]''. His first film score was for the 2002 film ''[[John Q.]]''<ref name=\":0\" /> This led to his first major film score, the 2004 film ''[[The Notebook (2004 film)|The Notebook]]'',<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.grammy.com/professional-development/article/aaron-zigman-scoring-notebook-best-me-more|title=Interview: The Best Of Composer Aaron Zigman|date=2014-12-01|website=GRAMMY.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> for which he won multiple [[BMI Awards]].\n\n== Work in China, Tango Manos and Jean-Yves Thibaudet ==\nIn the soundtrack for the 2016 drama film Wakefield, Thibaudet played Zigman\u2019s composition which was the first time another pianist performed his film work.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.seattlesymphony.org/about/meetthemusicians/theorchestra/artists/q-t/thibaudet-jean-yves|title=Jean-Yves Thibaudet|website=www.seattlesymphony.org|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> Zigman first visited Beijing while working on the film score for Chinese movie Hidden Man, directed by Wen Jiang.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/why-hollywood-film-talent-is-flocking-china-1124383|title=Why Hollywood Film Talent Is Flocking to China|website=The Hollywood Reporter|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://xw.qq.com/cmsid/20191217A073IP00|title=\u300a\u4eca\u65e5\u97f3\u4e50\u300b\u4e13\u8bbf {{!}} \u7f8e\u56fd\u4f5c\u66f2\u5bb6\u4e9a\u4f26\u00b7\u9f50\u683c\u66fcAaron Zigman|website=xw.qq.com|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> Hidden Man was China\u2019s entry for Best Foreign Language Film at the 91st Academy Awards.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://chinafilminsider.com/headlines-from-china-china-submits-jiang-wens-hidden-man-to-the-oscars/|title=Headlines from China: China Submits Jiang Wen's 'Hidden Man' To The Oscars|date=2018-10-09|website=China Film Insider|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> \n\n=== Tango Manos ===\nThe Tango Manos project was suggested to Zigman by Long Yu, Artistic Director and Chief Conductor of the China Philharmonic.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ebar.com/arts_&_culture/music//288232|title=French masters bring concert hall flair|website=The Bay Area Reporter / B.A.R. Inc.|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> Zigman composed the concerto for piano and orchestra dedicating it to French pianist Jean-Yves Thibaudet, who performed Tango Manos at the world premiere with the China Philharmonic at the Beijing Music Festival, October 14, 2019.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.sfsymphony.org/|title=San Francisco Symphony|website=San Francisco Symphony|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://m.sohu.com/a/346750379_114988|title=\u5386\u5c4a\u59d4\u7ea6\u4f5c\u54c1\u540c\u53f0\u7efd\u653e\uff0c\u9f50\u683c\u66fc\u94a2\u7434\u534f\u594f\u66f2\u4e16\u754c\u9996\u6f14_\u624b\u673a\u641c\u72d0\u7f51|website=m.sohu.com|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> \n\nZigman attended the October 13, 2019 press conference for the 22nd Beijing Music Festival in Beijing, China.<ref name=\":2\" /> Tango Manos was one of three works written for the Beijing Music Festival, commissioned by the China Philharmonic, Radio France and the San Francisco Symphony.<ref name=\":1\" /> The event was of cultural significance, taking place in Jingshan Park, in front of Shouhuang Hall.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.cgtn.com/news/2019-10-15/Concert-bridge-cultural-differences-at-Beijing-Music-Festival--KOxBzGdXIk/index.html|title=Concert bridge cultural differences at Beijing Music Festival|website=news.cgtn.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> \u00a0\n\nJean-Yves Thibaudet performed the US premiere of Tango Manos with the San Francisco Orchestra in February\u00a02020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ebar.com/arts_&_culture/music//288232|title=French masters bring concert hall flair|website=The Bay Area Reporter / B.A.R. Inc.|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>[[File:Film-composer-aaronzigman-john-legend.jpg|right|thumb|Aaron Zigman in studio with John Legend writing the theme song to the movie ''Pride'']]\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===2000s===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Director(s)\n! Studio(s)\n! Notes\n|-\n| 2002\n! ''[[John Q.]]''\n| [[Nick Cassavetes]]\n| [[New Line Cinema]]\n| {{N/A}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"| 2004\n! ''[[The Notebook (2004 film)|The Notebook]]''\n| [[Nick Cassavetes]]\n| [[New Line Cinema]]\n| {{N/A}}\n|-\n! ''[[Raise Your Voice]]''\n| [[Sean McNamara (director)|Sean McNamara]]\n| [[New Line Cinema]]\n| {{N/A}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"| 2005\n! ''[[The Wendell Baker Story]]''\n| [[Andrew Wilson (actor)|Andrew Wilson]]<br>[[Luke Wilson]]\n| Wendell Distribution\n| {{N/A}}\n|-\n! ''[[In the Mix (film)|In the Mix]]''\n| [[Ron Underwood]]\n| [[Lionsgate]]\n| {{N/A}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"8\"| 2006\n! ''[[Alpha Dog]]''\n| [[Nick Cassavetes]]\n| [[Universal Pictures]]\n| {{N/A}}\n|-\n! ''The Virgin of Juarez''\n| Kevin James Dobson\n| [[First Look Studios]]\n| {{N/A}}\n|-\n! ''[[ATL (film)|ATL]]''\n| [[Chris Robinson (director)|Chris Robinson]]\n| [[Warner Bros. Pictures]]\n| {{N/A}}\n|-\n! ''[[Take the Lead]]''\n| [[Liz Friedlander]]\n| [[New Line Cinema]]\n| {{N/A}}\n|-\n! ''[[Akeelah and the Bee]]''\n| [[Doug Atchison]]\n| [[Lionsgate]]\n| {{N/A}}\n|-\n! ''[[Step Up (film)|Step Up]]''\n| [[Anne Fletcher]]\n| [[Touchstone Pictures]]\n| {{N/A}}\n|-\n! ''[[10th & Wolf]]''\n| [[Robert Moresco]]\n| [[ThinkFilm]]\n| {{N/A}}\n|-\n! ''[[Flicka]]''\n| [[Michael Mayer (director)|Michael Mayer]]\n| [[20th Century Fox]]\n| {{N/A}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"7\"| 2007\n! ''[[Bridge to Terabithia (2007 film)|Bridge to Terabithia]]''\n| [[G\u00e1bor Csup\u00f3]]\n| [[Walt Disney Pictures]]\n| {{N/A}}\n|-\n! ''[[Pride (2007 film)|Pride]]''\n| Sunu Gonera\n| [[Lionsgate]]\n| {{N/A}}\n|-\n! ''[[Good Luck Chuck]]''\n| [[Mark Helfrich (film editor)|Mark Helfrich]]\n| [[Lionsgate]]\n| {{N/A}}\n|-\n! ''[[The Jane Austen Book Club (film)|The Jane Austen Book Club]]''\n| [[Robin Swicord]]\n| [[Sony Pictures Classics]]\n| {{N/A}}\n|-\n! ''[[Why Did I Get Married?]]''\n| [[Tyler Perry]]\n| [[Lionsgate]]\n| {{N/A}}\n|-\n! ''[[Martian Child]]''\n| [[Menno Meyjes]]\n| [[New Line Cinema]]\n| {{N/A}}\n|-\n! ''[[Mr. Magorium's Wonder Emporium]]''\n| [[Zach Helm]]\n| [[20th Century Fox]]\n| with [[Alexandre Desplat]]\n|-\n| rowspan=\"7\"| 2008\n! ''[[Step Up 2: The Streets]]''\n| [[Jon M. Chu]]\n| [[Touchstone Pictures]]\n| {{N/A}}\n|-\n! ''[[Meet the Browns (film)|Meet the Browns]]''\n| [[Tyler Perry]]\n| [[Lionsgate]]\n| {{N/A}}\n|-\n! ''[[Sex and the City: The Movie]]''\n| [[Michael Patrick King]]\n| [[New Line Cinema]]\n| {{N/A}}\n|-\n! ''[[The Family That Preys]]''\n| [[Tyler Perry]]\n| [[Lionsgate]]\n| {{N/A}}\n|-\n! ''[[Flash of Genius (film)|Flash of Genius]]''\n| [[Marc Abraham]]\n| [[Universal Pictures]]\n| {{N/A}}\n|-\n! ''[[Christmas Cottage]]''\n| Michael Campus\n| [[Lionsgate]]\n| {{N/A}}\n|-\n! ''[[Lake City (film)|Lake City]]''\n| [[Perry Moore]]<br>Hunter Hill\n| [[Screen Media Films]]\n| {{N/A}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"5\"| 2009\n! ''[[Madea Goes to Jail]]''\n| [[Tyler Perry]]\n| [[Lionsgate]]\n| {{N/A}}\n|-\n! ''[[The Proposal (2009 film)|The Proposal]]''\n| [[Anne Fletcher]]\n| [[Touchstone Pictures]]\n| {{N/A}}\n|-\n! ''[[My Sister's Keeper (film)|My Sister's Keeper]]''\n| [[Nick Cassavetes]]\n| [[New Line Cinema]]\n| {{N/A}}\n|-\n! ''[[The Ugly Truth (film)|The Ugly Truth]]''\n| [[Robert Luketic]]\n| [[Columbia Pictures]]\n| {{N/A}}\n|-\n! ''[[I Can Do Bad All By Myself (film)|I Can Do Bad All By Myself]]''\n| [[Tyler Perry]]\n| [[Lionsgate]]\n| {{N/A}}\n|}\n\n===2010s===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Director(s)\n! Studio(s)\n|-\n|rowspan=\"5\"| 2010\n! ''[[The Company Men]]''\n| [[John Wells (producer)|John Wells]]\n| [[The Weinstein Company]]\n|-\n! ''[[The Last Song (2010 film)|The Last Song]]''\n| [[Julie Anne Robinson]]\n| [[Touchstone Pictures]]\n|-\n! ''[[Why Did I Get Married Too?]]''\n| [[Tyler Perry]]\n| [[Lionsgate]]\n|-\n! ''[[Sex and the City 2]]''\n| [[Michael Patrick King]]\n| [[New Line Cinema]]\n|-\n! ''[[For Colored Girls]]''\n| [[Tyler Perry]]\n| [[Lionsgate]]\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"| 2011\n! ''[[Madea's Big Happy Family (film)|Madea's Big Happy Family]]''\n| [[Tyler Perry]]\n| [[Lionsgate]]\n|-\n! ''[[I Don't Know How She Does It]]''\n| [[Douglas McGrath]]\n| [[The Weinstein Company]]\n|-\n! ''[[What's Your Number?]]''\n| [[Mark Mylod]]\n| [[20th Century Fox]]\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"| 2012\n! ''[[Good Deeds]]''\n| [[Tyler Perry]]\n| [[Lionsgate]]\n|-\n! ''[[Madea's Witness Protection]]''\n| [[Tyler Perry]]\n| [[Lionsgate]]\n|-\n! ''[[Step Up Revolution]]''\n| [[Scott Speer]]\n| [[Summit Entertainment]]\n|-\n|rowspan=\"4\"| 2013\n! ''[[Escape from Planet Earth]]''\n| Cal Brunker\n| [[The Weinstein Company]]\n|-\n! ''[[Temptation: Confessions of a Marriage Counselor]]''\n| [[Tyler Perry]]\n| [[Lionsgate]]\n|-\n! ''[[Peeples (2013 film)|Peeples]]''\n| [[Tina Gordon Chism]]\n| [[Lionsgate]]\n|-\n! ''[[Baggage Claim (film)|Baggage Claim]]''\n| [[David E. Talbert]]\n| [[Fox Searchlight Pictures]]\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"| 2014\n! ''[[The Other Woman (2014 film)|The Other Woman]]''\n| [[Nick Cassavetes]]\n| [[20th Century Fox]]\n|-\n! ''[[The Best of Me (film)|The Best of Me]]''\n| [[Michael Hoffman (American director)|Michael Hoffman]]\n| [[Relativity Media]]\n|-\n| 2015\n! ''[[Mr. Right (2015 film)|Mr. Right]]''\n| [[Paco Cabezas]]\n| [[Focus World]]\n|-\n| 2016\n! ''[[Wakefield (film)|Wakefield]]''\n| [[Robin Swicord]]\n| \n|-\n| 2017\n! '''''[[The Shack (2017 film)|The Shack]]'''''\n| [[Stuart Hazeldine]]\n| [[Summit Entertainment]]\n|-\n| TBA\n! '''''[[A Nice Girl Like You]]'''''\n| Chris Riedell and Nick Riedell\n|\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|0956374}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Zigman, Aaron}}\n[[Category:Musicians from San Diego]]\n[[Category:Point Loma High School alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:University of California, Los Angeles alumni]]\n[[Category:American male composers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American composers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male musicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Aaron Zigman\n| image              = Top-film-composers-aaron-zigman.jpg\n| image_size         = \n| caption            = \n| birth_name         = \n| birth_place        = [[San Diego, California]]\n| death_date         = \n| death_place        = \n| occupation         = Composer, arranger, conductor, songwriter, producer\n| known_for          = Award-winning film composer and musician\n| notable_works      = Film scores for ''The Notebook'', ''Bridge to Terabithia'', ''John Q.'', ''The Proposal'', ''Flicka'', ''The Company Men'', ''For Colored Girls'', ''Flash of Genius'', ''Sex & the City I'' and ''II''. Co-wrote, arranged, and produced songs with Quincy Jones, Christina Aguilera, John Legend, Ray Charles, Natalie Cole, Aretha Franklin, Patti LaBelle, and Tina Turner.\n| website            = {{url|http://www.aaronzigman.com}}\n| landscape          = <!-- yes, if wide image, otherwise leave blank -->\n}}\n'''Aaron Zigman''' is a classically-trained American composer, producer, arranger, songwriter, and musician who has scored music for films including ''[[The Notebook]]'', ''[[The Company Men]]'', ''[[Bridge to Terabithia (2007 film)|Bridge to Terabithia]]'', ''[[John Q.]]'', ''[[The Proposal (2009 film)|The Proposal]]'', ''[[Flicka]]'', ''[[For Colored Girls]]'', ''[[Flash of Genius (film)|Flash of Genius]]'', ''[[Sex and the City|Sex & the City]], [[Alpha Dog]],'' and ''[[Escape from Planet Earth]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://catalog.afi.com/Person/273866-Aaron-Zigman?sid=cadb9b5a-b336-4745-bf58-01991f6bdf6b&sr=11.577783&cp=1&pos=0&isMiscCredit=false|title=AFI{{!}}Catalog|website=catalog.afi.com|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> He has also written, arranged and produced over 50 hit albums, and co-written songs with legendary and contemporary artists including [[Quincy Jones]], [[Christina Aguilera]], Phil Collins, [[Was (Not Was)]], [[John Legend]], Dione Warwick, [[Ray Charles]], Natalie Cole, Aretha Franklin, Tina Turner, and [[Seal (musician)|Seal]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.allaboutjazz.com/aaron-zigman-the-making-of-a-hit-soundtrack-the-jazz-influence-and-the-inside-story-of-music-for-the-cinema-by-victor-l-schermer.php|title=Aaron Zigman: The Making of a Hit Soundtrack, the Jazz Influence, and the &quot;Inside Story&quot; of Music for the Cinema article @ All About Jazz|last=Jazz|first=All About|website=All About Jazz|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and career==\nZigman was born in [[San Diego, California]]. A graduate of [[Point Loma High School]], he studied at the [[University of California, Los Angeles]].<ref name=\":0\" /> \n\nWhile still in college, he had a contract with Almo Irving and wrote songs for [[Carly Simon]] and the T.V. show ''Fame'', and co-wrote with [[David Lasley]], [[Jerry Knight]], and [[Steve Cropper]].<ref>[http://www.aaronzigman.com/bio.htm Aaron Zigman's official site] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110707072636/http://www.aaronzigman.com/bio.htm |date=2011-07-07 }}</ref> In 1983, he began studying with his cousin [[George Bassman]] (who orchestrated ''[[The Wizard of Oz (1939 film)|The Wizard of Oz]]'' and wrote the music for the films ''Marty'' and ''[[The Postman Always Rings Twice (1981 film)|The Postman Always Rings Twice]]'').<ref name=\":0\" /> Bassman had also penned the [[Tommy Dorsey]] Classic, \"Getting Sentimental Over You\", was the musical arranger for [[Lena Horne]] and [[Benny Goodman]], and orchestrated for [[Andre Kostelanetz]]. \n\nIn the 1980s, Zigman began to make a name for himself as a studio musician and wrote the pop music hit \"Crush On You\", a top chart record for [[The Jets (Minnesota band)|The Jets]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1988-01-24-vw-37763-story.html|title=Partying to the Max in Beverly Hills|date=1988-01-24|website=Los Angeles Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" /> He then worked for [[Clive Davis]], and produced and arranged for [[Aretha Franklin]] and [[Natalie Cole]].<ref name=\":0\" /> During this time he wrote, arranged and produced songs for many of the top singers and artists in the industry such as [[Ray Charles]], [[Phil Collins]], [[Dionne Warwick]], [[Boz Scaggs]], [[Tina Turner]], [[Seal (musician)|Seal]], [[Carly Simon]], the [[Pointer Sisters]], Jermaine Stewart,  [[Huey Lewis]], [[Jennifer Holliday]], [[Patti LaBelle]], [[Chicago]], [[Natalie Cole]], and [[Christina Aguilera]].<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bmi.com/news/entry/aaron_zigman_finds_his_calling|title=Aaron Zigman Finds His Calling|date=2010-01-02|website=BMI.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> \n\nIn the 1990s he entered the film industry, with his work being featured on soundtracks for ''[[Mulan (1998 film)|Mulan]]'', ''[[What's Love Got to Do with It (film)|What's Love Got to Do With It?]]'', ''[[The Birdcage]]'', ''[[Licence to Kill]]'', and ''[[Pocahontas (1995 film)|Pocahontas]]''. His first film score was for the 2002 film ''[[John Q.]]''<ref name=\":0\" /> This led to his first major film score, the 2004 film ''[[The Notebook (2004 film)|The Notebook]]'',<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.grammy.com/professional-development/article/aaron-zigman-scoring-notebook-best-me-more|title=Interview: The Best Of Composer Aaron Zigman|date=2014-12-01|website=GRAMMY.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> for which he won multiple [[BMI Awards]].\n\n== Work in China, Tango Manos and Jean-Yves Thibaudet ==\nZigman first visited Beijing while working on the film score for Chinese movie Hidden Man, directed by Wen Jiang.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/why-hollywood-film-talent-is-flocking-china-1124383|title=Why Hollywood Film Talent Is Flocking to China|website=The Hollywood Reporter|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://xw.qq.com/cmsid/20191217A073IP00|title=\u300a\u4eca\u65e5\u97f3\u4e50\u300b\u4e13\u8bbf {{!}} \u7f8e\u56fd\u4f5c\u66f2\u5bb6\u4e9a\u4f26\u00b7\u9f50\u683c\u66fcAaron Zigman|website=xw.qq.com|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> \n\n=== Tango Manos ===\nThe Tango Manos project was first suggested to Zigman by Long Yu, Artistic Director and Chief Conductor of the China Philharmonic.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ebar.com/arts_&_culture/music//288232|title=French masters bring concert hall flair|website=The Bay Area Reporter / B.A.R. Inc.|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> Zigman composed the concerto for piano and orchestra dedicating it to French pianist Jean-Yves Thibaudet, who performed it at the world premiere with the China Philharmonic at the Beijing Music Festival, October 14, 2019.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.sfsymphony.org/|title=San Francisco Symphony|website=San Francisco Symphony|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://m.sohu.com/a/346750379_114988|title=\u5386\u5c4a\u59d4\u7ea6\u4f5c\u54c1\u540c\u53f0\u7efd\u653e\uff0c\u9f50\u683c\u66fc\u94a2\u7434\u534f\u594f\u66f2\u4e16\u754c\u9996\u6f14_\u624b\u673a\u641c\u72d0\u7f51|website=m.sohu.com|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> In the soundtrack for the 2016 drama film Wakefield, Thibaudet played Zigman\u2019s composition which was the first time another pianist performed his film work.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.seattlesymphony.org/about/meetthemusicians/theorchestra/artists/q-t/thibaudet-jean-yves|title=Jean-Yves Thibaudet|website=www.seattlesymphony.org|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n\nZigman attended the October 13, 2019 press conference for the 22nd Beijing Music Festival in Beijing, China.<ref name=\":2\" /> Tango Manos was one of three works written for the Beijing Music Festival, commissioned by the China Philharmonic, Radio France and the San Francisco Symphony.<ref name=\":1\" /> The event was of cultural significance, taking place in Jingshan Park, in front of Shouhuang Hall.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.cgtn.com/news/2019-10-15/Concert-bridge-cultural-differences-at-Beijing-Music-Festival--KOxBzGdXIk/index.html|title=Concert bridge cultural differences at Beijing Music Festival|website=news.cgtn.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> \u00a0\n\nJean-Yves Thibaudet performed the US premiere of Tango Manos with the San Francisco Orchestra in February\u00a02020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ebar.com/arts_&_culture/music//288232|title=French masters bring concert hall flair|website=The Bay Area Reporter / B.A.R. Inc.|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>[[File:Film-composer-aaronzigman-john-legend.jpg|right|thumb|Aaron Zigman in studio with John Legend writing the theme song to the movie ''Pride'']]\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===2000s===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Director(s)\n! Studio(s)\n! Notes\n|-\n| 2002\n! ''[[John Q.]]''\n| [[Nick Cassavetes]]\n| [[New Line Cinema]]\n| {{N/A}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"| 2004\n! ''[[The Notebook (2004 film)|The Notebook]]''\n| [[Nick Cassavetes]]\n| [[New Line Cinema]]\n| {{N/A}}\n|-\n! ''[[Raise Your Voice]]''\n| [[Sean McNamara (director)|Sean McNamara]]\n| [[New Line Cinema]]\n| {{N/A}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"| 2005\n! ''[[The Wendell Baker Story]]''\n| [[Andrew Wilson (actor)|Andrew Wilson]]<br>[[Luke Wilson]]\n| Wendell Distribution\n| {{N/A}}\n|-\n! ''[[In the Mix (film)|In the Mix]]''\n| [[Ron Underwood]]\n| [[Lionsgate]]\n| {{N/A}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"8\"| 2006\n! ''[[Alpha Dog]]''\n| [[Nick Cassavetes]]\n| [[Universal Pictures]]\n| {{N/A}}\n|-\n! ''The Virgin of Juarez''\n| Kevin James Dobson\n| [[First Look Studios]]\n| {{N/A}}\n|-\n! ''[[ATL (film)|ATL]]''\n| [[Chris Robinson (director)|Chris Robinson]]\n| [[Warner Bros. Pictures]]\n| {{N/A}}\n|-\n! ''[[Take the Lead]]''\n| [[Liz Friedlander]]\n| [[New Line Cinema]]\n| {{N/A}}\n|-\n! ''[[Akeelah and the Bee]]''\n| [[Doug Atchison]]\n| [[Lionsgate]]\n| {{N/A}}\n|-\n! ''[[Step Up (film)|Step Up]]''\n| [[Anne Fletcher]]\n| [[Touchstone Pictures]]\n| {{N/A}}\n|-\n! ''[[10th & Wolf]]''\n| [[Robert Moresco]]\n| [[ThinkFilm]]\n| {{N/A}}\n|-\n! ''[[Flicka]]''\n| [[Michael Mayer (director)|Michael Mayer]]\n| [[20th Century Fox]]\n| {{N/A}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"7\"| 2007\n! ''[[Bridge to Terabithia (2007 film)|Bridge to Terabithia]]''\n| [[G\u00e1bor Csup\u00f3]]\n| [[Walt Disney Pictures]]\n| {{N/A}}\n|-\n! ''[[Pride (2007 film)|Pride]]''\n| Sunu Gonera\n| [[Lionsgate]]\n| {{N/A}}\n|-\n! ''[[Good Luck Chuck]]''\n| [[Mark Helfrich (film editor)|Mark Helfrich]]\n| [[Lionsgate]]\n| {{N/A}}\n|-\n! ''[[The Jane Austen Book Club (film)|The Jane Austen Book Club]]''\n| [[Robin Swicord]]\n| [[Sony Pictures Classics]]\n| {{N/A}}\n|-\n! ''[[Why Did I Get Married?]]''\n| [[Tyler Perry]]\n| [[Lionsgate]]\n| {{N/A}}\n|-\n! 