]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male musicians]]\n", "name_user": "Cinnabon95", "label": "safe", "comment": "more info added", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aaron_Zigman"}
{"title_page": "Public Health Emergency of International Concern", "text_new": "{{short description|Formal declaration by the World Health Organization}} \n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n[[File:World Health Organization Logo.svg|thumb|Logo of the World Health Organization, the authority which declares PHEIC]]\nA '''Public Health Emergency of International Concern'''<ref name=Van-Tam2010>{{Cite book|last=Van-Tam|first=Jonathan|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_IYYr9cjE30C&pg=PA195|title=Introduction to Pandemic Influenza|last2=Sellwood|first2=Chloe|date=2010|publisher=CABI|location=Wallingford, Oxford|isbn=978-1-84593-625-9|language=en}}</ref> is a formal declaration by the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) of \"an extraordinary event which is determined to constitute a public health risk to other States through the international spread of disease and to potentially require a coordinated international response\", formulated when a situation arises that is \"serious, sudden, unusual or unexpected\", which \"carries implications for public health beyond the affected state's national border\" and \"may require immediate international action\".<ref name=WHOIHR1>WHO Q&A (19 June 2019). {{Cite web|url=http://www.who.int/features/qa/emergency-committees/en/|title= International Health Regulations and Emergency Committees|website=WHO|access-date=19 June 2019}}</ref> Under the 2005 [[International Health Regulations]] (IHR), states have a legal duty to respond promptly to a PHEIC.<ref name=\"urlInside Justice-WHO-PHEIC\"/> The declaration is publicized by an Emergency Committee (EC) made up of international experts operating under the IHR (2005),<ref name=\"WHO-IHR2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.who.int/ihr/about/en/|title=Strengthening health security by implementing the International Health Regulations (2005); About IHR|publisher=WHO|access-date=19 June 2019}}</ref> which was developed following the [[Timeline of the SARS outbreak|SARS outbreak]] of 2002\u201303.<ref name=\"Hoffman2018\" />\n\nSince 2009 there have been six PHEIC declarations:<ref name=\"WashPost2016\">{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/monkey-cage/wp/2016/02/02/who-declared-a-public-health-emergency-about-zikas-effects-here-are-three-takeaways/|title=WHO declared a public health emergency about Zika's effects. Here are three takeaways|last=Pillinger|first=Mara|date=2 February 2016|access-date=19 June 2019|work=Washington Post}}{{subscription required}}</ref> the [[2009 flu pandemic|2009 H1N1 (or swine flu) pandemic]], the [[Poliomyelitis eradication#2011\u20132015|2014 polio declaration]], the [[2014 West Africa Ebola outbreak|2014 outbreak of Ebola in Western Africa]], the [[2015\u201316 Zika virus epidemic]],<ref name=\"Hunger2018\"/> the ongoing [[Kivu Ebola epidemic|2018\u201320 Kivu Ebola epidemic]],<ref name=\"WHO18Oct2019\"/> and the ongoing [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]].<ref name=\"WHOStatement30January2020\">WHO Statement (31 January 2020). {{Cite web|url=https://www.who.int/news-room/detail/30-01-2020-statement-on-the-second-meeting-of-the-international-health-regulations-(2005)-emergency-committee-regarding-the-outbreak-of-novel-coronavirus-(2019-ncov)|title=Statement on the second meeting of the International Health Regulations (2005) Emergency Committee regarding the outbreak of novel coronavirus (2019-nCoV)|last=|first=|date=31 January 2020|website=World Health Organisation|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=6 February 2020}}</ref> The recommendations are temporary and require reviews every three months.<ref name=WHOIHR1/>\n\n[[Severe acute respiratory syndrome|SARS]], [[smallpox]], [[wild type]] [[poliomyelitis]], and any new subtype of [[human influenza]] are automatically PHEICs and thus do not require an IHR decision to declare them as such.<ref name=Hall2018>{{cite book|author1=Mark A. Hall|author2=David Orentlicher|author3=Mary Anne Bobinski|author4=Nicholas Bagley|author5=I. Glenn Cohen|title=Health Care Law and Ethics|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mwJODwAAQBAJ&pg=PA908|edition=9th|year= 2018|publisher=Wolters Kluwer |location=New York|isbn=978-1-4548-8180-3|page=908|chapter=8. Public Health Law}}</ref> A PHEIC is not confined to infectious diseases, and may cover an emergency caused by exposure to a chemical agent or radioactive material.<ref name=Halabi2017>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=nvzmDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA110 |title=Global Management of Infectious Disease After Ebola|last=Halabi|first=Sam F.|last2=Crowley|first2=Jeffrey S.|last3=Gostin|first3=Lawrence Ogalthorpe|date=2017|publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]|isbn=978-0190604882|location=|pages=110|language=en}}</ref> In any case within its ambit, it is a \"call to action\" and \"last resort\" measure.<ref name=\"Rull2015\">{{Cite journal|last=Rull|first=Monica|last2=Kickbusch|first2=Ilona|last3=Lauer|first3=Helen|date=8 December 2015|title=Policy Debate {{!}} International Responses to Global Epidemics: Ebola and Beyond|journal=International Development Policy|language=en|volume=6|issue=2|doi=10.4000/poldev.2178|issn=1663-9375|doi-access=free}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\nMultiple surveillance and response systems exist worldwide for the early detection and effective response to contain the spread of disease. Time delays still occur for two main reasons, however. The first is the delay between the [[index case|first case]] and the confirmation of the outbreak by the healthcare system, allayed by good surveillance via data collection, evaluation, and organisation. The second is when there is a delay between the detection of the outbreak and widespread recognition and declaration of it as an international concern.<ref name=\"Hoffman2018\" /> The declaration is promulgated by an Emergency Committee (EC) made up of international experts operating under the IHR (2005),<ref name=\"WHO-IHR2\"/> which was developed following the [[Timeline of the SARS outbreak|SARS outbreak]] of 2002/2003.<ref name=\"Hoffman2018\" /> Between 2009 and 2016, there were four PHEIC declarations.<ref name=\"WashPost2016\"/> The fifth was the 2018\u201320 Kivu Ebola epidemic which was announced on 17 July 2019.<ref name=\"WHO18Oct2019\"/> The sixth is the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|2019\u201320 novel coronavirus pandemic]].<ref name=\"WHOStatement30January2020\"/> Under the 2005 [[International Health Regulations]] (IHR), States have a legal duty to respond promptly to a PHEIC.<ref name=\"urlInside Justice-WHO-PHEIC\"/>\n\n==Definition==\nPHEIC is defined as; <blockquote>an extraordinary event which is determined to constitute a public health risk to other States through the international spread of disease and to potentially require a coordinated international response<ref name=WHO2016>WHO Regulations (2005). {{Cite web|url=http://www.who.int/ihr/annex_2/en/|title= Annex 2 of the International Health Regulations (2005)|website=WHO|access-date=6 February 2020}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nThis definition designates a [[public health crisis]] of potentially global reach and implies a situation that is \"serious, sudden, unusual or unexpected\", which may necessitate immediate international action.<ref name=WHO2016/><ref name=Exter2015>{{Cite book|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FhMACwAAQBAJ&pg=PA540|title=International Health Law and Ethics: Basic Documents|last=Exter|first=Andr\u00e9 den|date=2015|publisher=Maklu|isbn=978-9046607923|edition=3rd|series=|location=|pages=540|language=en|chapter=Part VI Public Health; Chapter 1.1 International Health Regulations (2005)}}</ref>\n\nIt is a \"call to action\" and \"last resort\" measure.<ref name=\"Rull2015\"/>\n\n==Reporting a potential concern==\nWHO Member States have 24 hours within which to report potential PHEIC events to the WHO.<ref name=Hall2018/> It does not have to be a member State that reports a potential outbreak, hence reports to the WHO can also be received informally.<ref name=Davies2015/>\nUnder the IHR (2005), ways to detect, evaluate, notify and report events were ascertained by all countries in order to avoid PHEICs. The response to public health risks was also decided.<ref name=Rull2015/>\n\nThe IHR decision algorithm assists WHO Member States in deciding whether a potential PHEIC exists and the WHO should be notified. The WHO should be notified if any two of the four following questions are affirmed:<ref name=Hall2018/>\n*Is the public health impact of the event serious?\n*Is the event unusual or unexpected?\n*Is there a significant risk for international spread?\n*Is there a significant risk for international travel or trade restrictions?\n\nThe PHEIC criteria include a list of diseases that are always notifiable.<ref name=Davies2015>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=kvvVBgAAQBAJ&pg=PA61 |title=Disease Diplomacy: International Norms and Global Health Security|last=Davies|first=Sara E.|last2=Kamradt-Scott|first2=Adam|last3=Rushton|first3=Simon|date=2015|publisher=[[Johns Hopkins University Press]]|isbn=9781421416489|language=en}}</ref> [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome|SARS]], [[smallpox]], [[wild type]] [[poliomyelitis]] and any new subtype of [[human influenza]] are always a PHEIC and do not require an IHR decision to declare them as such.<ref name=WHO2016/>\n\nQuotidian epidemics which public attention do fulfill the criteria to be a PHEIC.<ref name=\"Rull2015\"/> EC's were not convened for the [[2010s Haiti cholera outbreak|cholera outbreak in Haiti]], [[Ghouta chemical attack|chemical weapons use in Syria]] or the [[Fukushima Daiichi nuclear disaster|Fukushima nuclear disaster in Japan]], for example.<ref name=Halabi2017/><ref name=Gostin2016/>\n\nFurther assessment is required for diseases which are prone to [[pandemic]]s, including but not limited to [[cholera]], [[pneumonic plague]], [[yellow fever]], and viral hemorrhagic fevers.<ref name=Gostin2016/>\n\nA declaration of a PHEIC may appear as an economic burden to the state facing the epidemic. Incentives to declare an epidemic are lacking and the PHEIC can be seen as placing limitations on trade in countries that are already struggling.<ref name=Rull2015/>\n\n==Emergency committee==\nIn order to declare a PHEIC, the [[WHO#Director-General|WHO Director-General]] is required to take into account factors which include the risk to human health and international spread as well as advice from an internationally made up committee of experts, the IHR Emergency Committee (EC), one of which should be an expert nominated by the State within whose region the event arises.<ref name=WHOIHR1/> Rather than being a standing committee, the EC is created [[ad hoc]].<ref name=Kamradt-Scott2019>{{Cite journal|last=Kamradt-Scott|first=Adam|last2=Eccleston-Turner|first2=Mark|date=1 April 2019|title=Transparency in IHR emergency committee decision making: the case for reform|url=https://gh.bmj.com/content/4/2/e001618|journal=British Medical Journal Global Health|language=en|volume=4|issue=2|pages=e001618|doi=10.1136/bmjgh-2019-001618|pmid=31139463|pmc=6509695|issn=2059-7908|via=}}</ref>\n\nUntil 2011, the names of IHR EC members were not publicly disclosed. These members are selected according to the disease in question and the nature of the event. The Director-General takes the EC's advice following their technical assessment of the crisis using legal criteria and a predetermined algorithm after a review of all available data on the event. Upon declaration, the EC then makes recommendations on what actions the Director-General and Member States should take to address the crisis.<ref name=Kamradt-Scott2019/> The recommendations are temporary and require three-monthly reviews.<ref name=WHOIHR1/>\n\n==Declarations==\n[[File:H1N1 influenza virus.jpg|thumb|upright|H1N1 influenza virus]]\n\n===2009 swine flu declaration===\nIn the spring of 2009, a novel influenza A (H1N1) virus emerged. It was detected first in the United States of America and spread quickly across the United States and the world.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cdc.gov/flu/pandemic-resources/2009-h1n1-pandemic.html|title=2009 H1N1 Pandemic|last=CDC|date=2019-06-11|website=Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|language=en-us|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref> On 26 April 2009,<ref name=H1N12009WHO>{{Cite book|url=http://apps.who.int/gb/ebwha/pdf_files/WHA64/A64_10-en.pdf|title=Implementation of the International Health Regulations (2005), Report of the Review Committee on the Functioning of the International Health Regulations (2005) in relation to Pandemic (H1N1) 2009|last=Director-General|publisher=WHO|year=2009|isbn=|location=|pages=118}}</ref> more than one month after its first emergence,<ref name=\"Hoffman2018\">{{Cite journal|last=Hoffman|first=Steven J.|last2=Silverberg|first2=Sarah L.|date=18 January 2018|title=Delays in Global Disease Outbreak Responses: Lessons from H1N1, Ebola, and Zika|journal=[[American Journal of Public Health]]|volume=108|issue=3|pages=329\u2013333|doi=10.2105/AJPH.2017.304245|pmid=29345996|pmc=5803810|issn=0090-0036}}</ref> the first PHEIC was declared when the [[2009 flu pandemic|H1N1 (or swine flu) pandemic]] was still in [[Influenza pandemic#Phases|Phase Three]].<ref name=\"urlInside Justice-WHO-PHEIC\">{{cite web| url = http://www.insidejustice.com/intl/2009/04/30/swine_flu_who_pheic/| title = Inside Justice &#124; Swine Flu: Legal Obligations and Consequences When the World Health Organization Declares a \"Public Health Emergency of International Concern\"| author =  Renee Dopplick| date = 29 April 2009| accessdate = 6 June 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"urlWHO | Swine influenza\">{{cite web| url = http://www.who.int/mediacentre/news/statements/2009/h1n1_20090425/en/\n| title = Swine influenza| author = Margaret Chan | date = 25 April 2009| publisher = [[World Health Organization]]| accessdate = 6 June 2014| author-link = Margaret Chan}}</ref><ref name=\"urlWHO | Swine flu illness in the United States and Mexico - update 2\">{{cite web| url = http://www.who.int/csr/don/2009_04_26/en/| title = Swine flu illness in the United States and Mexico \u2013 update 2| author = | date = 26 April 2009| publisher = [[World Health Organization]]| accessdate = 6 June 2014}}</ref> On the same day, within three hours the WHO web site received almost two million visits, necessitating the pandemic's own dedicated pandemic influenza web site.<ref name=H1N12009WHO/> At the time H1N1 had been declared a PHEIC, it had so far occurred in only three countries.<ref name=\"Hoffman2018\" /> Declaring H1N1 a PHEIC has therefore been argued as fueling public fear.<ref name=\"Gostin2016\">{{Cite journal|last=Gostin|first=Lawrence O.|last2=Katz|first2=Rebeccas|author-link2=Rebecca Katz|date=June 2016|title=The International Health Regulations: The Governing Framework for Global Health Security|url=|journal=The Milbank Quarterly|volume=94|issue=2|pages=264\u2013313|doi=10.1111/1468-0009.12186|pmc=4911720|pmid=27166578|via=}}</ref> However, a 2013 study sponsored by the WHO estimated that although the H1N1 pandemic was similar in magnitude to seasonal influenza, it resulted in the loss of more life-years due to a shift toward mortality among persons less than 65 years of age.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Simonsen |first=Lone |last2=Spreeuwenberg |first2=Peter |last3=Lustig |first3=Roger |last4=Taylor |first4=Robert J. |last5=Fleming |first5=Douglas M. |last6=Kroneman |first6=Madelon |last7=Van Kerkhove |first7=Maria D. |last8=Mounts |first8=Anthony W. |last9=Paget |first9=W. John |last10=Hay |first10=Simon I. |title=Global Mortality Estimates for the 2009 Influenza Pandemic from the GLaMOR Project: A Modeling Study |journal=[[PLOS Medicine]] |date=26 November 2013 |volume=10 |issue=11 |pages=e1001558 |doi=10.1371/journal.pmed.1001558 |pmid=24302890 |pmc=3841239}}</ref>\n\n===2014 polio declaration===\nThe second PHEIC was the [[Poliomyelitis eradication#2011\u20132015|2014 polio declaration]], issued in May 2014 with the resurgence of [[poliomyelitis|wild polio]] after its near-eradication, deemed \"an extraordinary event\".<ref name=\"urlWHO-IHREC-wild poliovirus\">{{cite web\n| url = http://www.who.int/mediacentre/news/statements/2014/polio-20140505/en/\n| title = WHO &#124; WHO statement on the meeting of the International Health Regulations Emergency Committee concerning the international spread of wild poliovirus\n| author = \n| date = 5 May 2014\n| publisher = [[World Health Organization]]\n| accessdate = 6 June 2014\n}}</ref><ref name=\"urlNewScientist-polio cases surge-2014-0505\">{{cite web\n| url = https://www.newscientist.com/article/dn25518-global-emergency-declared-as-polio-cases-surge.html\n| title = Global emergency declared as polio cases surge \u2013 health \u2013 05 May 2014 \u2013 New Scientist\n| first =  Debora\n| last = MacKenzie\n| date = 5 May 2014\n| publisher = New Scientist\n| accessdate = 6 June 2014\n}}</ref>\n\nGlobal eradication was deemed to be at risk with small numbers of cases in Afghanistan, Pakistan, and Nigeria.<ref name=Gostin2016/>\n\nIn October 2019, continuing cases of wild polio in Pakistan and Afghanistan, in addition to new vaccine-derived cases in Africa and Asia, was reviewed and remains a PHEIC.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cidrap.umn.edu/news-perspective/2019/10/news-scan-oct-04-2019|title=News Scan: Polio in Pakistan|last=|first=|date=4 October 2019|website=CIDRAP|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=10 October 2019}}</ref> It was extended on 11 December 2019.<ref name=THP11Dec2019>{{Cite web|url=https://travelhealthpro.org.uk/news/483/polio-public-health-emergency-of-international-concern|title=NaTHNaC - Polio: Public Health Emergency of International Concern|last=|first=|date=|website=TravelHealthPro|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=13 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n===2014 Ebola declaration===\nConfirmed cases of Ebola were being reported in Guinea and Liberia in March 2014 and Sierra Leone by May 2014. On Friday, 8 August 2014, following the occurrence of Ebola in the United States and Europe and with the already intense transmission ongoing in three other countries for months,<ref name=Rull2015/> the WHO declared its third PHEIC in response to the [[2014 West Africa Ebola outbreak|outbreak of Ebola in Western Africa]].<ref name=WHO2014>{{Cite web|url=http://www.euro.who.int/en/health-topics/emergencies/pages/news/news/2014/08/ebola-outbreak-in-west-africa-declared-a-public-health-emergency-of-international-concern|title=Ebola outbreak in West Africa declared a public health emergency of international concern|date=8 August 2014|website=www.euro.who.int|language=en|access-date=3 June 2019}}</ref> Later, one review showed that a direct impact of this epidemic on America escalated a PHEIC declaration.<ref name=\"Hoffman2018\" /> It was the first PHEIC in a resource-poor setting.<ref name=Rull2015/>\n\n===2016 Zika virus declaration===\nOn 1 February 2016, the WHO declared its fourth PHEIC in response to clusters of [[microcephaly]] and [[Guillain\u2013Barr\u00e9 syndrome]] in the [[Americas]], which at the time were suspected to be associated with the ongoing [[2015\u201316 Zika virus epidemic]].<ref>WHO (1 February 2016). [http://www.who.int/mediacentre/news/statements/2016/emergency-committee-zika-microcephaly/en/ WHO Director-General summarizes the outcome of the Emergency Committee on Zika]</ref> Later research and evidence bore out these concerns; in April, the WHO stated that \"there is scientific consensus that Zika virus is a cause of microcephaly and Guillain\u2013Barr\u00e9 syndrome.\"<ref name=\"WHO SitRep 7 Apr 2016\">{{cite web | url=http://apps.who.int/iris/bitstream/10665/204961/1/zikasitrep_7Apr2016_eng.pdf?ua=1 | title=Zika Virus Microcephaly And Guillain\u2013Barr\u00e9 Syndrome Situation Report | publisher=World Health Organization | date=7 April 2016 | accessdate=12 May 2016}}</ref>  This was the first time a PHEIC was declared for a [[Mosquito-borne disease|mosquito\u2010borne disease]].<ref name=Gostin2016/> This declaration was lifted on 18 November 2016.<ref>{{cite web|title=Fifth meeting of the Emergency Committee under the International Health Regulations (2005) regarding microcephaly, other neurological disorders and Zika virus|url=http://www.who.int/mediacentre/news/statements/2016/zika-fifth-ec/en/|website=World Health Organization|publisher=WHO|accessdate=1 December 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== 2018\u201320 Kivu Ebola declaration ===\nIn October 2018 and then later in April 2019, the WHO did not consider the [[2018\u201320 Kivu Ebola epidemic]] to be a PHEIC.<ref name=\"Green20April2019\">{{Cite journal|last=Green|first=Andrew|date=20 April 2019|title=DR Congo Ebola outbreak not given PHEIC designation|journal=The Lancet|volume=393|issue=10181|pages=1586|doi=10.1016/S0140-6736(19)30893-1|pmid=31007190}}</ref><ref name=\"PHEICApril2019\">{{cite web|url=https://www.who.int/news-room/detail/12-04-2019-statement-on-the-meeting-of-the-international-health-regulations-(2005)-emergency-committee-for-ebola-virus-disease-in-the-democratic-republic-of-the-congo-on-12th-april-2019|title=Statement on the meeting of the International Health Regulations (2005) Emergency Committee for Ebola virus disease in the Democratic Republic of the Congo on 12th April 2019|date=12 April 2019|publisher=World Health Organization|accessdate=13 June 2019}}</ref> The decision was controversial, with [[Michael Osterholm]], director of the [[Center for Infectious Disease Research and Policy]] (CIDRAP) responding with disappointment and describing the situation as \"an Ebola gas can sitting in DRC that's just waiting for a match to hit it\",<ref name=\"Cohen2019\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.sciencemag.org/news/2019/04/ebola-outbreak-congo-still-not-international-crisis-who-decides|title=Ebola outbreak in Congo still not an international crisis, WHO decides|last=Cohen|first=Jon|last2=2019|date=12 April 2019|website=Science {{!}} AAAS|language=en|access-date=18 June 2019}}</ref> while the WHO panel were unanimous that declaring it a PHEIC would not give any added benefit.<ref name=\"Cohen2019\" /> The advice against declaring a PHEIC in October 2018 and April 2019, despite the criteria for doing so appearing to be met on both occasions has led to the transparency of the IHR EC coming into question. The language used in the statements for the Kivu Ebola epidemic has been noted to be different. In October 2018, the EC stated \"a PHEIC should not be declared at this time\". However, in the 13 previously declined proposals for declaring a PHEIC, the resultant statements quoted \"the conditions for a PHEIC are not currently met\" and \"does not constitute a PHEIC\". In April 2019, they stated that \"there is no added benefit to declaring a PHEIC at this stage\", a notion that is not part of the PHEIC criteria laid down in the IHR.<ref name=\"Kamradt-Scott2019\" /><ref name=\"Lancet2019\">{{Cite journal|last=Lancet|first=The|date=25 May 2019|title=Acknowledging the limits of public health solutions|url=https://www.thelancet.com/journals/lancet/article/PIIS0140-6736(19)31183-3/abstract|journal=The Lancet|language=English|volume=393|issue=10186|pages=2100|doi=10.1016/S0140-6736(19)31183-3|issn=0140-6736|pmid=31226033|doi-access=free}}</ref>\n\nAfter confirmed cases of Ebola in neighbouring Uganda in June 2019, [[Tedros Adhanom]], the Director-General of the WHO, announced that the third meeting of a group of experts would be held on 14 June 2019 to assess whether the Ebola spread had become a PHEIC.<ref name=\"Hunt2019\">{{cite web|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2019/06/12/health/ebola-outbreak-death-uganda-africa-intl-bn/index.html|title=Ebola outbreak enters 'truly frightening phase' as it turns deadly in Uganda|last=Hunt|first=Katie|website=CNN|language=en|accessdate=12 June 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"NYTimes14June2019\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/12/world/africa/ebola-uganda-congo.html|title=Boy, 5, and Grandmother Die in Uganda as More Ebola Cases Emerge|last=Gladstone|first=Rick|date=12 June 2019|work=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=14 June 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The conclusion was that while the outbreak was a health emergency in the [[Democratic Republic of the Congo]] (DRC) and the region, it does not meet all the three criteria for a PHEIC.<ref name=\"WHO14June2019\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.who.int/news-room/detail/14-06-2019-statement-on-the-meeting-of-the-international-health-regulations-(2005)-emergency-committee-for-ebola-virus-disease-in-the-democratic-republic-of-the-congo|title=Statement on the meeting of the International Health Regulations (2005) Emergency Committee for Ebola virus disease in the Democratic Republic of the Congo on 14 June 2019|last=|first=|date=|website=World Health Organization|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=14 June 2019}}</ref> Despite the number of deaths reaching 1,405 by 11 June 2019 and 1,440 by 17 June 2019, the reason for not declaring a PHIEC was that the overall risk of international spread was deemed to be low, and the risk of damaging the economy of the DRC high.<ref name=\"SoucharyJune2019\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.cidrap.umn.edu/news-perspective/2019/06/ebola-case-counts-spike-again-drc|title=Ebola case counts spike again in DRC|last=Souchary|first=Stephanie|date=17 June 2019|website=CIDRAP|language=en|access-date=24 June 2019}}</ref> Adhanom also stated that declaring a PHEIC would be an inappropriate way to raise money for the epidemic.<ref name=\"CIDRAP16July2019\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.cidrap.umn.edu/news-perspective/2019/07/who-will-take-ebola-emergency-declaration-question-fourth-time|title=WHO will take up Ebola emergency declaration question for a fourth time|last=Soucheray|first=Stephanie|last2=2019|date=16 July 2019|website=CIDRAP|language=en|access-date=17 July 2019}}</ref> Following a visit to the DRC in July 2019, [[Rory Stewart]], the UK's [[Department for International Development|DfID]] minister, called for the WHO to declare it an emergency.<ref name=\"Wintour9July2019\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/jul/07/declare-ebola-outbreak-in-drc-an-emergency-says-uks-rory-stewart|title=Declare Ebola outbreak in DRC an emergency, says UK's Rory Stewart|last=Wintour|first=Patrick|date=7 July 2019|work=The Guardian|access-date=9 July 2019|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\nAcknowledging a high risk of spread to the capital of North Kivu, [[Goma]], a call for a PHEIC declaration was published on 10 July 2019 in the ''[[Washington Post]]'' by [[Daniel R. Lucey|Daniel Lucey]] and [[Ron Klain]] (the former US [[Ebola response coordinator]]). They stated that  \"in the absence of a trajectory toward extinguishing the outbreak, the opposite path\u2014severe escalation\u2014remains possible. The risk of the disease moving into nearby Goma, Congo\u2014a city of 1 million residents with an international airport \u2014or crossing into the massive refugee camps in South Sudan is mounting. With a limited number of vaccine doses remaining, either would be a catastrophe\".<ref name=\"Soucheray11July2019\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.cidrap.umn.edu/news-perspective/2019/07/three-more-health-workers-infected-ebola-outbreak|title=Three more health workers infected in Ebola outbreak|last=Soucheray|first=Stephanie|date=11 July 2019|website=CIDRAP|language=en|access-date=16 July 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Klain10July2019\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/its-time-to-declare-a-public-health-emergency-on-ebola/2019/07/10/c77641fc-a327-11e9-b732-41a79c2551bf_story.html|title=Opinion {{!}} It's time to declare a public health emergency on Ebola|last=Klain|first=Ronald A.|last2=Lucey|first2=Daniel|date=10 July 2019|website=Washington Post|language=en|access-date=16 July 2019}}</ref> Four days later, on 14 July 2019, a case of Ebola was confirmed in Goma, which has an international airport and a highly mobile population. Subsequently, the WHO announced a reconvening of a fourth EC meeting on 17 July 2019, when they officially announced it \"a regional emergency, and by no means a global threat\" and declared it as a PHEIC, without restrictions on trade or travel.<ref name=\"WHONewsRelease17July2019\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.who.int/news-room/detail/17-07-2019-ebola-outbreak-in-the-democratic-republic-of-the-congo-declared-a-public-health-emergency-of-international-concern|title=Ebola outbreak in the Democratic Republic of the Congo declared a Public Health Emergency of International Concern|last=|first=|date=2019-07-17|website=World Health Organization|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-31}}</ref><ref name=BBCNews17July2019>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/health-49025298|title=Ebola outbreak declared public health emergency|last=|first=|date=17 July 2019|work=BBC News|access-date=17 July 2019|language=en-GB}}</ref> In response to the declaration, the president of the DRC, together with an expert committee led by a virologist, took responsibility for directly supervising action, while in protest of the declaration, health minister, [[Oly Ilunga Kalenga]] resigned.<ref name=Schnirring22July2019>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cidrap.umn.edu/news-perspective/2019/07/drc-health-minister-resigns-after-government-takes-ebola-reins|title=DRC health minister resigns after government takes Ebola reins|last=Schnirring|first=Lisa|date=22 July 2019|website=CIDRAP|language=en|access-date=26 July 2019}}</ref> A review of the PHEIC had been planned at a fifth meeting of the EC on 10 October 2019<ref name=9Oct2019>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cidrap.umn.edu/news-perspective/2019/10/response-resumes-following-security-problems-drc-ebola-hot-spot|title=Response resumes following security problems in DRC Ebola hot spot|last=Schnirring|first=Lisa|last2=9 October 2019|date=|website=CIDRAP|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=10 October 2019}}</ref> and as of 18 October 2019, it continues to be a PHEIC.<ref name=\"WHO18Oct2019\">WHO Statement (18 October 2019). {{Cite web|url=https://www.who.int/news-room/detail/18-10-2019-statement-on-the-meeting-of-the-international-health-regulations-(2005)-emergency-committee-for-ebola-virus-disease-in-the-democratic-republic-of-the-congo|title=Statement on the meeting of the International Health Regulations (2005) Emergency Committee for Ebola virus disease in the Democratic Republic of the Congo on 18 October 2019|last=|first=|date=|website=www.who.int|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=21 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== 2019 coronavirus pandemic (COVID-19) ===\n[[File:2019-nCoV-CDC-23312.png|thumb|right|Morphology of SARS-CoV-2]]\nOn 30 January 2020, the WHO declared the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|outbreak of COVID-19]], centered on [[Wuhan]] in [[central China]], a PHEIC.<ref name=\"WHOStatement30January2020\" /><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/01/30/health/coronavirus-world-health-organization.html |title=W.H.O. Declares Global Emergency as the new Coronavirus Spreads |last=Ramzy |first=Austin |date=2020-01-30 |work=The New York Times |access-date=2020-01-30 |last2=Jr |first2=Donald G. McNeil |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331}}</ref> On the date of the declaration, there were 7,818 cases confirmed globally, affecting 19 countries in five WHO regions.<ref>WHO Report (30 January 2020). {{cite web |url=https://www.who.int/docs/default-source/coronaviruse/situation-reports/20200130-sitrep-10-ncov.pdf?sfvrsn=d0b2e480_2 |title=Novel Coronavirus(2019-nCoV): Situation Report-10 |publisher=WHO |date=30 January 2020 |accessdate=30 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.who.int/news-room/detail/30-01-2020-statement-on-the-second-meeting-of-the-international-health-regulations-(2005)-emergency-committee-regarding-the-outbreak-of-novel-coronavirus-(2019-ncov) |title=Statement on the second meeting of the International Health Regulations (2005) Emergency Committee regarding the outbreak of novel coronavirus (2019-nCoV) |publisher=WHO |date=30 January 2020 |accessdate=30 January 2020}}</ref> Previously, the WHO had held EC meetings on 22 and 23 January 2020 regarding the coronavirus pandemic,<ref name=Fifield23Jan2020>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/nine-dead-as-chinese-coronavirus-spreads-despite-efforts-to-contain-it/2020/01/22/1eaade72-3c6d-11ea-afe2-090eb37b60b1_story.html|title=Nine dead as Chinese coronavirus spreads, despite efforts to contain it|last=Fifield|first=Anna|last2=Sun|first2=Lena H. |date=23 January 2020|work=The Washington Post|access-date=6 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=Schnirring22Jan2020>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cidrap.umn.edu/news-perspective/2020/01/who-decision-ncov-emergency-delayed-cases-spike|title=WHO decision on nCoV emergency delayed as cases spike|last=Schnirring|first=Lisa|date=22 January 2020|website=CIDRAP|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=23 January 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"WHO22Jan2020\">WHO Statement (22 January 2020). {{Cite web|url=https://www.who.int/dg/speeches/detail/who-director-general-s-statement-on-ihr-emergency-committee-on-novel-coronavirus|title=WHO Director-General's statement on IHR Emergency Committee on Novel Coronavirus|last=|first=|date=22 January 2020|website=www.who.int|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=23 January 2020}}</ref> but it was determined that it was too early to declare a PHEIC  at that time given the lack of necessary data and the (then) scale of global impact.<ref name=\"StatNews\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.statnews.com/2020/01/23/who-declines-to-declare-china-virus-outbreak-a-global-health-emergency/|title=WHO declines to declare China virus outbreak a global health emergency|last=Joseph|first=Andrew|date=23 January 2020|website=STAT|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=23 January 2020}}</ref><ref name=WHO23Jan2020>WHO Statement (23 January 2020). {{Cite web|url=https://www.who.int/news-room/detail/23-01-2020-statement-on-the-meeting-of-the-international-health-regulations-(2005)-emergency-committee-regarding-the-outbreak-of-novel-coronavirus-(2019-ncov)|title=Statement on the meeting of the International Health Regulations (2005) Emergency Committee regarding the outbreak of novel coronavirus 2019 (n-CoV) on 23 January 2020|last=|first=|date=|website=www.who.int|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=23 January 2020}}</ref> The WHO recognized the spread of [[COVID-19]] as a [[pandemic]] on 11 March 2020.<ref name=\"WHOpandemic1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.who.int/dg/speeches/detail/who-director-general-s-opening-remarks-at-the-media-briefing-on-covid-19---11-march-2020|title=WHO Director-General's opening remarks at the media briefing on COVID-19 \u2013 11 March 2020|date=20 March 2020|publisher=[[World Health Organization]]|access-date=11 March 2020}}</ref> Europe, Iran, USA, South Korea and Japan reported a surging of cases and the total number quickly passed China.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gisanddata.maps.arcgis.com/apps/opsdashboard/index.html#/bda7594740fd40299423467b48e9ecf6|title=Operations Dashboard for ArcGIS|website=gisanddata.maps.arcgis.com|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref>\n\n==Response==\nIn 2018, an examination of the first four declarations (2009\u20132016) showed that the WHO was noted to be more effective in responding to international health emergencies, and that the international system in dealing with these emergencies was \"robust\".<ref name=\"Hunger2018\">{{Cite book|url=https://www.oxfordscholarship.com/view/10.1093/oso/9780198828945.001.0001/oso-9780198828945-chapter-4|title=Coping with Public Health Emergencies of International Concern|volume=1|last=Hunger|first=Iris|date=2018|publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]|isbn=9780191867422|location=|pages=|language=en-US|doi=10.1093/oso/9780198828945.003.0004}}{{subscription required}}</ref>\n\nAnother review of the first four declarations, with the exception of wild polio, demonstrated that responses were varied. Severe outbreaks, or those that threatened larger numbers of people, did not receive a swift PHEIC declaration, and the study hypothesized that responses were quicker when American citizens were infected and when the emergencies did not coincide with holidays.<ref name=Hoffman2018/>\n\n==Non-declarations==\n[[File:Mers-virus-3D-image.jpg|thumb|MERS-coronavirus]]\n\n===2013 MERS===\nPHEIC was not invoked with the [[Middle Eastern Respiratory Syndrome]] (MERS) outbreak in 2013.<ref name=\"urlMERS - The Global Dispatch\">{{cite web\n| url = http://www.theglobaldispatch.com/mers-does-not-constitute-a-public-health-emergency-of-international-concern-pheic-emergency-committee-32451/\n| title = MERS does not constitute a Public Health Emergency of International Concern (PHEIC): Emergency committee \u2013 The Global Dispatc\n| author =  Robert Herriman\n| date = 17 July 2013\n| publisher = The Global Dispatch\n| accessdate = 6 June 2014\n}}</ref><ref name=\"urlWHO-2IHRECV-MERS-CoV\">{{cite web\n| url = http://centerforvaccineethicsandpolicy.net/2013/07/20/who-statement-second-meeting-of-the-ihr-emergency-committee-concerning-mers-cov-pheic-conditions-not-met/\n| title = WHO Statement: Second Meeting of the IHR Emergency Committee concerning MERS-CoV \u2013 PHEIC Conditions Not Met &#124; global vaccine ethics and policy\n| author = David R Curry\n| date = 20 July 2013\n| publisher = Center for Vaccine Ethics and Policy\n| accessdate = 6 June 2014\n}}</ref> Originating in Saudi Arabia, MERS reached more than 24 countries and resulted in more than 580 deaths by 2015, although most cases were in hospital settings rather than sustained community spread. What constitutes a PHEIC has, as a result, been unclear.<ref name=Halabi2017/>\n\n== Non-infectious events ==\nPHEIC are not confined to only infectious diseases. It may cover events caused by chemical agents or radioactive materials.<ref name=Halabi2017/>\n\nThe emergence and spread of [[antimicrobial resistance]] may debatably constitute a PHEIC.<ref name=AMR>{{Cite web|url=https://medicalxpress.com/news/2011-04-international-health-antimicrobial-resistance.html|title=Can the International Health Regulations apply to antimicrobial resistance?|website=medicalxpress.com|language=en-us|access-date=15 June 2019}}</ref><ref name=Wernli2011>{{Cite journal|last=Wernli|first=Didier|last2=Haustein|first2=Thomas|last3=Conly|first3=John|last4=Carmeli|first4=Yehuda|last5=Kickbusch|first5=Ilona|last6=Harbarth|first6=Stephan|date=April 2011|title=A call for action: the application of The International Health Regulations to the global threat of antimicrobial resistance|journal=[[PLOS Medicine]]|volume=8|issue=4|pages=e1001022|doi=10.1371/journal.pmed.1001022|issn=1549-1676|pmc=3079636|pmid=21526227}}</ref><ref name=Kamradt-Scott2011>{{Cite journal|last=Kamradt-Scott|first=Adam|date=19 April 2011|title=A Public Health Emergency of International Concern? Response to a Proposal to Apply the International Health Regulations to Antimicrobial Resistance|journal=PLOS Medicine|language=en|volume=8|issue=4|pages=e1001021|doi=10.1371/journal.pmed.1001021|pmid=21526165|pmc=3080965|issn=1549-1676}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Biosecurity]]\n*[[Disease X]]\n*[[Notifiable disease]]\n*[[Public health emergency (United States)]]\n*[[State of emergency]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*[https://www.who.int/news-room/detail/20-12-2019-statement-o-the-twenty-third-ihr-emergency-committee-regarding-the-international-spread-of-poliovirus Statement of the Twenty-Third IHR Emergency Committee Regarding the International Spread of Poliovirus]. WHO 7 January 2020\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Politics|Viruses|right=yes}}\n*[https://www.who.int/features/qa/emergency-committees/en/ International Health Regulations and Emergency Committees]. www.who.int \n\n{{PHEIC}}\n{{Zika}}\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n\n[[Category:Public Health Emergency of International Concern| ]]\n[[Category:Global health]]\n[[Category:Health law]]\n[[Category:World Health Organization]]\n[[Category:Emergency management]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Formal declaration by the World Health Organization}} \n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n[[File:World Health Organization Logo.svg|thumb|Logo of the World Health Organization, the authority which declares PHEIC]]\nA '''Public Health Emergency of International Concern'''<ref name=Van-Tam2010>{{Cite book|last=Van-Tam|first=Jonathan|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_IYYr9cjE30C&pg=PA195|title=Introduction to Pandemic Influenza|last2=Sellwood|first2=Chloe|date=2010|publisher=CABI|location=Wallingford, Oxford|isbn=978-1-84593-625-9|language=en}}</ref> is a formal declaration by the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) of \"an extraordinary event which is determined to constitute a public health risk to other States through the international spread of disease and to potentially require a coordinated international response\", formulated when a situation arises that is \"serious, sudden, unusual or unexpected\", which \"carries implications for public health beyond the affected state's national border\" and \"may require immediate international action\".<ref name=WHOIHR1>WHO Q&A (19 June 2019). {{Cite web|url=http://www.who.int/features/qa/emergency-committees/en/|title= International Health Regulations and Emergency Committees|website=WHO|access-date=19 June 2019}}</ref> Under the 2005 [[International Health Regulations]] (IHR), states have a legal duty to respond promptly to a PHEIC.<ref name=\"urlInside Justice-WHO-PHEIC\"/> The declaration is publicized by an Emergency Committee (EC) made up of international experts operating under the IHR (2005),<ref name=\"WHO-IHR2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.who.int/ihr/about/en/|title=Strengthening health security by implementing the International Health Regulations (2005); About IHR|publisher=WHO|access-date=19 June 2019}}</ref> which was developed following the [[Timeline of the SARS outbreak|SARS outbreak]] of 2002\u201303.<ref name=\"Hoffman2018\" />\n\nSince 2009 there have been six PHEIC declarations:<ref name=\"WashPost2016\">{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/monkey-cage/wp/2016/02/02/who-declared-a-public-health-emergency-about-zikas-effects-here-are-three-takeaways/|title=WHO declared a public health emergency about Zika's effects. Here are three takeaways|last=Pillinger|first=Mara|date=2 February 2016|access-date=19 June 2019|work=Washington Post}}{{subscription required}}</ref> the [[2009 flu pandemic|2009 H1N1 (or swine flu) pandemic]], the [[Poliomyelitis eradication#2011\u20132015|2014 polio declaration]], the [[2014 West Africa Ebola outbreak|2014 outbreak of Ebola in Western Africa]], the [[2015\u201316 Zika virus epidemic]],<ref name=\"Hunger2018\"/> the ongoing [[Kivu Ebola epidemic|2018\u201320 Kivu Ebola epidemic]],<ref name=\"WHO18Oct2019\"/> and the ongoing [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]].<ref name=\"WHOStatement30January2020\">WHO Statement (31 January 2020). {{Cite web|url=https://www.who.int/news-room/detail/30-01-2020-statement-on-the-second-meeting-of-the-international-health-regulations-(2005)-emergency-committee-regarding-the-outbreak-of-novel-coronavirus-(2019-ncov)|title=Statement on the second meeting of the International Health Regulations (2005) Emergency Committee regarding the outbreak of novel coronavirus (2019-nCoV)|last=|first=|date=31 January 2020|website=World Health Organisation|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=6 February 2020}}</ref> The recommendations are temporary and require reviews every three months.<ref name=WHOIHR1/>\n\n[[Severe acute respiratory syndrome|SARS]], [[smallpox]], [[wild type]] [[poliomyelitis]], and any new subtype of [[human influenza]] are automatically PHEICs and thus do not require an IHR decision to declare them as such.<ref name=Hall2018>{{cite book|author1=Mark A. Hall|author2=David Orentlicher|author3=Mary Anne Bobinski|author4=Nicholas Bagley|author5=I. Glenn Cohen|title=Health Care Law and Ethics|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mwJODwAAQBAJ&pg=PA908|edition=9th|year= 2018|publisher=Wolters Kluwer |location=New York|isbn=978-1-4548-8180-3|page=908|chapter=8. Public Health Law}}</ref> A PHEIC is not confined to infectious diseases, and may cover an emergency caused by exposure to a chemical agent or radioactive material.<ref name=Halabi2017>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=nvzmDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA110 |title=Global Management of Infectious Disease After Ebola|last=Halabi|first=Sam F.|last2=Crowley|first2=Jeffrey S.|last3=Gostin|first3=Lawrence Ogalthorpe|date=2017|publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]|isbn=978-0190604882|location=|pages=110|language=en}}</ref> In any case within its ambit, it is a \"call to action\" and \"last resort\" measure.<ref name=\"Rull2015\">{{Cite journal|last=Rull|first=Monica|last2=Kickbusch|first2=Ilona|last3=Lauer|first3=Helen|date=8 December 2015|title=Policy Debate {{!}} International Responses to Global Epidemics: Ebola and Beyond|journal=International Development Policy|language=en|volume=6|issue=2|doi=10.4000/poldev.2178|issn=1663-9375|doi-access=free}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\nMultiple surveillance and response systems exist worldwide for the early detection and effective response to contain the spread of disease. Time delays still occur for two main reasons, however. The first is the delay between the [[index case|first case]] and the confirmation of the outbreak by the healthcare system, allayed by good surveillance via data collection, evaluation, and organisation. The second is when there is a delay between the detection of the outbreak and widespread recognition and declaration of it as an international concern.<ref name=\"Hoffman2018\" /> The declaration is promulgated by an Emergency Committee (EC) made up of international experts operating under the IHR (2005),<ref name=\"WHO-IHR2\"/> which was developed following the [[Timeline of the SARS outbreak|SARS outbreak]] of 2002/2003.<ref name=\"Hoffman2018\" /> Between 2009 and 2016, there were four PHEIC declarations.<ref name=\"WashPost2016\"/> The fifth was the 2018\u201320 Kivu Ebola epidemic which was announced on 17 July 2019.<ref name=\"WHO18Oct2019\"/> The sixth is the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|2019\u201320 novel coronavirus pandemic]].<ref name=\"WHOStatement30January2020\"/> Under the 2005 [[International Health Regulations]] (IHR), States have a legal duty to respond promptly to a PHEIC.<ref name=\"urlInside Justice-WHO-PHEIC\"/>\n\n==Definition==\nPHEIC is defined as; <blockquote>an extraordinary event which is determined to constitute a public health risk to other States through the international spread of disease and to potentially require a coordinated international response<ref name=WHO2016>WHO Regulations (2005). {{Cite web|url=http://www.who.int/ihr/annex_2/en/|title=WHO {{!}} Annex 2 of the International Health Regulations (2005)|website=WHO|access-date=6 February 2020}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nThis definition designates a [[public health crisis]] of potentially global reach and implies a situation that is \"serious, sudden, unusual or unexpected\", which may necessitate immediate international action.<ref name=WHO2016/><ref name=Exter2015>{{Cite book|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FhMACwAAQBAJ&pg=PA540|title=International Health Law and Ethics: Basic Documents|last=Exter|first=Andr\u00e9 den|date=2015|publisher=Maklu|isbn=9789046607923|edition=3rd|series=|location=|pages=540|language=en|chapter=Part VI Public Health; Chapter 1.1 International Health Regulations (2005)}}</ref>\n\nIt is a \"call to action\" and \"last resort\" measure.<ref name=\"Rull2015\"/>\n\n==Reporting a potential concern==\nWHO Member States have 24 hours within which to report potential PHEIC events to the WHO.<ref name=Hall2018/> It does not have to be a member State that reports a potential outbreak, hence reports to the WHO can also be received informally.<ref name=Davies2015/>\nUnder the IHR (2005), ways to detect, evaluate, notify and report events were ascertained by all countries in order to avoid PHEICs. The response to public health risks was also decided.<ref name=Rull2015/>\n\nThe IHR decision algorithm assists WHO Member States in deciding whether a potential PHEIC exists and the WHO should be notified. The WHO should be notified if any two of the four following questions are affirmed:<ref name=Hall2018/>\n*Is the public health impact of the event serious?\n*Is the event unusual or unexpected?\n*Is there a significant risk for international spread?\n*Is there a significant risk for international travel or trade restrictions?\n\nThe PHEIC criteria include a list of diseases that are always notifiable.<ref name=Davies2015>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=kvvVBgAAQBAJ&pg=PA61 |title=Disease Diplomacy: International Norms and Global Health Security|last=Davies|first=Sara E.|last2=Kamradt-Scott|first2=Adam|last3=Rushton|first3=Simon|date=2015|publisher=[[Johns Hopkins University Press]]|isbn=9781421416489|language=en}}</ref> [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome|SARS]], [[smallpox]], [[wild type]] [[poliomyelitis]] and any new subtype of [[human influenza]] are always a PHEIC and do not require an IHR decision to declare them as such.<ref name=WHO2016/>\n\nQuotidian epidemics which public attention do fulfill the criteria to be a PHEIC.<ref name=\"Rull2015\"/> EC's were not convened for the [[2010s Haiti cholera outbreak|cholera outbreak in Haiti]], [[Ghouta chemical attack|chemical weapons use in Syria]] or the [[Fukushima Daiichi nuclear disaster|Fukushima nuclear disaster in Japan]], for example.<ref name=Halabi2017/><ref name=Gostin2016/>\n\nFurther assessment is required for diseases which are prone to [[pandemic]]s, including but not limited to [[cholera]], [[pneumonic plague]], [[yellow fever]], and viral hemorrhagic fevers.<ref name=Gostin2016/>\n\nA declaration of a PHEIC may appear as an economic burden to the state facing the epidemic. Incentives to declare an epidemic are lacking and the PHEIC can be seen as placing limitations on trade in countries that are already struggling.<ref name=Rull2015/>\n\n==Emergency committee==\nIn order to declare a PHEIC, the [[WHO#Director-General|WHO Director-General]] is required to take into account factors which include the risk to human health and international spread as well as advice from an internationally made up committee of experts, the IHR Emergency Committee (EC), one of which should be an expert nominated by the State within whose region the event arises.<ref name=WHOIHR1/> Rather than being a standing committee, the EC is created [[ad hoc]].<ref name=Kamradt-Scott2019>{{Cite journal|last=Kamradt-Scott|first=Adam|last2=Eccleston-Turner|first2=Mark|date=1 April 2019|title=Transparency in IHR emergency committee decision making: the case for reform|url=https://gh.bmj.com/content/4/2/e001618|journal=British Medical Journal Global Health|language=en|volume=4|issue=2|pages=e001618|doi=10.1136/bmjgh-2019-001618|pmid=31139463|pmc=6509695|issn=2059-7908|via=}}</ref>\n\nUntil 2011, the names of IHR EC members were not publicly disclosed. These members are selected according to the disease in question and the nature of the event. The Director-General takes the EC's advice following their technical assessment of the crisis using legal criteria and a predetermined algorithm after a review of all available data on the event. Upon declaration, the EC then makes recommendations on what actions the Director-General and Member States should take to address the crisis.<ref name=Kamradt-Scott2019/> The recommendations are temporary and require three-monthly reviews.<ref name=WHOIHR1/>\n\n==Declarations==\n[[File:H1N1 influenza virus.jpg|thumb|upright|H1N1 influenza virus]]\n\n===2009 swine flu declaration===\nIn the spring of 2009, a novel influenza A (H1N1) virus emerged. It was detected first in the United States of America and spread quickly across the United States and the world.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cdc.gov/flu/pandemic-resources/2009-h1n1-pandemic.html|title=2009 H1N1 Pandemic|last=CDC|date=2019-06-11|website=Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|language=en-us|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref> On 26 April 2009,<ref name=H1N12009WHO>{{Cite book|url=http://apps.who.int/gb/ebwha/pdf_files/WHA64/A64_10-en.pdf|title=Implementation of the International Health Regulations (2005), Report of the Review Committee on the Functioning of the International Health Regulations (2005) in relation to Pandemic (H1N1) 2009|last=Director-General|publisher=WHO|year=2009|isbn=|location=|pages=118}}</ref> more than one month after its first emergence,<ref name=\"Hoffman2018\">{{Cite journal|last=Hoffman|first=Steven J.|last2=Silverberg|first2=Sarah L.|date=18 January 2018|title=Delays in Global Disease Outbreak Responses: Lessons from H1N1, Ebola, and Zika|journal=[[American Journal of Public Health]]|volume=108|issue=3|pages=329\u2013333|doi=10.2105/AJPH.2017.304245|pmid=29345996|pmc=5803810|issn=0090-0036}}</ref> the first PHEIC was declared when the [[2009 flu pandemic|H1N1 (or swine flu) pandemic]] was still in [[Influenza pandemic#Phases|Phase Three]].<ref name=\"urlInside Justice-WHO-PHEIC\">{{cite web| url = http://www.insidejustice.com/intl/2009/04/30/swine_flu_who_pheic/| title = Inside Justice &#124; Swine Flu: Legal Obligations and Consequences When the World Health Organization Declares a \"Public Health Emergency of International Concern\"| author =  Renee Dopplick| date = 29 April 2009| accessdate = 6 June 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"urlWHO | Swine influenza\">{{cite web| url = http://www.who.int/mediacentre/news/statements/2009/h1n1_20090425/en/\n| title = Swine influenza| author = Margaret Chan | date = 25 April 2009| publisher = [[World Health Organization]]| accessdate = 6 June 2014| author-link = Margaret Chan}}</ref><ref name=\"urlWHO | Swine flu illness in the United States and Mexico - update 2\">{{cite web| url = http://www.who.int/csr/don/2009_04_26/en/| title = Swine flu illness in the United States and Mexico \u2013 update 2| author = | date = 26 April 2009| publisher = [[World Health Organization]]| accessdate = 6 June 2014}}</ref> On the same day, within three hours the WHO web site received almost two million visits, necessitating the pandemic's own dedicated pandemic influenza web site.<ref name=H1N12009WHO/> At the time H1N1 had been declared a PHEIC, it had so far occurred in only three countries.<ref name=\"Hoffman2018\" /> Declaring H1N1 a PHEIC has therefore been argued as fueling public fear.<ref name=\"Gostin2016\">{{Cite journal|last=Gostin|first=Lawrence O.|last2=Katz|first2=Rebeccas|author-link2=Rebecca Katz|date=June 2016|title=The International Health Regulations: The Governing Framework for Global Health Security|url=|journal=The Milbank Quarterly|volume=94|issue=2|pages=264\u2013313|doi=10.1111/1468-0009.12186|pmc=4911720|pmid=27166578|via=}}</ref> However, a 2013 study sponsored by the WHO estimated that although the H1N1 pandemic was similar in magnitude to seasonal influenza, it resulted in the loss of more life-years due to a shift toward mortality among persons less than 65 years of age.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Simonsen |first=Lone |last2=Spreeuwenberg |first2=Peter |last3=Lustig |first3=Roger |last4=Taylor |first4=Robert J. |last5=Fleming |first5=Douglas M. |last6=Kroneman |first6=Madelon |last7=Van Kerkhove |first7=Maria D. |last8=Mounts |first8=Anthony W. |last9=Paget |first9=W. John |last10=Hay |first10=Simon I. |title=Global Mortality Estimates for the 2009 Influenza Pandemic from the GLaMOR Project: A Modeling Study |journal=[[PLOS Medicine]] |date=26 November 2013 |volume=10 |issue=11 |pages=e1001558 |doi=10.1371/journal.pmed.1001558 |pmid=24302890 |pmc=3841239}}</ref>\n\n===2014 polio declaration===\nThe second PHEIC was the [[Poliomyelitis eradication#2011\u20132015|2014 polio declaration]], issued in May 2014 with the resurgence of [[poliomyelitis|wild polio]] after its near-eradication, deemed \"an extraordinary event\".<ref name=\"urlWHO-IHREC-wild poliovirus\">{{cite web\n| url = http://www.who.int/mediacentre/news/statements/2014/polio-20140505/en/\n| title = WHO &#124; WHO statement on the meeting of the International Health Regulations Emergency Committee concerning the international spread of wild poliovirus\n| author = \n| date = 5 May 2014\n| publisher = [[World Health Organization]]\n| accessdate = 6 June 2014\n}}</ref><ref name=\"urlNewScientist-polio cases surge-2014-0505\">{{cite web\n| url = https://www.newscientist.com/article/dn25518-global-emergency-declared-as-polio-cases-surge.html\n| title = Global emergency declared as polio cases surge \u2013 health \u2013 05 May 2014 \u2013 New Scientist\n| first =  Debora\n| last = MacKenzie\n| date = 5 May 2014\n| publisher = New Scientist\n| accessdate = 6 June 2014\n}}</ref>\n\nGlobal eradication was deemed to be at risk with small numbers of cases in Afghanistan, Pakistan, and Nigeria.<ref name=Gostin2016/>\n\nIn October 2019, continuing cases of wild polio in Pakistan and Afghanistan, in addition to new vaccine-derived cases in Africa and Asia, was reviewed and remains a PHEIC.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cidrap.umn.edu/news-perspective/2019/10/news-scan-oct-04-2019|title=News Scan: Polio in Pakistan|last=|first=|date=4 October 2019|website=CIDRAP|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=10 October 2019}}</ref> It was extended on 11 December 2019.<ref name=THP11Dec2019>{{Cite web|url=https://travelhealthpro.org.uk/news/483/polio-public-health-emergency-of-international-concern|title=NaTHNaC - Polio: Public Health Emergency of International Concern|last=|first=|date=|website=TravelHealthPro|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=13 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n===2014 Ebola declaration===\nConfirmed cases of Ebola were being reported in Guinea and Liberia in March 2014 and Sierra Leone by May 2014. On Friday, 8 August 2014, following the occurrence of Ebola in the United States and Europe and with the already intense transmission ongoing in three other countries for months,<ref name=Rull2015/> the WHO declared its third PHEIC in response to the [[2014 West Africa Ebola outbreak|outbreak of Ebola in Western Africa]].<ref name=WHO2014>{{Cite web|url=http://www.euro.who.int/en/health-topics/emergencies/pages/news/news/2014/08/ebola-outbreak-in-west-africa-declared-a-public-health-emergency-of-international-concern|title=Ebola outbreak in West Africa declared a public health emergency of international concern|date=8 August 2014|website=www.euro.who.int|language=en|access-date=3 June 2019}}</ref> Later, one review showed that a direct impact of this epidemic on America escalated a PHEIC declaration.<ref name=\"Hoffman2018\" /> It was the first PHEIC in a resource-poor setting.<ref name=Rull2015/>\n\n===2016 Zika virus declaration===\nOn 1 February 2016, the WHO declared its fourth PHEIC in response to clusters of [[microcephaly]] and [[Guillain\u2013Barr\u00e9 syndrome]] in the [[Americas]], which at the time were suspected to be associated with the ongoing [[2015\u201316 Zika virus epidemic]].<ref>WHO (1 February 2016). [http://www.who.int/mediacentre/news/statements/2016/emergency-committee-zika-microcephaly/en/ WHO Director-General summarizes the outcome of the Emergency Committee on Zika]</ref> Later research and evidence bore out these concerns; in April, the WHO stated that \"there is scientific consensus that Zika virus is a cause of microcephaly and Guillain\u2013Barr\u00e9 syndrome.\"<ref name=\"WHO SitRep 7 Apr 2016\">{{cite web | url=http://apps.who.int/iris/bitstream/10665/204961/1/zikasitrep_7Apr2016_eng.pdf?ua=1 | title=Zika Virus Microcephaly And Guillain\u2013Barr\u00e9 Syndrome Situation Report | publisher=World Health Organization | date=7 April 2016 | accessdate=12 May 2016}}</ref>  This was the first time a PHEIC was declared for a [[Mosquito-borne disease|mosquito\u2010borne disease]].<ref name=Gostin2016/> This declaration was lifted on 18 November 2016.<ref>{{cite web|title=Fifth meeting of the Emergency Committee under the International Health Regulations (2005) regarding microcephaly, other neurological disorders and Zika virus|url=http://www.who.int/mediacentre/news/statements/2016/zika-fifth-ec/en/|website=World Health Organization|publisher=WHO|accessdate=1 December 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== 2018\u201320 Kivu Ebola declaration ===\nIn October 2018 and then later in April 2019, the WHO did not consider the [[2018\u201320 Kivu Ebola epidemic]] to be a PHEIC.<ref name=\"Green20April2019\">{{Cite journal|last=Green|first=Andrew|date=20 April 2019|title=DR Congo Ebola outbreak not given PHEIC designation|journal=The Lancet|volume=393|issue=10181|pages=1586|doi=10.1016/S0140-6736(19)30893-1|pmid=31007190}}</ref><ref name=\"PHEICApril2019\">{{cite web|url=https://www.who.int/news-room/detail/12-04-2019-statement-on-the-meeting-of-the-international-health-regulations-(2005)-emergency-committee-for-ebola-virus-disease-in-the-democratic-republic-of-the-congo-on-12th-april-2019|title=Statement on the meeting of the International Health Regulations (2005) Emergency Committee for Ebola virus disease in the Democratic Republic of the Congo on 12th April 2019|date=12 April 2019|publisher=World Health Organization|accessdate=13 June 2019}}</ref> The decision was controversial, with [[Michael Osterholm]], director of the [[Center for Infectious Disease Research and Policy]] (CIDRAP) responding with disappointment and describing the situation as \"an Ebola gas can sitting in DRC that's just waiting for a match to hit it\",<ref name=\"Cohen2019\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.sciencemag.org/news/2019/04/ebola-outbreak-congo-still-not-international-crisis-who-decides|title=Ebola outbreak in Congo still not an international crisis, WHO decides|last=Cohen|first=Jon|last2=2019|date=12 April 2019|website=Science {{!}} AAAS|language=en|access-date=18 June 2019}}</ref> while the WHO panel were unanimous that declaring it a PHEIC would not give any added benefit.<ref name=\"Cohen2019\" /> The advice against declaring a PHEIC in October 2018 and April 2019, despite the criteria for doing so appearing to be met on both occasions has led to the transparency of the IHR EC coming into question. The language used in the statements for the Kivu Ebola epidemic has been noted to be different. In October 2018, the EC stated \"a PHEIC should not be declared at this time\". However, in the 13 previously declined proposals for declaring a PHEIC, the resultant statements quoted \"the conditions for a PHEIC are not currently met\" and \"does not constitute a PHEIC\". In April 2019, they stated that \"there is no added benefit to declaring a PHEIC at this stage\", a notion that is not part of the PHEIC criteria laid down in the IHR.<ref name=\"Kamradt-Scott2019\" /><ref name=\"Lancet2019\">{{Cite journal|last=Lancet|first=The|date=25 May 2019|title=Acknowledging the limits of public health solutions|url=https://www.thelancet.com/journals/lancet/article/PIIS0140-6736(19)31183-3/abstract|journal=The Lancet|language=English|volume=393|issue=10186|pages=2100|doi=10.1016/S0140-6736(19)31183-3|issn=0140-6736|pmid=31226033|doi-access=free}}</ref>\n\nAfter confirmed cases of Ebola in neighbouring Uganda in June 2019, [[Tedros Adhanom]], the Director-General of the WHO, announced that the third meeting of a group of experts would be held on 14 June 2019 to assess whether the Ebola spread had become a PHEIC.<ref name=\"Hunt2019\">{{cite web|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2019/06/12/health/ebola-outbreak-death-uganda-africa-intl-bn/index.html|title=Ebola outbreak enters 'truly frightening phase' as it turns deadly in Uganda|last=Hunt|first=Katie|website=CNN|language=en|accessdate=12 June 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"NYTimes14June2019\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/12/world/africa/ebola-uganda-congo.html|title=Boy, 5, and Grandmother Die in Uganda as More Ebola Cases Emerge|last=Gladstone|first=Rick|date=12 June 2019|work=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=14 June 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The conclusion was that while the outbreak was a health emergency in the [[Democratic Republic of the Congo]] (DRC) and the region, it does not meet all the three criteria for a PHEIC.<ref name=\"WHO14June2019\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.who.int/news-room/detail/14-06-2019-statement-on-the-meeting-of-the-international-health-regulations-(2005)-emergency-committee-for-ebola-virus-disease-in-the-democratic-republic-of-the-congo|title=Statement on the meeting of the International Health Regulations (2005) Emergency Committee for Ebola virus disease in the Democratic Republic of the Congo on 14 June 2019|last=|first=|date=|website=World Health Organization|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=14 June 2019}}</ref> Despite the number of deaths reaching 1,405 by 11 June 2019 and 1,440 by 17 June 2019, the reason for not declaring a PHIEC was that the overall risk of international spread was deemed to be low, and the risk of damaging the economy of the DRC high.<ref name=\"SoucharyJune2019\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.cidrap.umn.edu/news-perspective/2019/06/ebola-case-counts-spike-again-drc|title=Ebola case counts spike again in DRC|last=Souchary|first=Stephanie|date=17 June 2019|website=CIDRAP|language=en|access-date=24 June 2019}}</ref> Adhanom also stated that declaring a PHEIC would be an inappropriate way to raise money for the epidemic.<ref name=\"CIDRAP16July2019\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.cidrap.umn.edu/news-perspective/2019/07/who-will-take-ebola-emergency-declaration-question-fourth-time|title=WHO will take up Ebola emergency declaration question for a fourth time|last=Soucheray|first=Stephanie|last2=2019|date=16 July 2019|website=CIDRAP|language=en|access-date=17 July 2019}}</ref> Following a visit to the DRC in July 2019, [[Rory Stewart]], the UK's [[Department for International Development|DfID]] minister, called for the WHO to declare it an emergency.<ref name=\"Wintour9July2019\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/jul/07/declare-ebola-outbreak-in-drc-an-emergency-says-uks-rory-stewart|title=Declare Ebola outbreak in DRC an emergency, says UK's Rory Stewart|last=Wintour|first=Patrick|date=7 July 2019|work=The Guardian|access-date=9 July 2019|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\nAcknowledging a high risk of spread to the capital of North Kivu, [[Goma]], a call for a PHEIC declaration was published on 10 July 2019 in the ''[[Washington Post]]'' by [[Daniel R. Lucey|Daniel Lucey]] and [[Ron Klain]] (the former US [[Ebola response coordinator]]). They stated that  \"in the absence of a trajectory toward extinguishing the outbreak, the opposite path\u2014severe escalation\u2014remains possible. The risk of the disease moving into nearby Goma, Congo\u2014a city of 1 million residents with an international airport \u2014or crossing into the massive refugee camps in South Sudan is mounting. With a limited number of vaccine doses remaining, either would be a catastrophe\".<ref name=\"Soucheray11July2019\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.cidrap.umn.edu/news-perspective/2019/07/three-more-health-workers-infected-ebola-outbreak|title=Three more health workers infected in Ebola outbreak|last=Soucheray|first=Stephanie|date=11 July 2019|website=CIDRAP|language=en|access-date=16 July 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Klain10July2019\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/its-time-to-declare-a-public-health-emergency-on-ebola/2019/07/10/c77641fc-a327-11e9-b732-41a79c2551bf_story.html|title=Opinion {{!}} It's time to declare a public health emergency on Ebola|last=Klain|first=Ronald A.|last2=Lucey|first2=Daniel|date=10 July 2019|website=Washington Post|language=en|access-date=16 July 2019}}</ref> Four days later, on 14 July 2019, a case of Ebola was confirmed in Goma, which has an international airport and a highly mobile population. Subsequently, the WHO announced a reconvening of a fourth EC meeting on 17 July 2019, when they officially announced it \"a regional emergency, and by no means a global threat\" and declared it as a PHEIC, without restrictions on trade or travel.<ref name=\"WHONewsRelease17July2019\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.who.int/news-room/detail/17-07-2019-ebola-outbreak-in-the-democratic-republic-of-the-congo-declared-a-public-health-emergency-of-international-concern|title=Ebola outbreak in the Democratic Republic of the Congo declared a Public Health Emergency of International Concern|last=|first=|date=2019-07-17|website=World Health Organization|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-31}}</ref><ref name=BBCNews17July2019>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/health-49025298|title=Ebola outbreak declared public health emergency|last=|first=|date=17 July 2019|work=BBC News|access-date=17 July 2019|language=en-GB}}</ref> In response to the declaration, the president of the DRC, together with an expert committee led by a virologist, took responsibility for directly supervising action, while in protest of the declaration, health minister, [[Oly Ilunga Kalenga]] resigned.<ref name=Schnirring22July2019>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cidrap.umn.edu/news-perspective/2019/07/drc-health-minister-resigns-after-government-takes-ebola-reins|title=DRC health minister resigns after government takes Ebola reins|last=Schnirring|first=Lisa|date=22 July 2019|website=CIDRAP|language=en|access-date=26 July 2019}}</ref> A review of the PHEIC had been planned at a fifth meeting of the EC on 10 October 2019<ref name=9Oct2019>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cidrap.umn.edu/news-perspective/2019/10/response-resumes-following-security-problems-drc-ebola-hot-spot|title=Response resumes following security problems in DRC Ebola hot spot|last=Schnirring|first=Lisa|last2=9 October 2019|date=|website=CIDRAP|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=10 October 2019}}</ref> and as of 18 October 2019, it continues to be a PHEIC.<ref name=\"WHO18Oct2019\">WHO Statement (18 October 2019). {{Cite web|url=https://www.who.int/news-room/detail/18-10-2019-statement-on-the-meeting-of-the-international-health-regulations-(2005)-emergency-committee-for-ebola-virus-disease-in-the-democratic-republic-of-the-congo|title=Statement on the meeting of the International Health Regulations (2005) Emergency Committee for Ebola virus disease in the Democratic Republic of the Congo on 18 October 2019|last=|first=|date=|website=www.who.int|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=21 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== 2019 coronavirus pandemic (COVID-19) ===\n[[File:2019-nCoV-CDC-23312.png|thumb|right|Morphology of SARS-CoV-2]]\nOn 30 January 2020, the WHO declared the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|outbreak of COVID-19]], centered on [[Wuhan]] in [[central China]], a PHEIC.<ref name=\"WHOStatement30January2020\" /><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/01/30/health/coronavirus-world-health-organization.html |title=W.H.O. Declares Global Emergency as the new Coronavirus Spreads |last=Ramzy |first=Austin |date=2020-01-30 |work=The New York Times |access-date=2020-01-30 |last2=Jr |first2=Donald G. McNeil |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331}}</ref> On the date of the declaration, there were 7,818 cases confirmed globally, affecting 19 countries in five WHO regions.<ref>WHO Report (30 January 2020). {{cite web |url=https://www.who.int/docs/default-source/coronaviruse/situation-reports/20200130-sitrep-10-ncov.pdf?sfvrsn=d0b2e480_2 |title=Novel Coronavirus(2019-nCoV): Situation Report-10 |publisher=WHO |date=30 January 2020 |accessdate=30 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.who.int/news-room/detail/30-01-2020-statement-on-the-second-meeting-of-the-international-health-regulations-(2005)-emergency-committee-regarding-the-outbreak-of-novel-coronavirus-(2019-ncov) |title=Statement on the second meeting of the International Health Regulations (2005) Emergency Committee regarding the outbreak of novel coronavirus (2019-nCoV) |publisher=WHO |date=30 January 2020 |accessdate=30 January 2020}}</ref> Previously, the WHO had held EC meetings on 22 and 23 January 2020 regarding the coronavirus pandemic,<ref name=Fifield23Jan2020>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/nine-dead-as-chinese-coronavirus-spreads-despite-efforts-to-contain-it/2020/01/22/1eaade72-3c6d-11ea-afe2-090eb37b60b1_story.html|title=Nine dead as Chinese coronavirus spreads, despite efforts to contain it|last=Fifield|first=Anna|last2=Sun|first2=Lena H. |date=23 January 2020|work=The Washington Post|access-date=6 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=Schnirring22Jan2020>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cidrap.umn.edu/news-perspective/2020/01/who-decision-ncov-emergency-delayed-cases-spike|title=WHO decision on nCoV emergency delayed as cases spike|last=Schnirring|first=Lisa|date=22 January 2020|website=CIDRAP|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=23 January 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"WHO22Jan2020\">WHO Statement (22 January 2020). {{Cite web|url=https://www.who.int/dg/speeches/detail/who-director-general-s-statement-on-ihr-emergency-committee-on-novel-coronavirus|title=WHO Director-General's statement on IHR Emergency Committee on Novel Coronavirus|last=|first=|date=22 January 2020|website=www.who.int|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=23 January 2020}}</ref> but it was determined that it was too early to declare a PHEIC  at that time given the lack of necessary data and the (then) scale of global impact.<ref name=\"StatNews\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.statnews.com/2020/01/23/who-declines-to-declare-china-virus-outbreak-a-global-health-emergency/|title=WHO declines to declare China virus outbreak a global health emergency|last=Joseph|first=Andrew|date=23 January 2020|website=STAT|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=23 January 2020}}</ref><ref name=WHO23Jan2020>WHO Statement (23 January 2020). {{Cite web|url=https://www.who.int/news-room/detail/23-01-2020-statement-on-the-meeting-of-the-international-health-regulations-(2005)-emergency-committee-regarding-the-outbreak-of-novel-coronavirus-(2019-ncov)|title=Statement on the meeting of the International Health Regulations (2005) Emergency Committee regarding the outbreak of novel coronavirus 2019 (n-CoV) on 23 January 2020|last=|first=|date=|website=www.who.int|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=23 January 2020}}</ref> The WHO recognized the spread of [[COVID-19]] as a [[pandemic]] on 11 March 2020.<ref name=\"WHOpandemic1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.who.int/dg/speeches/detail/who-director-general-s-opening-remarks-at-the-media-briefing-on-covid-19---11-march-2020|title=WHO Director-General's opening remarks at the media briefing on COVID-19 \u2013 11 March 2020|date=20 March 2020|publisher=[[World Health Organization]]|access-date=11 March 2020}}</ref> Europe, Iran, USA, South Korea and Japan reported a surging of cases and the total number quickly passed China.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gisanddata.maps.arcgis.com/apps/opsdashboard/index.html#/bda7594740fd40299423467b48e9ecf6|title=Operations Dashboard for ArcGIS|website=gisanddata.maps.arcgis.com|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref>\n\n==Response==\nIn 2018, an examination of the first four declarations (2009\u20132016) showed that the WHO was noted to be more effective in responding to international health emergencies, and that the international system in dealing with these emergencies was \"robust\".<ref name=\"Hunger2018\">{{Cite book|url=https://www.oxfordscholarship.com/view/10.1093/oso/9780198828945.001.0001/oso-9780198828945-chapter-4|title=Coping with Public Health Emergencies of International Concern|volume=1|last=Hunger|first=Iris|date=2018|publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]|isbn=9780191867422|location=|pages=|language=en-US|doi=10.1093/oso/9780198828945.003.0004}}{{subscription required}}</ref>\n\nAnother review of the first four declarations, with the exception of wild polio, demonstrated that responses were varied. Severe outbreaks, or those that threatened larger numbers of people, did not receive a swift PHEIC declaration, and the study hypothesized that responses were quicker when American citizens were infected and when the emergencies did not coincide with holidays.<ref name=Hoffman2018/>\n\n==Non-declarations==\n[[File:Mers-virus-3D-image.jpg|thumb|MERS-coronavirus]]\n\n===2013 MERS===\nPHEIC was not invoked with the [[Middle Eastern Respiratory Syndrome]] (MERS) outbreak in 2013.<ref name=\"urlMERS - The Global Dispatch\">{{cite web\n| url = http://www.theglobaldispatch.com/mers-does-not-constitute-a-public-health-emergency-of-international-concern-pheic-emergency-committee-32451/\n| title = MERS does not constitute a Public Health Emergency of International Concern (PHEIC): Emergency committee \u2013 The Global Dispatc\n| author =  Robert Herriman\n| date = 17 July 2013\n| publisher = The Global Dispatch\n| accessdate = 6 June 2014\n}}</ref><ref name=\"urlWHO-2IHRECV-MERS-CoV\">{{cite web\n| url = http://centerforvaccineethicsandpolicy.net/2013/07/20/who-statement-second-meeting-of-the-ihr-emergency-committee-concerning-mers-cov-pheic-conditions-not-met/\n| title = WHO Statement: Second Meeting of the IHR Emergency Committee concerning MERS-CoV \u2013 PHEIC Conditions Not Met &#124; global vaccine ethics and policy\n| author = David R Curry\n| date = 20 July 2013\n| publisher = Center for Vaccine Ethics and Policy\n| accessdate = 6 June 2014\n}}</ref> Originating in Saudi Arabia, MERS reached more than 24 countries and resulted in more than 580 deaths by 2015, although most cases were in hospital settings rather than sustained community spread. What constitutes a PHEIC has, as a result, been unclear.<ref name=Halabi2017/>\n\n== Non-infectious events ==\nPHEIC are not confined to only infectious diseases. It may cover events caused by chemical agents or radioactive materials.<ref name=Halabi2017/>\n\nThe emergence and spread of [[antimicrobial resistance]] may debatably constitute a PHEIC.<ref name=AMR>{{Cite web|url=https://medicalxpress.com/news/2011-04-international-health-antimicrobial-resistance.html|title=Can the International Health Regulations apply to antimicrobial resistance?|website=medicalxpress.com|language=en-us|access-date=15 June 2019}}</ref><ref name=Wernli2011>{{Cite journal|last=Wernli|first=Didier|last2=Haustein|first2=Thomas|last3=Conly|first3=John|last4=Carmeli|first4=Yehuda|last5=Kickbusch|first5=Ilona|last6=Harbarth|first6=Stephan|date=April 2011|title=A call for action: the application of The International Health Regulations to the global threat of antimicrobial resistance|journal=[[PLOS Medicine]]|volume=8|issue=4|pages=e1001022|doi=10.1371/journal.pmed.1001022|issn=1549-1676|pmc=3079636|pmid=21526227}}</ref><ref name=Kamradt-Scott2011>{{Cite journal|last=Kamradt-Scott|first=Adam|date=19 April 2011|title=A Public Health Emergency of International Concern? Response to a Proposal to Apply the International Health Regulations to Antimicrobial Resistance|journal=PLOS Medicine|language=en|volume=8|issue=4|pages=e1001021|doi=10.1371/journal.pmed.1001021|pmid=21526165|pmc=3080965|issn=1549-1676}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Biosecurity]]\n*[[Disease X]]\n*[[Notifiable disease]]\n*[[Public health emergency (United States)]]\n*[[State of emergency]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*[https://www.who.int/news-room/detail/20-12-2019-statement-o-the-twenty-third-ihr-emergency-committee-regarding-the-international-spread-of-poliovirus Statement of the Twenty-Third IHR Emergency Committee Regarding the International Spread of Poliovirus]. WHO 7 January 2020\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Politics|Viruses|right=yes}}\n*[https://www.who.int/features/qa/emergency-committees/en/ International Health Regulations and Emergency Committees]. www.who.int \n\n{{PHEIC}}\n{{Zika}}\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n\n[[Category:Public Health Emergency of International Concern| ]]\n[[Category:Global health]]\n[[Category:Health law]]\n[[Category:World Health Organization]]\n[[Category:Emergency management]]\n", "name_user": "Srich32977", "label": "safe", "comment": "redundant", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Public_Health_Emergency_of_International_Concern"}
{"title_page": "Muslim population growth", "text_new": "{{Expand Arabic|date=May 2019}}\n{{cleanup|reason=predictions of distant future statistics are unreliable; [[WP:NOTCRYSTAL]].|date=December 2019}}\n[[File:Islam percent population in each nation World Map Muslim data by Pew Research.svg|300px|thumb|World Muslim population by percentage ([[Pew Research Center]], 2014)]]\n'''Muslim population growth''' is the [[population growth]] of [[Muslim]]s worldwide. In 2010-2015, the expected Muslim growth rate was 1.8%.<ref name=\"pew2015all\">{{cite report |url=https://assets.pewresearch.org/wp-content/uploads/sites/11/2015/03/PF_15.04.02_ProjectionsFullReport.pdf |title=The Future of World Religions: Population Growth Projections, 2010-2050 |publisher=[[Pew Research Center]] |date=April 2, 2015}}</ref> This compares with average [[world population growth]] rate of 1.2% per year for the referenced period.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.worldometers.info/world-population/ |title=World Population (2020 and historical) |accessdate=12 February 2020}}</ref> as of 2015, it was predicted that the world's Muslim population would grow twice as fast as the overall global population in the following decades.<ref name=\"pew2015all\" /> Young median age and high fertility rate of Muslims relative to other religious groups are significant factors behind Islam's population growth;<ref name=\"Pew2011Muslim\" /><ref name=\"FastestGrowing\" /> As of 2015, the Muslim fertility rate for [[Muslim-majority countries|all 49 Muslim-majority countries]] is 2.9\u2014well above the global rate\u2014but down from 4.3 in 1990-1995.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2017/11/muslim-overpopulation-myth/545318/|title=The Muslim Overpopulation Myth That Just Won\u2019t Die|date=November 14, 2017|author=Krithika Varagur|publisher=[[The Atlantic]]|accessdate=April 21, 2020}}</ref> According to Pew Research, [[religious conversion]] has no net impact on the Muslim population as the number of people who [[Convert to Islam|convert to Islam]] is roughly similar to those who leave Islam.<ref name=\"Pew2011Muslim\">{{cite report |url=http://www.pewforum.org/2011/01/27/the-future-of-the-global-muslim-population/ |title=The Future of the Global Muslim Population |date=27 January 2011|publisher=[[Pew Research Center]]|access-date=27 December 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"FastestGrowing\">{{cite web |title=Why Muslims are the world's fastest-growing religious group |url=http://www.pewresearch.org/fact-tank/2015/04/23/why-muslims-are-the-worlds-fastest-growing-religious-group/ |publisher=[[Pew Research Center]] |date=23 April 2015 |accessdate=5 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SAzizViY30EC |title=The World's Religions in Figures: An Introduction to International Religious Demography |first1=Todd M. |last1=Johnson |first2=Brian J. |last2=Grim |date=25 March 2013 |publisher=[[John Wiley & Sons]] |isbn=9781118323038}}</ref>\n\n==By region==\n\n===World===\n{{See also|Islam by country}}\n* The six fastest-growing religions in the world are estimated to be [[Islam]] (1.84%), the [[Bah\u00e1'\u00ed Faith]] (1.70%), [[Sikhism]] (1.62%), [[Jainism]] (1.57%), [[Hinduism]] (1.52%), and [[Christianity]] (1.38%), with high birth rates being cited as the major reason.<ref>{{cite news |title=The List: The World\u2019s Fastest-Growing Religions |work=[[Foreign Policy]] |date=14 May 2007 |url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2007/05/14/the-list-the-worlds-fastest-growing-religions/ |accessdate=11 February 2020}}</ref>\n* On April 2, 2015, the [[Pew Research Center]] published a demographic study about \"The Future of World Religions: Population Growth Projections, 2010-2050\" with projections of the growth of Islam and reasons why \"Islam will grow faster than any other major religion.\"<ref name=\"pew2015all\" /> The study concluded that the global Muslim population is expected to grow at a faster rate than the non-Muslim population due primarily to the young age and high fertility rate of Muslims.<ref name=\"Pew2017Change\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/goatsandsoda/2015/12/25/460797744/a-religious-forecast-for-2050-atheism-is-down-islam-is-rising|title=A Religious Forecast For 2050: Atheism Is Down, Islam Is Rising |work=[[NPR]]}}</ref>\n\n:'''Projected global Muslim population (2010-2050):'''\n:# The number of Muslims world-wide is projected to increase from about 1.6 billion in 2010 to nearly 2.8 billion in 2050. Consequently, Muslims are projected to rise from 23% of the world\u2019s population in 2010 to 30% in 2050.\n:#Muslims are expected to grow twice as fast as the overall global population (the expected annual growth rate of Muslims is projected to be 0.6 p.p. above the rate for the world\u2019s population through 2050)\n:#If current trends continue, by 2050 the number of Muslims will nearly equal the number of Christians around the world.\n:# In Europe, Muslims will make up 10% of the overall population.\n:# India will retain a [[Hindu]] majority but also will have the largest Muslim population of any country in the world, surpassing [[Indonesia]].\n:# In the United States, Judaism will no longer be the largest non-Christian religion. Muslims will be more numerous in the U.S. than people who identify as Jewish on the basis of religion.\n\n:'''Reasons given for the projected growth'''\n:# The change in the world's religious is \"driven primarily by differences in fertility rates and the size of youth populations among the world's major religions, as well as by people switching faiths.\"\n:# ''Fertility rates''. The world's total population \"is expected to rise to 9.3 billion, a 35% increase\" between 2010 and 2050, However, \"over that same period, Muslims, who have a comparatively youthful population with high fertility rates, are projected to increase by 73%.\" Muslim growth benefits from the fertility factor because \"globally, Muslims have the highest fertility rate, an average of 3.1 children per woman.\" This is above a replacement level of 2.1 which is \"the minimum typically needed to maintain a stable population.\"\n:# ''Size of youth population''. \"In 2010, more than a quarter of the world's total population (27%) was under the age of 15. But a \"higher percentage of Muslims (34%) were younger than 15.\"\n:# ''Size of old population''. In 2010, \"11% of the world's population was at least 60 years old,\" but only 7% of Muslims were over 60.\n:# ''Switching''. Between 2010 and 2050 a gain of 3,220,000 Muslim adherents is projected to come through switching, mostly found in the [[Sub Saharan Africa]] (2.9 million). Also, the Muslim population are projected to add 1.3 million and lose 880,000 via switching, for a net gain of 420,000 between 2015 and 2020.\n:# ''Migration''. Migration  is the third reason for the Muslim population growth. For example, 1.8% of the projected growth in Europe is attributed to Muslims migrating in.\n\n===Asia===\n[[Islam]] is currently the largest religion in Asia. According to the [[Pew Research Center]], 27.3% of the people living in the Asia-Pacific region in 2030 will be Muslim, up from about a quarter in 2010 (24.8%) and 21.6% in 1990.<ref name=\"Pew2011Muslim\" />\n\n====India====\nIslam is the [[Growth of religion|fastest-growing religion]] in India.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.censusindia.gov.in/Census_Data_2001/India_at_glance/religion.aspx |title=Census of India |access-date=11 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071015225409/http://www.censusindia.gov.in/Census_Data_2001/India_at_glance/religion.aspx |publisher=[[Registrar General and Census Commissioner of India]] |archive-date=15 October 2007}}</ref> Growth rate of Muslims has been consistently higher than the growth rate of Hindus, ever since the census data of independent India has been available. For example, during the 1991-2001 decade, Muslim growth rate was 29.5% (vs 19.9% for Hindus). However, Muslims population growth rate declined to 24.6% during 2001-2011 decade, in keeping with the similar decline in most religious groups of India.<ref>{{cite news|title=Myth of Muslim growth|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/opinion/columns/myth-of-muslim-growth/|accessdate=5 June 2016|newspaper=[[The Indian Express]]|date=2 September 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/census-2011-data-on-population-by-religious-communities/article7579161.ece|title=Muslim population growth slows |work=[[The Hindu]] |language=en-IN |issn=0971-751X |date=25 August 2015 |access-date=21 August 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|title=The Myth Of The Muslim Population Bomb|url=http://www.tehelka.com/2015/02/the-myth-of-the-muslim-population-bomb/|accessdate=5 June 2016|magazine=[[Tehelka]]|date=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160604122248/http://www.tehelka.com/2015/02/the-myth-of-the-muslim-population-bomb/|archive-date=4 June 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Five charts that puncture the bogey of Muslim population growth|url=http://scroll.in/article/705283/five-charts-that-puncture-the-bogey-of-muslim-population-growth|publisher=[[Scroll.in]]|accessdate=6 June 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn India regarding attitudes \"toward [[birth control]],\" younger (ages 10\u201319) Muslim women are less likely to favor it than are older (ages 20\u201330). Regarding \"knowledge of  birth control,\" younger (ages 10\u201319) Muslim women know less than do older (ages 20\u201330).  \"Muslim marriages take place earlier\" than other religions, and younger (ages 10\u201319) Muslim women are more likely to want to have \"many children\" than are older (ages 20\u201330).<ref>{{cite book |last=Shakeel |first=Ahmad |title=Muslim Attitude Towards Family Planning |publisher=Sarup & Sons |year=2003 |url=https://books.google.com/books/about/Muslim_Attitude_Towards_Family_Planning.html?id=MFrDOXtYXfwC |pages=26, 33, 47, 51}}</ref>\n\nAccording to [[Paul Kurtz]], Muslims in India are much more resistant to modern contraceptive measures compared to other Indians and, as a consequence, the fertility rate among non-Muslim women is much lower compared to that of Muslim women.<ref>{{cite book |last=Guilmoto |first= Christophe |title=Fertility transition in South India |publisher=[[SAGE Publishing]] |year=2005 |isbn=9780761932925}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Kurtz |first=Paul |title=Multi-Secularism: A New Agenda |publisher=[[Transaction Publishers]] |isbn = 9781412814195 | year=2010}}</ref>\nIslam is the second-largest [[religion in India]], making up 14.2% of the country's population with about 172 million adherents ([[2011 Census of India|2011 census]]).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rediff.com/news/slide-show/slide-show-1-by-2030-muslims-will-make-up-16-pc-of-indias-population/20110128.htm |title=By 2030, Muslims will make up 16 pc of India's population |work=Rediff News |date=28 January 2011}}</ref> In 2010, India had the second largest population of Muslims, after Indonesia and ahead of Pakistan.<ref>{{cite report | url=http://www.pewforum.org/2012/12/18/global-religious-landscape-muslim/ | title=The Global Religious Landscape \u2013 Muslims | work=[[Pew Research Center]] | accessdate=29 July 2015 | date=18 December 2012}}</ref>\n\n====China====\nIn China, Muslim population growth has been estimated to be as much as 2.7% from 1964\u20131982, however the Pew Research Center projects a slowing down of Muslim population growth in China due partly to the fact that many [[Hui people|Hui Muslims]] voluntarily limit themselves to one child in China, a response to their Imams expressing the benefits of population control. <ref>{{cite report |url=http://www.pewforum.org/2011/01/27/future-of-the-global-muslim-population-regional-asia/ |title=The Future of the Global Muslim Population - Region: Asia-Pacific |publisher=[[Pew Research Center]] |date=27 January 2011 |access-date=11 February 2020}}</ref> By contrast, China's Christian population growth has been estimated at 4.7% based on total population figures from the year 1949. <ref>{{cite report |url=https://www.pewforum.org/2011/12/19/global-christianity-regions/|title=\"Global Christianity: Regional Distribution of Christians\" |work=[[Pew Research Center]] |date=19 December 2011 |access-date=11 August 2013}}</ref> The number of permitted births in China varies between one and three children depending on geographic area.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://ilookchina.net/2010/11/05/exemptions-in-chinas-one-child-policy/ |title=Exemptions in China's 'one-child policy' |date=5 November 2010}}</ref> Chinese family planning policy allows minorities, including Muslims, to have up to two children in urban areas, and three to four children in rural areas.{{citation needed|date=August 2016}}\n\n===Europe===\n{{See also|Islam in Europe}}\nIslam is the [[Growth of religion|fastest-growing religion]] in Europe.<ref>{{cite book|last=Nachmani|first=Amikam|title=Europe and its Muslim minorities: aspects of conflict, attempts at accord|year=2010|publisher=Sussex Academic|location=Brighton|isbn=9781845194000|page=35}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Cherribi|first=Sam|title=In the house of war: Dutch Islam observed|year=2010|publisher=Oxford University Press|location=Oxford|isbn=9780199734115|page=33}}</ref> According to the [[Pew Research Center]], the Muslim population in Europe (excluding Turkey) was about 30 million in 1990, 44 million in 2010 and is expected to increase to 58 million by 2030; the Muslim share of the population increased from 4.1% in 1990 to 6% in 2010 and is expected to reach 8% in 2030.<ref name=\"Pew2011Muslim\" /> In recent years, \"Europe has experienced a record influx of asylum seekers fleeing from Syria and predominantly Muslim countries\" due to various conflicts in its country.<ref name=\"Pew2017\">{{cite report |url=https://www.pewforum.org/2017/11/29/europes-growing-muslim-population/ |title=Europe\u2019s Growing Muslim Population |date=29 November 2017 |publisher=[[Pew Research Center]] |access-date=11 November 2019}}</ref> And, the wave of Muslim migrants has caused debates about immigration and security policies and raised questions about the current and future number of Muslims in Europe.<ref name=\"Pew2017\" /> There were approximately 19 million Muslims in the [[European Union]] in 2010 or about (3.8%).<ref>{{cite report |url=http://www.pewforum.org/2011/01/27/future-of-the-global-muslim-population-regional-europe/ |title=The Future of the Global Muslim Population - Region: Europe |publisher=[[Pew Research Center]] |date=27 January 2011 |access-date=11 February 2020}}</ref> \nData for the rates of growth of [[Islam in Europe]] reveal that the growing number of Muslims is due primarily to immigration.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/4385768.stm |title=Muslims in Europe: Country guide |work=[[BBC News]] |date=2005-12-23 |accessdate=2010-04-01}}</ref> Additionally, average Muslims today are younger and have a higher fertility than other Europeans.<ref name=\"Pew2017\" /> Between the mid-2010 and mid-2016, migration was the biggest factor driving the growth of Muslim populations in Europe.<ref name=\"Pew20175facts\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.pewresearch.org/fact-tank/2017/11/29/5-facts-about-the-muslim-population-in-europe/ |title=5 facts about the Muslim population in Europe |work=[[Pew Research Center]] |date=29 November 2017 |access-date=11 November 2019}}</ref> Approximately, 2.5 million Muslims came to Europe for reasons other than employment and education.<ref name=\"Pew20175facts\" /> And, more than 1.3 million Muslims received and are expected to receive refugee status, allowing them to stay in Europe.<ref name=\"Pew20175facts\" />\n\nIn 2016, the median age of Muslims throughout Europe was 30.4, 13 years younger than the median age of other Europeans.<ref name=\"Pew20175facts\" /> 50% of all European Muslims are younger than 30, however, only 32% of non-Muslims in Europe were under the age of 30.<ref name=\"Pew20175facts\" /> While the birth rate for Muslims in Europe is expected to decline over the next two decades, it will remain slightly higher than in the non-Muslim population.<ref name=\"Pew2011Muslim\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.acbkenniscentrum.nl/public/Publicatie/48/download1/2011-03-18%20Turken%20in%20Nederland%20factsheet.pdf |title=Factsheet: Turken in Nederland |year=2011 |format=PDF |access-date=11 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131017021431/http://www.acbkenniscentrum.nl/public/Publicatie/48/download1/2011-03-18%20Turken%20in%20Nederland%20factsheet.pdf |archive-date=17 October 2013 |work=ACB Kenniscentrum |language=nl |page=2}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Sterke regionale verschillen in vruchtbaarheid naar herkomstgroepering |url=https://www.cbs.nl/nl-nl/achtergrond/2012/28/sterke-regionale-verschillen-in-vruchtbaarheid-naar-herkomstgroepering |language=nl |work=[[Statistics Netherlands]] |date=11 July 2012 |access-date=11 February 2020}}</ref> \n\nPew Research Center has provided three different projections (high, medium, zero migration) regarding the expected future migration levels.<ref name=\"Euronews1\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.euronews.com/2017/11/30/what-proportion-of-europe-s-population-is-muslim- |title=What proportion of Europe\u2019s population is Muslim? |last=Sandford |first=Alasdair |date=30 November 2017 |work=[[Euronews]] |language=en |access-date=11 November 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Pew20175facts\" /> Even in the zero migration scenario, the Muslim population is expected to rise from 3.8% to 4.9% by 2050.<ref name=\"Euronews1\" /> In medium and high migration scenario, it assumes the Muslims to reach 11.2% and 14% respectively.<ref name=\"Euronews1\" /> On the other hand, the non-Muslim population is expected to decrease in all three scenarios.<ref name=\"Euronews1\" /><ref name=\"Pew20175facts\" />\n\n==== France ====\nIn France there are an estimated 100,000 Muslim converts, compared with about 50,000 in 1986.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/02/04/world/europe/rise-of-islamic-converts-challenges-france.html |last=de la Baume |first=Ma\u00efa |work=[[The New York Times]] |title=More in France Are Turning to Islam, Challenging a Nation\u2019s Idea of Itself |date=3 February 2013}}</ref> The population mostly originate from Algeria, Morocco, and, France is home to a third of EU Muslims.<ref name=\"Brookings2008\">{{Cite paper |last=Va\u00efsse |first=Justin |date=8 September 2008 |title=Muslims in Europe: A short introduction |url=https://www.brookings.edu/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/09_europe_muslims_vaisse.pdf |format=PDF |publisher=[[Brookings Institution]]}}</ref> As of mid-2016, there are 5.7 million Muslims in France (8.8% of the population) and the Muslim population continues to grow.<ref name=\"Pew20175facts\" />\n\n==== Germany ====\nIn Germany, there are approximately 5 million Muslims (6.1% of the population), and at least 2.3 million trace their origin to Turkey.<ref name=\"Pew20175facts\" /><ref name=\"Brookings2008\" /> The \u201cguest worker program\u201d and the domination of Turkish religious authorities have increased German Islam.<ref name=\"Brookings2008\" /> A report from Pew found \"Germany as the top destination for Muslim migrants between 2010 and 2016\".<ref name=\"Euronews1\" />\n\n==== United Kingdom ====\nThe United Kingdom is home to 1.5 to 2 million Muslims (3% of the population) and has the highest number of Muslim migrants.<ref name=\"Euronews1\" /><ref name=\"Brookings2008\" /> Most originate from South Asia, particularly Pakistan.<ref name=\"Brookings2008\" />\n\n==== Italy ====\nThe presence of Muslims in Italy is fairly new. There are approximately 1 million Muslims (1.5% of the population) and most come from Morocco and Albania.<ref name=\"Brookings2008\" />\n\n==By denomination==\n\nThe following table lists historical growth rates (rounded) by schools and branches in Islam as published by the previous two editions of the ''[[World Christian Encyclopedia]]''.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|- valign=top\n! align left width=130px|Branches/Schools\n! align right width=130px|Growth rate (%) in 1982\n! align right width=130px|Growth rate (%) in 2001\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|'''[[Sunni]]'''<br />\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"| -\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"| -<br />\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[Hanafi]]\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"| 2.8\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"| 2.1\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[Shafi]]\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"| 2.9\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"| 2.2\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[Maliki]]\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"| 2.4\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"| 2.0\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[Hanbali]]\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"| 2.7\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"| 2.2\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"| '''[[Shia]]'''\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"| -\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"| -\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[Twelver]]\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"| 2.8\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"| 2.2\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[Isma'ilism|Isma'ili]]\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"| 3.4\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"| 2.7\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[Zaydi]]\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"| 2.8\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"| 2.3\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[Alawites]]\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"| 2.8\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"| 4.2\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"| '''[[Khariji]]'''\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"| 2.7\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"| 2.1\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"| '''[[Wahhabi]]'''\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"| -\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"| 1.4\n|}\n\n== Conversion ==\nIn its 2015 report, the [[Pew Research Center]] said that the \"bulging youth populations are among the reasons that Muslims are projected to grow faster than the world's overall population\".<ref name=\"pew2015all\" /> Only 0.3% (3,220,000 people) of the expected Muslim population growth (1,161,780,000) in the period of 2010\u20132050 would be due to conversions; 99.7% would be due to a high birth rate among Muslims.<ref name=\"Pew2011Muslim\" /><ref>{{cite book |author=Samuel P. Huntington |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LO4xG-bH1CQC&printsec=frontcover&dq=The+Clash+of+Civilizations+and+the+Remaking+of+World+Order&hl=en&sa=X&ei=J7ziUa2rGoLfrAH-y4CADA&ved=0CC8Q6AEwAA |title=The Clash of Civilizations and the Remaking of World Order |publisher=[[Simon & Schuster]] |year=2007 |pages=65\u201366}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author=Robinson, B. A. |title=Religions of the world: Numbers of adherents of major religions, their geographical distribution, date founded, and sacred texts |url=http://www.religioustolerance.org/worldrel.htm |work=ReligiousTolerance.org |access-date=5 May 2011}}</ref> Another [[Pew Research Center]] study in 2017 projected that only 0.3% (500,000 people) of the Muslim population growth in the period of 2010\u20132015 will be due to conversions, while 99.7% (152,000,000) will be due natural increase (births minus deaths).<ref name=\"Pew2017Change\">{{cite report |url=http://www.pewforum.org/2017/04/05/the-changing-global-religious-landscape/ |title=The Changing Global Religious Landscape |date=5 April 2017 |publisher=[[Pew Research Center]]}}</ref> According to ''The New York Times'', an estimated 25% of American Muslims are converts.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/04/30/nyregion/muslim-converts-face-discrimination.html |last=Elliott |first=Andrea |work=[[The New York Times]] |title=Muslim Converts Face Discrimination |date=30 April 2005 |accessdate=11 February 2020}}</ref> \nIn Britain, around 6,000 people convert to Islam per year and according to a June 2000 article in the British Muslims Monthly Survey the bulk of new Muslim converts in Britain were women.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://artsweb.bham.ac.uk/bmms/2000/06June00.asp#Women%20convert |title=British Muslims Monthly Survey for June 2000, Vol. VIII, No. 6 |at=Women convert}}</ref> According to ''[[The Huffington Post]]'', \"observers estimate that as many as 20,000 Americans convert to Islam annually.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/08/24/post-911-islam-converts_n_935572.html |last=Sacirbey |first=Omar |title=Conversion To Islam One Result Of Post-9/11 Curiosity |date=24 August 2011 |work=[[Huffington Post]]}}</ref>\n\nAccording to [[Pew Research]], the number of U.S. converts to Islam is roughly equal to the number of U.S. Muslims who leave the religion.<ref name=\"Pew2018conversion\">{{cite web |author1=Besheer Mohamed |author2=Elizabeth Pobrebarac Sciupac |title=The share of Americans who leave Islam is offset by those who become Muslim |url=http://www.pewresearch.org/fact-tank/2018/01/26/the-share-of-americans-who-leave-islam-is-offset-by-those-who-become-muslim/ |work=[[Pew Research Center]] |date=26 January 2018 |accessdate=11 February 2020}}</ref> 77% of new converts to Islam are from Christianity, whereas 19% were from [[irreligion|non-religion]]. Whereas, 55% of Muslims who left Islam went to non-religion, and 22% converted to Christianity.<ref name=\"Pew2018conversion\" />\n\nDarren E. Sherkat questioned in ''[[Foreign Affairs]]'' whether some of the Muslim growth projections are accurate as they do not take into account the increasing number of non-religious Muslims. Quantitative research is lacking, but he believes the European trend mirrors the American: data from the General Social Survey in the United States show that 22 percent of those raised Muslim no longer embrace Islam in adulthood, and 18 percent hold no religious identification.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.foreignaffairs.com/reviews/2015-06-22/losing-their-religion |title=Losing Their Religion: When Muslim Immigrants Leave Islam |date=22 June 2015 |work=[[Foreign Affairs]] |author=Darren E. Sherkat}}</ref>\n\nStudies estimate significantly more people have converted from Islam to Christianity in the 21st century than at any other point in Islamic history.<ref name=\"World Christian Encyclopedia p. 374\">{{cite book |date=February 15, 2001 |editor1=David B. Barrett |editor2=George Thomas Kurian |editor3=Todd M. Johnson |title=World Christian Encyclopedia p. 374|url= |location= |publisher=Oxford University Press USA |isbn=0195079639 }}</ref> A 2015 study found that up to 4.2 million Muslim [[converted to Christianity]].<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Johnstone|first1=Patrick|last2=Miller|first2=Duane Alexander|title=Believers in Christ from a Muslim Background: A Global Census|journal=Interdisciplinary Journal of Research on Religion|date=2015|volume=11|page=8|url=https://www.academia.edu/16338087|accessdate=30 October 2015}}</ref> The increasingly large ex-Muslim communities in the Western world that adhere to no religion have also been well documented.<ref>{{cite news|author=Andrew Anthony|year= 2015|title=Losing their religion: The hidden crisis of faith among Britain's young Muslims|work=The Guardian|url= https://www.theguardian.com/global/2015/may/17/losing-their-religion-british-ex-muslims-non-believers-hidden-crisis-faith}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Christian population growth]]\n* [[Fastest Growing Religion]]\n* [[Islam by country]]\n* [[Islamic Missionary Activity]]\n* [[List of converts to Islam]]\n* [[List of religious populations]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n[[Category:Sexuality in Islam]]\n[[Category:Religious demographics]]\n[[Category:Islam-related controversies]]\n", "text_old": "{{Expand Arabic|date=May 2019}}\n{{cleanup|reason=predictions of distant future statistics are unreliable; [[WP:NOTCRYSTAL]].|date=December 2019}}\n[[File:Islam percent population in each nation World Map Muslim data by Pew Research.svg|300px|thumb|World Muslim population by percentage ([[Pew Research Center]], 2014)]]\n'''Muslim population growth''' is the [[population growth]] of [[Muslim]]s worldwide. In 2010-2015, the expected Muslim growth rate was 1.8%.<ref name=\"pew2015all\">{{cite report |url=https://assets.pewresearch.org/wp-content/uploads/sites/11/2015/03/PF_15.04.02_ProjectionsFullReport.pdf |title=The Future of World Religions: Population Growth Projections, 2010-2050 |publisher=[[Pew Research Center]] |date=April 2, 2015}}</ref> This compares with average [[world population growth]] rate of 1.2% per year for the referenced period.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.worldometers.info/world-population/ |title=World Population (2020 and historical) |accessdate=12 February 2020}}</ref> As of 2015, it was predicted that the world's Muslim population would grow twice as fast as the overall global population in the following decades.<ref name=\"pew2015all\" /> Young median age and high fertility rate of Muslims relative to other religious groups are significant factors behind Islam's population growth;<ref name=\"Pew2011Muslim\" /><ref name=\"FastestGrowing\" /> As of 2015, the Muslim fertility rate for [[Muslim-majority countries|all 49 Muslim-majority countries]] is 2.9\u2014well above the global rate\u2014but down from 4.3 in 1990-1995.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2017/11/muslim-overpopulation-myth/545318/|title=The Muslim Overpopulation Myth That Just Won\u2019t Die|date=November 14, 2017|author=Krithika Varagur|publisher=[[The Atlantic]]|accessdate=April 21, 2020}}</ref> According to Pew Research, [[religious conversion]] has no net impact on the Muslim population as the number of people who [[Convert to Islam|convert to Islam]] is roughly similar to those who leave Islam.<ref name=\"Pew2011Muslim\">{{cite report |url=http://www.pewforum.org/2011/01/27/the-future-of-the-global-muslim-population/ |title=The Future of the Global Muslim Population |date=27 January 2011|publisher=[[Pew Research Center]]|access-date=27 December 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"FastestGrowing\">{{cite web |title=Why Muslims are the world's fastest-growing religious group |url=http://www.pewresearch.org/fact-tank/2015/04/23/why-muslims-are-the-worlds-fastest-growing-religious-group/ |publisher=[[Pew Research Center]] |date=23 April 2015 |accessdate=5 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SAzizViY30EC |title=The World's Religions in Figures: An Introduction to International Religious Demography |first1=Todd M. |last1=Johnson |first2=Brian J. |last2=Grim |date=25 March 2013 |publisher=[[John Wiley & Sons]] |isbn=9781118323038}}</ref>\n\n==By region==\n\n===World===\n{{See also|Islam by country}}\n* The six fastest-growing religions in the world are estimated to be [[Islam]] (1.84%), the [[Bah\u00e1'\u00ed Faith]] (1.70%), [[Sikhism]] (1.62%), [[Jainism]] (1.57%), [[Hinduism]] (1.52%), and [[Christianity]] (1.38%), with high birth rates being cited as the major reason.<ref>{{cite news |title=The List: The World\u2019s Fastest-Growing Religions |work=[[Foreign Policy]] |date=14 May 2007 |url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2007/05/14/the-list-the-worlds-fastest-growing-religions/ |accessdate=11 February 2020}}</ref>\n* On April 2, 2015, the [[Pew Research Center]] published a demographic study about \"The Future of World Religions: Population Growth Projections, 2010-2050\" with projections of the growth of Islam and reasons why \"Islam will grow faster than any other major religion.\"<ref name=\"pew2015all\" /> The study concluded that the global Muslim population is expected to grow at a faster rate than the non-Muslim population due primarily to the young age and high fertility rate of Muslims.<ref name=\"Pew2017Change\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/goatsandsoda/2015/12/25/460797744/a-religious-forecast-for-2050-atheism-is-down-islam-is-rising|title=A Religious Forecast For 2050: Atheism Is Down, Islam Is Rising |work=[[NPR]]}}</ref>\n\n:'''Projected global Muslim population (2010-2050):'''\n:# The number of Muslims world-wide is projected to increase from about 1.6 billion in 2010 to nearly 2.8 billion in 2050. Consequently, Muslims are projected to rise from 23% of the world\u2019s population in 2010 to 30% in 2050.\n:#Muslims are expected to grow twice as fast as the overall global population (the expected annual growth rate of Muslims is projected to be 0.6 p.p. above the rate for the world\u2019s population through 2050)\n:#If current trends continue, by 2050 the number of Muslims will nearly equal the number of Christians around the world.\n:# In Europe, Muslims will make up 10% of the overall population.\n:# India will retain a [[Hindu]] majority but also will have the largest Muslim population of any country in the world, surpassing [[Indonesia]].\n:# In the United States, Judaism will no longer be the largest non-Christian religion. Muslims will be more numerous in the U.S. than people who identify as Jewish on the basis of religion.\n\n:'''Reasons given for the projected growth'''\n:# The change in the world's religious is \"driven primarily by differences in fertility rates and the size of youth populations among the world's major religions, as well as by people switching faiths.\"\n:# ''Fertility rates''. The world's total population \"is expected to rise to 9.3 billion, a 35% increase\" between 2010 and 2050, However, \"over that same period, Muslims, who have a comparatively youthful population with high fertility rates, are projected to increase by 73%.\" Muslim growth benefits from the fertility factor because \"globally, Muslims have the highest fertility rate, an average of 3.1 children per woman.\" This is above a replacement level of 2.1 which is \"the minimum typically needed to maintain a stable population.\"\n:# ''Size of youth population''. \"In 2010, more than a quarter of the world's total population (27%) was under the age of 15. But a \"higher percentage of Muslims (34%) were younger than 15.\"\n:# ''Size of old population''. In 2010, \"11% of the world's population was at least 60 years old,\" but only 7% of Muslims were over 60.\n:# ''Switching''. Between 2010 and 2050 a gain of 3,220,000 Muslim adherents is projected to come through switching, mostly found in the [[Sub Saharan Africa]] (2.9 million). Also, the Muslim population are projected to add 1.3 million and lose 880,000 via switching, for a net gain of 420,000 between 2015 and 2020.\n:# ''Migration''. Migration  is the third reason for the Muslim population growth. For example, 1.8% of the projected growth in Europe is attributed to Muslims migrating in.\n\n===Asia===\n[[Islam]] is currently the largest religion in Asia. According to the [[Pew Research Center]], 27.3% of the people living in the Asia-Pacific region in 2030 will be Muslim, up from about a quarter in 2010 (24.8%) and 21.6% in 1990.<ref name=\"Pew2011Muslim\" />\n\n====India====\nIslam is the [[Growth of religion|fastest-growing religion]] in India.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.censusindia.gov.in/Census_Data_2001/India_at_glance/religion.aspx |title=Census of India |access-date=11 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071015225409/http://www.censusindia.gov.in/Census_Data_2001/India_at_glance/religion.aspx |publisher=[[Registrar General and Census Commissioner of India]] |archive-date=15 October 2007}}</ref> Growth rate of Muslims has been consistently higher than the growth rate of Hindus, ever since the census data of independent India has been available. For example, during the 1991-2001 decade, Muslim growth rate was 29.5% (vs 19.9% for Hindus). However, Muslims population growth rate declined to 24.6% during 2001-2011 decade, in keeping with the similar decline in most religious groups of India.<ref>{{cite news|title=Myth of Muslim growth|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/opinion/columns/myth-of-muslim-growth/|accessdate=5 June 2016|newspaper=[[The Indian Express]]|date=2 September 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/census-2011-data-on-population-by-religious-communities/article7579161.ece|title=Muslim population growth slows |work=[[The Hindu]] |language=en-IN |issn=0971-751X |date=25 August 2015 |access-date=21 August 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|title=The Myth Of The Muslim Population Bomb|url=http://www.tehelka.com/2015/02/the-myth-of-the-muslim-population-bomb/|accessdate=5 June 2016|magazine=[[Tehelka]]|date=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160604122248/http://www.tehelka.com/2015/02/the-myth-of-the-muslim-population-bomb/|archive-date=4 June 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Five charts that puncture the bogey of Muslim population growth|url=http://scroll.in/article/705283/five-charts-that-puncture-the-bogey-of-muslim-population-growth|publisher=[[Scroll.in]]|accessdate=6 June 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn India regarding attitudes \"toward [[birth control]],\" younger (ages 10\u201319) Muslim women are less likely to favor it than are older (ages 20\u201330). Regarding \"knowledge of  birth control,\" younger (ages 10\u201319) Muslim women know less than do older (ages 20\u201330).  \"Muslim marriages take place earlier\" than other religions, and younger (ages 10\u201319) Muslim women are more likely to want to have \"many children\" than are older (ages 20\u201330).<ref>{{cite book |last=Shakeel |first=Ahmad |title=Muslim Attitude Towards Family Planning |publisher=Sarup & Sons |year=2003 |url=https://books.google.com/books/about/Muslim_Attitude_Towards_Family_Planning.html?id=MFrDOXtYXfwC |pages=26, 33, 47, 51}}</ref>\n\nAccording to [[Paul Kurtz]], Muslims in India are much more resistant to modern contraceptive measures compared to other Indians and, as a consequence, the fertility rate among non-Muslim women is much lower compared to that of Muslim women.<ref>{{cite book |last=Guilmoto |first= Christophe |title=Fertility transition in South India |publisher=[[SAGE Publishing]] |year=2005 |isbn=9780761932925}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Kurtz |first=Paul |title=Multi-Secularism: A New Agenda |publisher=[[Transaction Publishers]] |isbn = 9781412814195 | year=2010}}</ref>\nIslam is the second-largest [[religion in India]], making up 14.2% of the country's population with about 172 million adherents ([[2011 Census of India|2011 census]]).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rediff.com/news/slide-show/slide-show-1-by-2030-muslims-will-make-up-16-pc-of-indias-population/20110128.htm |title=By 2030, Muslims will make up 16 pc of India's population |work=Rediff News |date=28 January 2011}}</ref> In 2010, India had the second largest population of Muslims, after Indonesia and ahead of Pakistan.<ref>{{cite report | url=http://www.pewforum.org/2012/12/18/global-religious-landscape-muslim/ | title=The Global Religious Landscape \u2013 Muslims | work=[[Pew Research Center]] | accessdate=29 July 2015 | date=18 December 2012}}</ref>\n\n====China====\nIn China, Muslim population growth has been estimated to be as much as 2.7% from 1964\u20131982, however the Pew Research Center projects a slowing down of Muslim population growth in China due partly to the fact that many [[Hui people|Hui Muslims]] voluntarily limit themselves to one child in China, a response to their Imams expressing the benefits of population control. <ref>{{cite report |url=http://www.pewforum.org/2011/01/27/future-of-the-global-muslim-population-regional-asia/ |title=The Future of the Global Muslim Population - Region: Asia-Pacific |publisher=[[Pew Research Center]] |date=27 January 2011 |access-date=11 February 2020}}</ref> By contrast, China's Christian population growth has been estimated at 4.7% based on total population figures from the year 1949. <ref>{{cite report |url=https://www.pewforum.org/2011/12/19/global-christianity-regions/|title=\"Global Christianity: Regional Distribution of Christians\" |work=[[Pew Research Center]] |date=19 December 2011 |access-date=11 August 2013}}</ref> The number of permitted births in China varies between one and three children depending on geographic area.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://ilookchina.net/2010/11/05/exemptions-in-chinas-one-child-policy/ |title=Exemptions in China's 'one-child policy' |date=5 November 2010}}</ref> Chinese family planning policy allows minorities, including Muslims, to have up to two children in urban areas, and three to four children in rural areas.{{citation needed|date=August 2016}}\n\n===Europe===\n{{See also|Islam in Europe}}\nIslam is the [[Growth of religion|fastest-growing religion]] in Europe.<ref>{{cite book|last=Nachmani|first=Amikam|title=Europe and its Muslim minorities: aspects of conflict, attempts at accord|year=2010|publisher=Sussex Academic|location=Brighton|isbn=9781845194000|page=35}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Cherribi|first=Sam|title=In the house of war: Dutch Islam observed|year=2010|publisher=Oxford University Press|location=Oxford|isbn=9780199734115|page=33}}</ref> According to the [[Pew Research Center]], the Muslim population in Europe (excluding Turkey) was about 30 million in 1990, 44 million in 2010 and is expected to increase to 58 million by 2030; the Muslim share of the population increased from 4.1% in 1990 to 6% in 2010 and is expected to reach 8% in 2030.<ref name=\"Pew2011Muslim\" /> In recent years, \"Europe has experienced a record influx of asylum seekers fleeing from Syria and predominantly Muslim countries\" due to various conflicts in its country.<ref name=\"Pew2017\">{{cite report |url=https://www.pewforum.org/2017/11/29/europes-growing-muslim-population/ |title=Europe\u2019s Growing Muslim Population |date=29 November 2017 |publisher=[[Pew Research Center]] |access-date=11 November 2019}}</ref> And, the wave of Muslim migrants has caused debates about immigration and security policies and raised questions about the current and future number of Muslims in Europe.<ref name=\"Pew2017\" /> There were approximately 19 million Muslims in the [[European Union]] in 2010 or about (3.8%).<ref>{{cite report |url=http://www.pewforum.org/2011/01/27/future-of-the-global-muslim-population-regional-europe/ |title=The Future of the Global Muslim Population - Region: Europe |publisher=[[Pew Research Center]] |date=27 January 2011 |access-date=11 February 2020}}</ref> \nData for the rates of growth of [[Islam in Europe]] reveal that the growing number of Muslims is due primarily to immigration.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/4385768.stm |title=Muslims in Europe: Country guide |work=[[BBC News]] |date=2005-12-23 |accessdate=2010-04-01}}</ref> Additionally, average Muslims today are younger and have a higher fertility than other Europeans.<ref name=\"Pew2017\" /> Between the mid-2010 and mid-2016, migration was the biggest factor driving the growth of Muslim populations in Europe.<ref name=\"Pew20175facts\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.pewresearch.org/fact-tank/2017/11/29/5-facts-about-the-muslim-population-in-europe/ |title=5 facts about the Muslim population in Europe |work=[[Pew Research Center]] |date=29 November 2017 |access-date=11 November 2019}}</ref> Approximately, 2.5 million Muslims came to Europe for reasons other than employment and education.<ref name=\"Pew20175facts\" /> And, more than 1.3 million Muslims received and are expected to receive refugee status, allowing them to stay in Europe.<ref name=\"Pew20175facts\" />\n\nIn 2016, the median age of Muslims throughout Europe was 30.4, 13 years younger than the median age of other Europeans.<ref name=\"Pew20175facts\" /> 50% of all European Muslims are younger than 30, however, only 32% of non-Muslims in Europe were under the age of 30.<ref name=\"Pew20175facts\" /> While the birth rate for Muslims in Europe is expected to decline over the next two decades, it will remain slightly higher than in the non-Muslim population.<ref name=\"Pew2011Muslim\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.acbkenniscentrum.nl/public/Publicatie/48/download1/2011-03-18%20Turken%20in%20Nederland%20factsheet.pdf |title=Factsheet: Turken in Nederland |year=2011 |format=PDF |access-date=11 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131017021431/http://www.acbkenniscentrum.nl/public/Publicatie/48/download1/2011-03-18%20Turken%20in%20Nederland%20factsheet.pdf |archive-date=17 October 2013 |work=ACB Kenniscentrum |language=nl |page=2}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Sterke regionale verschillen in vruchtbaarheid naar herkomstgroepering |url=https://www.cbs.nl/nl-nl/achtergrond/2012/28/sterke-regionale-verschillen-in-vruchtbaarheid-naar-herkomstgroepering |language=nl |work=[[Statistics Netherlands]] |date=11 July 2012 |access-date=11 February 2020}}</ref> \n\nPew Research Center has provided three different projections (high, medium, zero migration) regarding the expected future migration levels.<ref name=\"Euronews1\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.euronews.com/2017/11/30/what-proportion-of-europe-s-population-is-muslim- |title=What proportion of Europe\u2019s population is Muslim? |last=Sandford |first=Alasdair |date=30 November 2017 |work=[[Euronews]] |language=en |access-date=11 November 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Pew20175facts\" /> Even in the zero migration scenario, the Muslim population is expected to rise from 3.8% to 4.9% by 2050.<ref name=\"Euronews1\" /> In medium and high migration scenario, it assumes the Muslims to reach 11.2% and 14% respectively.<ref name=\"Euronews1\" /> On the other hand, the non-Muslim population is expected to decrease in all three scenarios.<ref name=\"Euronews1\" /><ref name=\"Pew20175facts\" />\n\n==== France ====\nIn France there are an estimated 100,000 Muslim converts, compared with about 50,000 in 1986.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/02/04/world/europe/rise-of-islamic-converts-challenges-france.html |last=de la Baume |first=Ma\u00efa |work=[[The New York Times]] |title=More in France Are Turning to Islam, Challenging a Nation\u2019s Idea of Itself |date=3 February 2013}}</ref> The population mostly originate from Algeria, Morocco, and, France is home to a third of EU Muslims.<ref name=\"Brookings2008\">{{Cite paper |last=Va\u00efsse |first=Justin |date=8 September 2008 |title=Muslims in Europe: A short introduction |url=https://www.brookings.edu/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/09_europe_muslims_vaisse.pdf |format=PDF |publisher=[[Brookings Institution]]}}</ref> As of mid-2016, there are 5.7 million Muslims in France (8.8% of the population) and the Muslim population continues to grow.<ref name=\"Pew20175facts\" />\n\n==== Germany ====\nIn Germany, there are approximately 5 million Muslims (6.1% of the population), and at least 2.3 million trace their origin to Turkey.<ref name=\"Pew20175facts\" /><ref name=\"Brookings2008\" /> The \u201cguest worker program\u201d and the domination of Turkish religious authorities have increased German Islam.<ref name=\"Brookings2008\" /> A report from Pew found \"Germany as the top destination for Muslim migrants between 2010 and 2016\".<ref name=\"Euronews1\" />\n\n==== United Kingdom ====\nThe United Kingdom is home to 1.5 to 2 million Muslims (3% of the population) and has the highest number of Muslim migrants.<ref name=\"Euronews1\" /><ref name=\"Brookings2008\" /> Most originate from South Asia, particularly Pakistan.<ref name=\"Brookings2008\" />\n\n==== Italy ====\nThe presence of Muslims in Italy is fairly new. There are approximately 1 million Muslims (1.5% of the population) and most come from Morocco and Albania.<ref name=\"Brookings2008\" />\n\n==By denomination==\n\nThe following table lists historical growth rates (rounded) by schools and branches in Islam as published by the previous two editions of the ''[[World Christian Encyclopedia]]''.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|- valign=top\n! align left width=130px|Branches/Schools\n! align right width=130px|Growth rate (%) in 1982\n! align right width=130px|Growth rate (%) in 2001\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|'''[[Sunni]]'''<br />\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"| -\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"| -<br />\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[Hanafi]]\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"| 2.8\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"| 2.1\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[Shafi]]\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"| 2.9\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"| 2.2\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[Maliki]]\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"| 2.4\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"| 2.0\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[Hanbali]]\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"| 2.7\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"| 2.2\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"| '''[[Shia]]'''\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"| -\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"| -\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[Twelver]]\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"| 2.8\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"| 2.2\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[Isma'ilism|Isma'ili]]\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"| 3.4\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"| 2.7\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[Zaydi]]\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"| 2.8\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"| 2.3\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[Alawites]]\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"| 2.8\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"| 4.2\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"| '''[[Khariji]]'''\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"| 2.7\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"| 2.1\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"| '''[[Wahhabi]]'''\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"| -\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"| 1.4\n|}\n\n== Conversion ==\nIn its 2015 report, the [[Pew Research Center]] said that the \"bulging youth populations are among the reasons that Muslims are projected to grow faster than the world's overall population\".<ref name=\"pew2015all\" /> Only 0.3% (3,220,000 people) of the expected Muslim population growth (1,161,780,000) in the period of 2010\u20132050 would be due to conversions; 99.7% would be due to a high birth rate among Muslims.<ref name=\"Pew2011Muslim\" /><ref>{{cite book |author=Samuel P. Huntington |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LO4xG-bH1CQC&printsec=frontcover&dq=The+Clash+of+Civilizations+and+the+Remaking+of+World+Order&hl=en&sa=X&ei=J7ziUa2rGoLfrAH-y4CADA&ved=0CC8Q6AEwAA |title=The Clash of Civilizations and the Remaking of World Order |publisher=[[Simon & Schuster]] |year=2007 |pages=65\u201366}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author=Robinson, B. A. |title=Religions of the world: Numbers of adherents of major religions, their geographical distribution, date founded, and sacred texts |url=http://www.religioustolerance.org/worldrel.htm |work=ReligiousTolerance.org |access-date=5 May 2011}}</ref> Another [[Pew Research Center]] study in 2017 projected that only 0.3% (500,000 people) of the Muslim population growth in the period of 2010\u20132015 will be due to conversions, while 99.7% (152,000,000) will be due natural increase (births minus deaths).<ref name=\"Pew2017Change\">{{cite report |url=http://www.pewforum.org/2017/04/05/the-changing-global-religious-landscape/ |title=The Changing Global Religious Landscape |date=5 April 2017 |publisher=[[Pew Research Center]]}}</ref> According to ''The New York Times'', an estimated 25% of American Muslims are converts.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/04/30/nyregion/muslim-converts-face-discrimination.html |last=Elliott |first=Andrea |work=[[The New York Times]] |title=Muslim Converts Face Discrimination |date=30 April 2005 |accessdate=11 February 2020}}</ref> \nIn Britain, around 6,000 people convert to Islam per year and according to a June 2000 article in the British Muslims Monthly Survey the bulk of new Muslim converts in Britain were women.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://artsweb.bham.ac.uk/bmms/2000/06June00.asp#Women%20convert |title=British Muslims Monthly Survey for June 2000, Vol. VIII, No. 6 |at=Women convert}}</ref> According to ''[[The Huffington Post]]'', \"observers estimate that as many as 20,000 Americans convert to Islam annually.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/08/24/post-911-islam-converts_n_935572.html |last=Sacirbey |first=Omar |title=Conversion To Islam One Result Of Post-9/11 Curiosity |date=24 August 2011 |work=[[Huffington Post]]}}</ref>\n\nAccording to [[Pew Research]], the number of U.S. converts to Islam is roughly equal to the number of U.S. Muslims who leave the religion.<ref name=\"Pew2018conversion\">{{cite web |author1=Besheer Mohamed |author2=Elizabeth Pobrebarac Sciupac |title=The share of Americans who leave Islam is offset by those who become Muslim |url=http://www.pewresearch.org/fact-tank/2018/01/26/the-share-of-americans-who-leave-islam-is-offset-by-those-who-become-muslim/ |work=[[Pew Research Center]] |date=26 January 2018 |accessdate=11 February 2020}}</ref> 77% of new converts to Islam are from Christianity, whereas 19% were from [[irreligion|non-religion]]. Whereas, 55% of Muslims who left Islam went to non-religion, and 22% converted to Christianity.<ref name=\"Pew2018conversion\" />\n\nDarren E. Sherkat questioned in ''[[Foreign Affairs]]'' whether some of the Muslim growth projections are accurate as they do not take into account the increasing number of non-religious Muslims. Quantitative research is lacking, but he believes the European trend mirrors the American: data from the General Social Survey in the United States show that 22 percent of those raised Muslim no longer embrace Islam in adulthood, and 18 percent hold no religious identification.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.foreignaffairs.com/reviews/2015-06-22/losing-their-religion |title=Losing Their Religion: When Muslim Immigrants Leave Islam |date=22 June 2015 |work=[[Foreign Affairs]] |author=Darren E. Sherkat}}</ref>\n\nStudies estimate significantly more people have converted from Islam to Christianity in the 21st century than at any other point in Islamic history.<ref name=\"World Christian Encyclopedia p. 374\">{{cite book |date=February 15, 2001 |editor1=David B. Barrett |editor2=George Thomas Kurian |editor3=Todd M. Johnson |title=World Christian Encyclopedia p. 374|url= |location= |publisher=Oxford University Press USA |isbn=0195079639 }}</ref> A 2015 study found that up to 4.2 million Muslim [[converted to Christianity]].<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Johnstone|first1=Patrick|last2=Miller|first2=Duane Alexander|title=Believers in Christ from a Muslim Background: A Global Census|journal=Interdisciplinary Journal of Research on Religion|date=2015|volume=11|page=8|url=https://www.academia.edu/16338087|accessdate=30 October 2015}}</ref> The increasingly large ex-Muslim communities in the Western world that adhere to no religion have also been well documented.<ref>{{cite news|author=Andrew Anthony|year= 2015|title=Losing their religion: The hidden crisis of faith among Britain's young Muslims|work=The Guardian|url= https://www.theguardian.com/global/2015/may/17/losing-their-religion-british-ex-muslims-non-believers-hidden-crisis-faith}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Christian population growth]]\n* [[Fastest Growing Religion]]\n* [[Islam by country]]\n* [[Islamic Missionary Activity]]\n* [[List of converts to Islam]]\n* [[List of religious populations]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n[[Category:Sexuality in Islam]]\n[[Category:Religious demographics]]\n[[Category:Islam-related controversies]]\n", "name_user": "J.S. Clingman", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Muslim_population_growth"}
{"title_page": "Balyasakhi", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2015}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=November 2015}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Balyasakhi\n| image          =Balyasakhi.jpg\n| image_size     =\n| caption        =\n| director       = Antony Mitradas\n| producer       = [[P. Subramaniam]]\n| writer         = K. P. Kottarakkara\n| screenplay     = K. P. Kottarakkara\n| music          = Br. Lakshmanan\n| released       = {{Film date|1954|03|19|df=y}}\n| cinematography = N. S. Mani\n| editing        = K. D. George\n| studio         = Neela\n| lyrics         =\n| distributor    =\n| starring       = [[Prem Nazir]]<br> [[Miss Kumari]]\n| country        = [[India]]\n| language       = [[Malayalam Language|Malayalam]]\n}}\n\n'''''Balyasakhi''''' is a 1954 [[Cinema of India|Indian]] [[Malayalam language|Malayalam]] film, directed by Antony Mitradas and produced by P. Subramaniam.<ref>http://www.malayalachalachithram.com/movie.php?i=43</ref> The film stars [[Prem Nazir]] and [[Miss Kumari]] in the lead roles.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.malayalamcinema.com/gallery_balyasakhi.htm |title=Archived copy |access-date=20 September 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141208100051/http://www.malayalamcinema.com/gallery_balyasakhi.htm |archive-date=8 December 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The film had musical score by Br. Lakshmanan.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.metromatinee.com/MovieStills/Balyasakhi-1737-1 |title=Archived copy |access-date=20 September 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141112024256/http://www.metromatinee.com/MovieStills/Balyasakhi-1737-1 |archive-date=12 November 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Cast==\n* Prem Nazir as Vijayan\n* Kumari Thankam\n* [[S. P. Pillai]]\n* Miss Kumari \n* Vanchiyoor Madhavan Nair\n* Jose Prakash\n* Sebastian Kunjukunju Bhagavathar\n* T. S. Muthaiah\n* Adoor Pankajam\n* Aranmula Ponnamma\n* [[Baby Indira]]\n* Bahadoor\n* Master Hari\n* Veeran\n* Snehalatha\n* Saraswathi\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|0214523}}\n\n[[Category:1954 films]]\n[[Category:Indian films]]\n[[Category:1950s Malayalam-language films]]\n\n\n{{1950s-Malayalam-film-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2015}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=November 2015}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Balyasakhi\n| image          =Balyasakhi.jpg\n| image_size     =\n| caption        =\n| director       = Antony Mitradas\n| producer       = P. Subramaniam\n| writer         = K. P. Kottarakkara\n| screenplay     = K. P. Kottarakkara\n| music          = Br. Lakshmanan\n| released       = {{Film date|1954|03|19|df=y}}\n| cinematography = N. S. Mani\n| editing        = K. D. George\n| studio         = Neela\n| lyrics         =\n| distributor    =\n| starring       = [[Prem Nazir]]<br> [[Miss Kumari]]\n| country        = [[India]]\n| language       = [[Malayalam Language|Malayalam]]\n}}\n\n'''''Balyasakhi''''' is a 1954 [[Cinema of India|Indian]] [[Malayalam language|Malayalam]] film, directed by Antony Mitradas and produced by P. Subramaniam.<ref>http://www.malayalachalachithram.com/movie.php?i=43</ref> The film stars [[Prem Nazir]] and [[Miss Kumari]] in the lead roles.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.malayalamcinema.com/gallery_balyasakhi.htm |title=Archived copy |access-date=20 September 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141208100051/http://www.malayalamcinema.com/gallery_balyasakhi.htm |archive-date=8 December 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The film had musical score by Br. Lakshmanan.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.metromatinee.com/MovieStills/Balyasakhi-1737-1 |title=Archived copy |access-date=20 September 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141112024256/http://www.metromatinee.com/MovieStills/Balyasakhi-1737-1 |archive-date=12 November 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Cast==\n* Prem Nazir as Vijayan\n* Kumari Thankam\n* [[S. P. Pillai]]\n* Miss Kumari \n* Vanchiyoor Madhavan Nair\n* Jose Prakash\n* 